A01.1.00.001.name: Head
A01.1.00.001.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.002.name: Forehead
A01.1.00.002.definition: the part of the face above the eyes —called also brow, frons (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.003.name: Occiput
A01.1.00.003.definition: the back part of the head or skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.004.name: Temple
A01.1.00.004.definition: the flattened space on each side of the forehead of some mammals (as humans) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.005.name: Ear
A01.1.00.005.definition: the characteristic vertebrate organ of hearing and equilibrium consisting in the typical mammal of a sound-collecting outer ear separated by the tympanic membrane from a sound-transmitting middle ear that in turn is separated from a sensory inner ear by membranous fenestrae (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.006.name: Face
A01.1.00.006.definition: the front part of the human head including the chin, mouth, nose, cheeks, eyes, and usually the forehead (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.007.name: Eye
A01.1.00.007.definition: an organ of sight; especially : a nearly spherical hollow organ that is lined with a sensitive retina, is lodged in a bony orbit in the skull, is the vertebrate organ of sight, and is normally paired (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.008.name: Cheek
A01.1.00.008.definition: the fleshy side of the face below the eye and above and to the side of the mouth; broadly : the lateral aspect of the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.009.name: Nose
A01.1.00.009.definition: the part of the face that bears the nostrils and covers the anterior part of the nasal cavity; broadly : this part together with the nasal cavity  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.010.name: Mouth
A01.1.00.010.definition: the natural opening through which food passes into the animal body and which in vertebrates is typically bounded externally by the lips and internally by the pharynx and encloses the tongue, gums, and teeth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.011.name: Chin
A01.1.00.011.definition: the lower portion of the face lying below the lower lip and including the prominence of the lower jaw —called also mentum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.012.name: Neck
A01.1.00.012.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.013.name: Trunk
A01.1.00.013.definition: the human body apart from the head and appendages : torso (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.014.name: Thorax
A01.1.00.014.definition: the part of the mammalian body that is situated between the neck and the abdomen and supported by the ribs, costal cartilages, and sternum; also : thoracic cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.016.name: Abdomen
A01.1.00.016.definition: the part of the body between the thorax and the pelvis with the exception of the back —called also belly  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.017.name: Pelvis
A01.1.00.017.definition: a basin-shaped structure in the skeleton of many vertebrates that is formed by the pelvic girdle together with the sacrum and often various coccygeal and caudal vertebrae and that in humans is composed of the two hip bones bounding it on each side and in front while the sacrum and coccyx complete it behind  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.018.name: Back
A01.1.00.018.definition: the rear part of the human body especially from the neck to the end of the spine  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.021.name: Axilla
A01.1.00.021.definition: the cavity beneath the junction of the arm or anterior appendage and shoulder or shoulder girdle containing the axillary artery and vein, a part of the brachial plexus of nerves, many lymph nodes, and fat and areolar tissue; especially : armpit (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.023.name: Elbow
A01.1.00.023.definition: the joint between the human forearm and the upper arm that supports the outer curve of the arm when bent —called also elbow joint  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.024.name: Forearm
A01.1.00.024.definition: the part of the arm between the elbow and the wrist; also : the corresponding part in other vertebrates (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.025.name: Hand
A01.1.00.025.definition: the terminal part of the vertebrate forelimb when modified (as in humans) as a grasping organ  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.026.name: Wrist
A01.1.00.026.definition: the joint or the region of the joint between the human hand and the arm or a corresponding part on a lower animal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.027.name: Metacarpus
A01.1.00.027.definition: the part of the human hand or the front foot in quadrupeds between the carpus and the phalanges that contains five more or less elongated bones when all the digits are present (as in humans) but is modified in many animals by the loss or reduction of some bones or the fusing of adjacent bones (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.028.name: Palm
A01.1.00.028.definition: the somewhat concave part of the human hand between the bases of the fingers and the wrist or the corresponding part of the forefoot of a lower mammal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.032.name: Pelvic girdle
A01.1.00.032.definition: a bony or cartilaginous arch that supports the hind limbs of a vertebrate, that corresponds to the shoulder girdle of the forelimbs but is usually more rigid and firmly attached to the spinal column, and that consists in lower forms of a single cartilage which is replaced in higher forms including humans by paired hip bones articulating solidly with the sacrum dorsally and with one another at the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.033.name: Buttocks
A01.1.00.033.definition: the back of a hip that forms one of the fleshy parts on which a person sits  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.034.name: Hip
A01.1.00.034.definition: the laterally projecting region of each side of the lower or posterior part of the mammalian trunk formed by the lateral parts of the pelvis and upper part of the femur together with the fleshy parts covering them  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.035.name: Thigh
A01.1.00.035.definition: the proximal segment of the vertebrate hind or lower limb extending from the hip to the knee and supported by a single large bone  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.036.name: Knee
A01.1.00.036.definition: a joint in the middle part of the human leg that is the articulation between the femur, tibia, and patella —called also knee joint  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.038.name: Leg
A01.1.00.038.definition: a limb of an animal used especially for supporting the body and for walking: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.039.name: Calf
A01.1.00.039.definition: the fleshy back part of the leg below the knee (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.040.name: Foot
A01.1.00.040.definition: the terminal part of the vertebrate leg upon which an individual stands  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.041.name: Ankle
A01.1.00.041.definition: the joint between the foot and the leg that constitutes in humans a ginglymus joint between the tibia and fibula above and the talus below —called also ankle joint  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.042.name: Heel
A01.1.00.042.definition: the back of the human foot below the ankle and behind the arch  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.043.name: Metatarsus
A01.1.00.043.definition: the part of the human foot or of the hind foot in quadrupeds that is between the tarsus and phalanges, contains when all the digits are present (as in humans) five more or less elongated bones but is modified in many animals with loss or reduction of some bones or fusing of others, and in humans forms the instep (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.044.name: Sole
A01.1.00.044.definition: the undersurface of a foot  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.046.name: Toes
A01.1.00.046.definition: one of the terminal members of a vertebrate's foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.047.name: Cavities
A01.1.00.047.definition: an unfilled space within a mass  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.049.name: Thoracic cavity
A01.1.00.049.definition: the division of the body cavity that lies above the diaphragm, is bounded peripherally by the wall of the chest, and contains the heart and lungs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.1.00.052.name: Pelvic cavity
A01.1.00.052.definition: the cavity of the pelvis comprising in humans a broad upper and a more contracted lower part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.00.015.name: Midclavicular line
A01.2.00.015.definition: an imaginary line parallel to the long axis of the body and passing through the midpoint of the clavicle on the ventral surface of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.00.018.name: Midaxillary line
A01.2.00.018.definition: an imaginary line through the axilla parallel to the long axis of the body and midway between its ventral and dorsal surfaces (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.02.004.name: Carotid triangle
A01.2.02.004.definition: a space in each lateral half of the neck that is bounded in back by the sternocleidomastoid muscle, below by the omohyoid muscle, and above by the stylohyoid and digastric muscles —called also superior carotid triangle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.04.001.name: Abdominal regions
A01.2.04.001.definition: any of the nine areas into which the abdomen is divided by four imaginary planes of which two are vertical passing through the middle of the inguinal ligament on each side and two are horizontal passing respectively through the junction of the ninth rib and costal cartilage and through the top of the iliac crest (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.04.002.name: Hypochondrium
A01.2.04.002.definition: either hypochondriac region of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.04.004.name: Flank
A01.2.04.004.definition: the fleshy part of the side between the ribs and the hip; broadly : the side of a quadruped (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.04.006.name: Groin
A01.2.04.006.definition: the fold or depression marking the juncture of the lower abdomen and the inner part of the thigh; also : the region of this line (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.07.022.name: Palm
A01.2.07.022.definition: the somewhat concave part of the human hand between the bases of the fingers and the wrist or the corresponding part of the forefoot of a lower mammal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.07.023.name: Thenar eminence
A01.2.07.023.definition: the ball of the thumb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.07.024.name: Hypothenar eminence
A01.2.07.024.definition: the prominent part of the palm of the hand above the base of the little finger (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.08.008.name: Femoral triangle
A01.2.08.008.definition: an area in the upper anterior part of the thigh bounded by the inguinal ligament, the sartorius, and the adductor longus —called also femoral trigone, Scarpa's triangle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A01.2.08.025.name: Sole
A01.2.08.025.definition: the undersurface of a foot  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.000.name: Bones
A02.0.00.000.definition: one of the hard parts of the skeleton of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.007.name: Periosteum
A02.0.00.007.definition: the membrane of connective tissue that closely invests all bones except at the articular surfaces (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.008.name: Perichondrium
A02.0.00.008.definition: the membrane of fibrous connective tissue that invests cartilage except at joints (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.009.name: Axial skeleton
A02.0.00.009.definition: the skeleton of the trunk and head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.011.name: Long bone
A02.0.00.011.definition: any of the elongated bones supporting a vertebrate limb and consisting of an essentially cylindrical shaft that contains bone marrow and ends in enlarged heads for articulation with other bones (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.012.name: Short bone
A02.0.00.012.definition: a bone (as of the tarsus or carpus) that is of approximately equal length in all dimensions (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.013.name: Flat bone
A02.0.00.013.definition: any of various bones (as of the skull, the jaw, the pelvis, or the rib cage) not rounded in cross section (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.017.name: Diaphysis
A02.0.00.017.definition: the shaft of a long bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.018.name: Epiphysis
A02.0.00.018.definition: a part or process of a bone that ossifies separately and later becomes ankylosed to the main part of the bone; especially : the usually rounded end of the shaft of a long bone that is composed mainly of cancellous bone covered by a thin layer of compact bone  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.022.name: Metaphysis
A02.0.00.022.definition: the transitional zone at which the diaphysis and epiphysis of a bone come together (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.023.name: Apophysis
A02.0.00.023.definition: an expanded or projecting part especially of an organism (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.025.name: Tubercle
A02.0.00.025.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.026.name: Tuberosity
A02.0.00.026.definition: a rounded prominence; especially : a large prominence on a bone usually serving for the attachment of muscles or ligaments (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.027.name: Eminence
A02.0.00.027.definition: a protuberance or projection on a bodily part and especially a bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.028.name: Process
A02.0.00.028.definition: a natural progressively continuing operation or development marked by a series of gradual changes that succeed one another in a relatively fixed way and lead toward a particular result or end  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.029.name: Condyle
A02.0.00.029.definition: an articular prominence of a bone —used chiefly of such as occur in pairs resembling a pair of knuckles (as those of the occipital bone for articulation with the atlas, those at the distal end of the humerus and femur, and those of the lower jaw) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.030.name: Epicondyle
A02.0.00.030.definition: any of several prominences on the distal part of a long bone serving for the attachment of muscles and ligaments:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.031.name: Crest
A02.0.00.031.definition: a showy tuft or process on the head of an animal and especially a bird  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.032.name: Line
A02.0.00.032.definition: something (as a ridge, seam, mark, or streak) that is distinct, elongated, and narrow  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.033.name: Notch
A02.0.00.033.definition: a V-shaped indentation (as on a bone) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.034.name: Fossa
A02.0.00.034.definition: an anatomical pit, groove, or depression (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.035.name: Groove
A02.0.00.035.definition: a long narrow depression occurring naturally on the surface of an organism or an anatomical part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.038.name: Endosteum
A02.0.00.038.definition: the layer of vascular connective tissue lining the medullary cavities of bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.044.name: Primary
A02.0.00.044.definition: first in order of time or development  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.0.00.045.name: Secondary
A02.0.00.045.definition: not first in order of occurrence or development: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.007.name: Neurocranium
A02.1.00.007.definition: the portion of the skull that encloses and protects the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.009.name: Chondrocranium
A02.1.00.009.definition: the embryonic cartilaginous cranium; also : the part of the adult skull derived therefrom (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.010.name: Desmocranium
A02.1.00.010.definition: the earliest mesenchymal precursor of the chondrocranium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.011.name: Pericranium
A02.1.00.011.definition: the external periosteum of the skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.013.name: Forehead
A02.1.00.013.definition: the part of the face above the eyes —called also brow, frons (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.014.name: Occiput
A02.1.00.014.definition: the back part of the head or skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.015.name: Nasion
A02.1.00.015.definition: the middle point of the nasofrontal suture (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.016.name: Bregma
A02.1.00.016.definition: the point of junction of the coronal and sagittal sutures of the skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.017.name: Lambda
A02.1.00.017.definition: the point of junction of the sagittal and lambdoid sutures of the skull  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.019.name: Pterion
A02.1.00.019.definition: the point on each side of the skull where the parietal and temporal bones meet the greater wing of the sphenoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.020.name: Asterion
A02.1.00.020.definition: the point behind the ear where the parietal, temporal, and occipital bones meet (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.021.name: Gonion
A02.1.00.021.definition: the point on each lower human jaw closest to the vertex of the gonial angle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.022.name: Temporal fossa
A02.1.00.022.definition: a broad fossa on the side of the skull of higher vertebrates behind the orbit that contains muscles for raising the lower jaw and that in humans is occupied by the temporalis muscle, is separated from the orbit by the zygomatic bone, is bounded laterally by the zygomatic arch, and lies above the infratemporal crest of the greater wing of the sphenoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.023.name: Zygomatic arch
A02.1.00.023.definition: the arch of bone that extends along the front or side of the skull beneath the orbit and that is formed by the union of the temporal process of the zygomatic bone in front with the zygomatic process of the temporal bone behind (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.024.name: Infratemporal fossa
A02.1.00.024.definition: a fossa that is bounded above by the plane of the zygomatic arch, laterally by the ramus of the mandible, and medially by the pterygoid plate, and that contains the masseter and pterygoid muscles and the mandibular nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.025.name: Pterygopalatine fossa
A02.1.00.025.definition: a small triangular space beneath the apex of the orbit that is bounded above by the sphenoid bone and the orbital process of the palatine bone, in front by the maxilla, medially by the palatine bone, and behind by the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone and that contains among other structures the pterygopalatine ganglion —called also pterygomaxillary fossa, sphenomaxillary fossa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.026.name: Pterygomaxillary fissure
A02.1.00.026.definition: a vertical gap between the lateral pterygoid plate of the pterygoid process and the maxilla that descends at right angles to the medial end of the inferior orbital fissure and gives passage to part of the maxillary artery and vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.027.name: Fontanelles
A02.1.00.027.definition: a membrane-covered opening in bone or between bones; specifically : any of the spaces closed by membranous structures between the uncompleted angles of the parietal bones and the neighboring bones of a fetal or young skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.028.name: Anterior fontanelle
A02.1.00.028.definition: the fontanel occurring at the meeting point of the coronal and sagittal sutures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.033.name: Vertex
A02.1.00.033.definition: the top of the head  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.035.name: Diploe
A02.1.00.035.definition: cancellous bony tissue between the external and internal layers of the skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Cara interna de la base del cráneo

A02.1.00.051.name: Clivus
A02.1.00.051.definition: the smooth sloping surface on the upper posterior part of the body of the sphenoid bone supporting the pons and the basilar artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Cara externa de la base del cráneo

A02.1.00.054.name: Jugular foramen
A02.1.00.054.definition: a large irregular opening from the posterior cranial fossa that is bounded anteriorly by the petrous part of the temporal bone and posteriorly by the jugular notch of the occipital bone and that transmits the inferior petrosal sinus, the glossopharyngeal, vagus, and accessory nerves, and the internal jugular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.055.name: Foramen lacerum
A02.1.00.055.definition: an irregular aperture on the lower surface of the skull bounded by parts of the temporal, sphenoid, and occipital bones that is filled with fibrocartilage, gives passage to several vessels (as emissary veins), and has the internal carotid artery running above its upper surface after exiting the carotid canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.058.name: Greater palatine foramen
A02.1.00.058.definition: a foramen in each posterior side of the palate giving passage to the greater palatine artery and to a palatine nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.060.name: Incisive fossa
A02.1.00.060.definition: a depression on the front of the maxillary bone above the incisor teeth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.067.name: Orbit
A02.1.00.067.definition: the bony cavity perforated for the passage of nerves and blood vessels that occupies the lateral front of the skull immediately beneath the frontal bone on each side and encloses and protects the eye and its appendages —called also eye socket, orbital cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.075.name: Roof
A02.1.00.075.definition: the vaulted upper boundary of the mouth supported largely by the palatine bones and limited anteriorly by the dental lamina and posteriorly by the uvula and upper part of the fauces  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.076.name: Floor
A02.1.00.076.definition: the lower inside surface of a hollow anatomical structure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.088.name: Piriform aperture
A02.1.00.088.definition: the anterior opening of the nasal cavities in the skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.094.name: Spheno-ethmoidal recess
A02.1.00.094.definition: a small space between the sphenoid bone and the superior nasal concha into which the sphenoid sinus opens (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.096.name: Choana
A02.1.00.096.definition: either of the pair of posterior apertures of the nasal cavity that open into the nasopharynx —called also posterior naris (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.00.097.name: Sphenopalatine foramen
A02.1.00.097.definition: a foramen between the sphenoidal and orbital parts of the vertical plate of the palatine bone; also : a deep notch between these parts that by articulation with the sphenoid bone is converted into a foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.02.001.name: Parietal bone
A02.1.02.001.definition: either of a pair of membrane bones of the roof of the skull between the frontal and occipital bones that are large and quadrilateral in outline, meet in the sagittal suture, and form much of the top and sides of the cranium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Surco de la arteria meníngea media

A02.1.03.001.name: Frontal bone
A02.1.03.001.definition: a bone that forms the forehead and roofs over most of the orbits and nasal cavity and that at birth consists of two halves separated by a suture; also : either of the two halves especially in a vertebrate in which they do not unite to form a single bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.006.name: Glabella
A02.1.03.006.definition: the smooth prominence between the eyebrows —called also mesophryon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.013.name: Temporal line
A02.1.03.013.definition: either of two nearly parallel ridges or lines on each side of the skull that begin as a single ridge on the temporal bone, run upward and backward from the zygomatic process above the temporal fossa, divide into upper and lower lines, and continue on the parietal bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.014.name: Zygomatic process
A02.1.03.014.definition: any of several bony processes that articulate with the zygomatic bone: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.016.name: Frontal crest
A02.1.03.016.definition: a median ridge on the internal surface of the vertical part of the human frontal bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.017.name: Groove for the superior sagittal sinus

term_localized.en: Groove for the superior sagittal sinus

A02.1.03.020.name: Nasal spine
A02.1.03.020.definition: any of several median bony processes adjacent to the nasal passages: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.025.name: Trochlear fovea
A02.1.03.025.definition: a depression that is located in the anteromedial aspect of the orbital surface of each bony plate of the frontal bone making up the superior part of one of the orbits and that forms a point of attachment for the corresponding superior oblique muscle of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.03.029.name: Frontal sinus
A02.1.03.029.definition: either of two air spaces lined with mucous membrane each of which lies within the frontal bone above one of the orbits (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.001.name: Occipital bone
A02.1.04.001.definition: a compound bone that forms the posterior part of the skull and surrounds the foramen magnum, bears the condyles for articulation with the atlas, is composed of four united elements, is much curved and roughly trapezoidal in outline, ends in front of the foramen magnum in the basilar process, and bears on its external surface behind the foramen magnum the two curved transverse superior and inferior nuchal lines as well as the median external occipital crest and external occipital protuberance (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.002.name: Foramen magnum
A02.1.04.002.definition: the opening in the skull through which the spinal cord passes to become the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.003.name: Basion
A02.1.04.003.definition: the midpoint of the anterior margin of the foramen magnum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.004.name: Opisthion
A02.1.04.004.definition: the median point of the posterior border of the foramen magnum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.006.name: Clivus
A02.1.04.006.definition: the smooth sloping surface on the upper posterior part of the body of the sphenoid bone supporting the pons and the basilar artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.013.name: (Interparietal bone)
A02.1.04.013.definition: a median triangular bone lying at the junction of the parietal and occipital bones and rarely present in humans but conspicuous in various lower mammals —called also interparietal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.014.name: Occipital condyle
A02.1.04.014.definition: an articular surface on the occipital bone on each side of the foramen magnum by which the skull articulates with the atlas (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.04.020.name: Jugular process
A02.1.04.020.definition: a quadrilateral or triangular process of the occipital bone on each side that articulates with the temporal bone and is situated lateral to the condyle of the occipital bone on each side articulating with the atlas (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.001.name: Sphenoid
A02.1.05.001.definition: of, relating to, or being a compound bone of the base of the cranium of various vertebrates formed by the fusion of several bony elements with the basisphenoid and in humans consisting of a median body from whose sides extend a pair of broad curved winglike expansions in front of which is another pair of much smaller triangular lateral processes while ventrally two large deeply cleft processes extend downward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.002.name: Body
A02.1.05.002.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.006.name: Sella turcica
A02.1.05.006.definition: a depression in the middle line of the upper surface of the sphenoid bone in which the pituitary gland is lodged (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.016.name: Sphenoidal sinus
A02.1.05.016.definition: either of two irregular cavities in the body of the sphenoid bone that communicate with the nasal cavities (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.020.name: Lesser wing
A02.1.05.020.definition: an anterior triangular process on each side of the sphenoid bone in front of and much smaller than the corresponding greater wing (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.024.name: Greater wing
A02.1.05.024.definition: a broad curved winglike expanse on each side of the sphenoid bone —called also alisphenoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.028.name: Infratemporal crest
A02.1.05.028.definition: a transverse ridge on the outer surface of the greater wing of the sphenoid bone that divides it into a superior portion that contributes to the formation of the temporal fossa and an inferior portion that contributes to the formation of the infratemporal fossa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.035.name: Foramen rotundum
A02.1.05.035.definition: a circular aperture in the anterior and medial part of the greater wing of the sphenoid that gives passage to the maxillary nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.036.name: Foramen ovale
A02.1.05.036.definition: an opening in the septum between the two atria of the heart that is normally present only in the fetus  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.038.name: Foramen spinosum
A02.1.05.038.definition: an aperture in the greater wing of the sphenoid that gives passage to the middle meningeal artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.042.name: Pterygoid process
A02.1.05.042.definition: a process that extends downward from each side of the sphenoid bone near the union of its body and a greater wing, that consists of the medial and lateral pterygoid plates which are fused above anteriorly and separated below by the pterygoid fissure whose edges articulate with a process of the palatine bone, and that contains on its posterior aspect the pterygoid and scaphoid fossae which give attachment to muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.043.name: Lateral plate
A02.1.05.043.definition: an unsegmented sheet of mesoderm on each side of the vertebrate embryo from which the coelom and its linings develop (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.046.name: Pterygoid fossa
A02.1.05.046.definition: a V-shaped depression on the posterior part of each pterygoid process that is formed by the divergence posteriorly of its medial and lateral pterygoid plates and that contains the medial pterygoid muscle and the tensor veli palatini (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.047.name: Scaphoid fossa
A02.1.05.047.definition: a shallow oval depression that is situated above the pterygoid fossa on the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone and that provides attachment for the origin of the tensor veli palatini muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.048.name: Vaginal process
A02.1.05.048.definition: a projecting lamina of bone on the inferior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone that is continuous with the tympanic plate and surrounds the root of the styloid process  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.05.051.name: Pterygoid hamulus
A02.1.05.051.definition: a hook-shaped process forming the inferior extremity of each medial pterygoid plate of the sphenoid bone and providing a support around which the tendon of the tensor veli palatini moves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Surco del gancho de la apófisis

A02.1.05.053.name: Pterygoid canal
A02.1.05.053.definition: an anteroposterior canal in the base of each medial pterygoid plate of the sphenoid bone that gives passage to the Vidian artery and the Vidian nerve —called also Vidian canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.001.name: Temporal bone
A02.1.06.001.definition: a compound bone of the side of the skull that has four principal parts including the squamous, petrous, and tympanic portions and the mastoid process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.004.name: Mastoid process
A02.1.06.004.definition: the process of the temporal bone behind the ear that is well developed and of somewhat conical form in adults but inconspicuous in children (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.009.name: Facial canal
A02.1.06.009.definition: a passage in the petrous part of the temporal bone that extends from the internal auditory canal to the stylomastoid foramen and transmits various branches of the facial nerve —called also aqueduct of Fallopius, fallopian aqueduct, fallopian canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Conductillo de la cuerda del tímpano

A02.1.06.013.name: Carotid canal
A02.1.06.013.definition: the canal by which the internal carotid artery enters the skull —called also carotid foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Conducto para el músculo ten del tímpano
Cara anterior de la porción petrosa

A02.1.06.022.name: Tegmen tympani
A02.1.06.022.definition: a thin plate of bone that covers the middle ear and separates it from the cranial cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Hiato del conducto para el nervio mayor
Hiato del conducto para el nervio menor
Borde superior de la porción petrosa
Cara posterior de la porción petrosa

A02.1.06.033.name: Internal acoustic meatus
A02.1.06.033.definition: a short auditory canal in the petrous portion of the temporal bone through which pass the facial and auditory nerves and the internal auditory artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Borde posterior de la porció petrosa
Facies cara inferior de la porcion petrosa

A02.1.06.041.name: Jugular fossa
A02.1.06.041.definition: a depression on the basilar surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone that contains a dilation of the internal jugular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.047.name: Styloid process
A02.1.06.047.definition: any of several long slender pointed bony processes: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.048.name: Stylomastoid foramen
A02.1.06.048.definition: a foramen that occurs on the lower surface of the temporal bone between the styloid and mastoid processes and that forms the termination of the facial canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.055.name: External acoustic meatus
A02.1.06.055.definition: the auditory canal leading from the opening of the external ear to the eardrum —called also external acoustic meatus, external auditory meatus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Apófisis vaginal de la apófisis estiloides
Surco de la arteria temporal media

A02.1.06.067.name: Zygomatic process
A02.1.06.067.definition: any of several bony processes that articulate with the zygomatic bone: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.06.074.name: Petrotympanic fissure
A02.1.06.074.definition: a narrow transverse slit dividing the glenoid fossa of the temporal bone —called also Glaserian fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.001.name: Ethmoid
A02.1.07.001.definition: of, relating to, adjoining, or being one or more bones of the walls and septum of the nasal cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.002.name: Cribriform plate
A02.1.07.002.definition: the horizontal plate of the ethmoid bone perforated with numerous foramina for the passage of the olfactory nerve filaments from the nasal cavity —called also lamina cribrosa  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.004.name: Crista galli
A02.1.07.004.definition: an upright process on the anterior portion of the cribriform plate to which the anterior part of the falx cerebri is attached (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ala de la apófisis crista galli

A02.1.07.006.name: Perpendicular plate
A02.1.07.006.definition: a flattened bony lamina of the ethmoid bone that is the largest bony part assisting in forming the nasal septum  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.011.name: Orbital plate
A02.1.07.011.definition: the part of the frontal bone forming most of the top of the orbit  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.016.name: Uncinate process
A02.1.07.016.definition: a hooklike body part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.07.018.name: Hiatus semilunaris
A02.1.07.018.definition: a curved fissure in the nasal passages into which the frontal and maxillary sinuses open (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.08.003.name: Maxillary process
A02.1.08.003.definition: a triangular embryonic process that grows out from the dorsal end of the mandibular arch on each side and forms the lateral part of the upper lip, the cheek, and the upper jaw except the premaxilla (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.09.001.name: Lacrimal bone
A02.1.09.001.definition: a small thin bone making up part of the front inner wall of each orbit and providing a groove for the passage of the lacrimal ducts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.10.001.name: Nasal bone
A02.1.10.001.definition: either of two bones of the skull of vertebrates above the fishes that lie in front of the frontal bones and in humans are oblong in shape forming by their junction the bridge of the nose and partly covering the nasal cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.11.001.name: Vomer
A02.1.11.001.definition: a bone of the skull of most vertebrates that is situated below the ethmoid region, that develops from lateral halves which remain separate in some animals, and that in humans forms the posterior and inferior part of the nasal septum comprising a vertical plate pointed in front and expanding at the upper back part into lateral wings (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.005.name: Infra-orbital groove
A02.1.12.005.definition: a groove in the middle of the posterior part of the bony floor of the orbit that gives passage to the infraorbital artery, vein, and nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.008.name: Infra-orbital foramen
A02.1.12.008.definition: an opening in the maxillary bone just below the lower rim of the orbit that gives passage to the infraorbital artery, nerve, and vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.009.name: Canine fossa
A02.1.12.009.definition: a depression external to and somewhat above the prominence on the surface of the superior maxillary bone caused by the socket of the canine tooth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.010.name: Nasal notch
A02.1.12.010.definition: the rough surface on the anterior lower border of the frontal bone between the orbits which articulates with the nasal bones and the maxillae (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.011.name: Anterior nasal spine
A02.1.12.011.definition: the nasal spine that is formed by the union of processes of the two premaxillae and projects upward between the anterior nares (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.015.name: Alveolar canals
A02.1.12.015.definition: the canals in the jawbones for the passage of the dental nerves and associated vessels (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.023.name: Maxillary sinus
A02.1.12.023.definition: an air cavity in the body of the maxilla that communicates with the middle meatus of the nose —called also antrum of Highmore (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.024.name: Frontal process
A02.1.12.024.definition: a long plate that is part of the maxillary bone and contributes to the formation of the lateral part of the nose and of the nasal cavity —called also nasal process  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.028.name: Zygomatic process
A02.1.12.028.definition: any of several bony processes that articulate with the zygomatic bone: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.029.name: Palatine process
A02.1.12.029.definition: a process of the maxilla that projects medially, articulates posteriorly with the palatine bone, and forms with the corresponding process on the other side the anterior three-fourths of the hard palate —called also palatal process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.035.name: Alveolar process
A02.1.12.035.definition: the bony ridge or raised thickened border of the upper or lower jaw that contains the sockets of the teeth —called also alveolar ridge (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.12.036.name: Alveolar arch
A02.1.12.036.definition: the arch of the upper or lower jaw formed by the alveolar processes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.001.name: Palatine bone
A02.1.13.001.definition: a bone of extremely irregular form on each side of the skull that is situated in the posterior part of the nasal cavity between the maxilla and the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone and that consists of a horizontal plate which joins the bone of the opposite side and forms the back part of the hard palate and a vertical plate which is extended into three processes and helps to form the floor of the orbit, the outer wall of the nasal cavity, and several adjoining parts —called also palate bone, palatine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.002.name: Perpendicular plate
A02.1.13.002.definition: a flattened bony lamina of the ethmoid bone that is the largest bony part assisting in forming the nasal septum  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.011.name: Orbital process
A02.1.13.011.definition: a process of the palatine bone that forms part of the floor of the orbit (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.012.name: Sphenoidal process
A02.1.13.012.definition: a process on the superior border of the vertical plate of the palatine bone articulating with the sphenoid  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.013.name: Horizontal plate
A02.1.13.013.definition: a plate of the palatine bone that is situated horizontally, joins the bone of the opposite side, and forms the back part of the hard palate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.13.017.name: Posterior nasal spine
A02.1.13.017.definition: the nasal spine that is formed by the union of processes of the two palatine bones and projects between the choanae (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.14.001.name: Zygomatic bone
A02.1.14.001.definition: a bone of the side of the face below the eye that in mammals forms part of the zygomatic arch and part of the orbit and articulates with the temporal, sphenoid, and frontal bones and with the maxilla of the upper jaw —called also cheekbone, jugal, malar bone, zygoma (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.14.005.name: Temporal process
A02.1.14.005.definition: a process of the zygomatic bone that with the zygomatic process of the temporal bone with which it articulates laterally forms part of the zygomatic arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.14.006.name: Frontal process
A02.1.14.006.definition: a long plate that is part of the maxillary bone and contributes to the formation of the lateral part of the nose and of the nasal cavity —called also nasal process  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.005.name: Mental protuberance
A02.1.15.005.definition: the bony protuberance at the front of the lower jaw forming the chin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.006.name: Mental tubercle
A02.1.15.006.definition: a prominence on each side of the mental protuberance of the mandible —called also genial tubercle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.007.name: Mental foramen
A02.1.15.007.definition: a foramen for the passage of blood vessels and a nerve on the outside of the lower jaw on each side near the chin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.012.name: Mylohyoid line
A02.1.15.012.definition: a ridge on the inner side of the bone of the lower jaw extending from the junction of the two halves of the bone in front to the last molar on each side and giving attachment to the mylohyoid muscle and to the superior constrictor of the pharynx —called also mylohyoid ridge (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.017.name: Alveolar arch
A02.1.15.017.definition: the arch of the upper or lower jaw formed by the alveolar processes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.028.name: Mandibular foramen
A02.1.15.028.definition: the opening on the medial surface of the ramus of the mandible that leads into the mandibular canal and transmits blood vessels and nerves supplying the lower teeth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.029.name: Lingula
A02.1.15.029.definition: a tongue-shaped process or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.030.name: Mandibular canal
A02.1.15.030.definition: a bony canal within the mandible that gives passage to blood vessels and nerves supplying the lower teeth —called also inferior alveolar canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.032.name: Coronoid process
A02.1.15.032.definition: the anterior process of the superior border of the ramus of the mandible  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.034.name: Mandibular notch
A02.1.15.034.definition: a curved depression on the upper border of the lower jaw between the coronoid process and the condyloid process —called also sigmoid notch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.15.035.name: Condylar process
A02.1.15.035.definition: the rounded process by which the ramus of the mandible articulates with the temporal bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.1.16.001.name: Hyoid bone
A02.1.16.001.definition: a U-shaped bone or complex of bones that is situated between the base of the tongue and the larynx and that supports the tongue, the larynx, and their muscles —called also hyoid, lingual bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.00.008.name: Scoliosis
A02.2.00.008.definition: a lateral curvature of the spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.00.009.name: Vertebral canal
A02.2.00.009.definition: a canal that contains the spinal cord and is delimited by the neural arches on the dorsal side of the vertebrae : spinal canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.001.name: Vertebra
A02.2.01.001.definition: any of the bony or cartilaginous segments that make up the spinal column and that have a short more or less cylindrical body whose ends articulate by pads of elastic or cartilaginous tissue with those of adjacent vertebrae and a bony arch that encloses the spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.002.name: Vertebral body
A02.2.01.002.definition: the thick, cylindrical, anterior part of a vertebra that bears the weight of the head and trunk, is attached to and articulates with an adjacent vertebral body by an intervertebral disk, and encloses the front part of the vertebral foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.007.name: Lamina
A02.2.01.007.definition: a thin plate or layer especially of an anatomical part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.008.name: Intervertebral foramen
A02.2.01.008.definition: any of the openings on the left and right side of the spinal column between vertebrae that is formed by a superior and inferior notch in the pedicles of contiguous vertebrae and gives passage to the spinal nerves from the spinal canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.011.name: Vertebral foramen
A02.2.01.011.definition: the opening in a vertebra that is formed by a neural arch and back portion of a vertebral body and through which the spinal cord passes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.012.name: Spinous process
A02.2.01.012.definition: spine; specifically : a bony process of a vertebra that projects posteriorly from the neural arch and the junction of two laminae and provides attachment for muscles concerned especially with flexion, extension, rotation, and stability of the spinal column (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.013.name: Transverse process
A02.2.01.013.definition: either of the two bony processes of a vertebra that project laterally from the neural arch at the junction of a pedicle and lamina and that provide attachment for muscles and ligaments concerned especially with rotation, lateral flexion, and stability of the spinal column (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.014.name: Superior articular process
A02.2.01.014.definition: a process of a vertebra that lies on each side of the neural arch and projects upward and articulates with an inferior articular process of the next more cranial vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.01.016.name: Inferior articular process
A02.2.01.016.definition: a process of a vertebra that lies on each side of the neural arch and projects downward and articulates with a superior articular process of the next more caudal vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.02.202.name: Dens
A02.2.02.202.definition: a toothlike process that projects from the anterior end of the centrum of the axis in the spinal column, serves as a pivot on which the atlas rotates, and is morphologically the centrum of the atlas though detached from that vertebra and more or less perfectly united with the next one behind —called also odontoid process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.02.203.name: Apex
A02.2.02.203.definition: a narrowed or pointed end of an anatomical structure: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Fosita costal de la apófisis transversa

A02.2.03.005.name: Uncus of body of first thoracic vertebra

term_localized.en: Uncus of body of first thoracic vertebra
term_localized.es: Uncus de la primera vértebra torácica

A02.2.04.003.name: Costal process
A02.2.04.003.definition: the ventral or anterior root of the transverse process of a cervical vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.002.name: Base
A02.2.05.002.definition: that portion of a bodily organ or part by which it is attached to another more central structure of the organism  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.004.name: Ala
A02.2.05.004.definition: a wing or a winglike anatomic process or part; especially : ala nasi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.005.name: Superior articular process
A02.2.05.005.definition: a process of a vertebra that lies on each side of the neural arch and projects upward and articulates with an inferior articular process of the next more cranial vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.011.name: Intervertebral foramina
A02.2.05.011.definition: any of the openings on the left and right side of the spinal column between vertebrae that is formed by a superior and inferior notch in the pedicles of contiguous vertebrae and gives passage to the spinal nerves from the spinal canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.018.name: Sacral cornu
A02.2.05.018.definition: a rounded process on each side of the fifth sacral vertebra that projects downward and represents an inferior articular process of the vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.019.name: Sacral canal
A02.2.05.019.definition: the part of the spinal canal lying in the sacrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.020.name: Sacral hiatus
A02.2.05.020.definition: the opening into the spinal canal in the midline of the dorsal surface of the sacrum between the laminae of the fifth sacral vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.2.05.021.name: Apex
A02.2.05.021.definition: a narrowed or pointed end of an anatomical structure: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.01.005.name: Costal cartilage
A02.3.01.005.definition: any of the cartilages that connect the distal ends of the ribs with the sternum and by their elasticity permit movement of the chest in respiration (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.001.name: Rib
A02.3.02.001.definition: any of the paired curved bony or partly cartilaginous rods that stiffen the lateral walls of the body of most vertebrates and protect the viscera, that occur in mammals exclusively or almost exclusively in the thoracic region, and that in humans normally include 12 pairs of which all are articulated with the spinal column at the dorsal end and the first 10 are connected also at the ventral end with the sternum by costal cartilages (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.002.name: Head
A02.3.02.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.004.name: Crest
A02.3.02.004.definition: a showy tuft or process on the head of an animal and especially a bird  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.005.name: Neck
A02.3.02.005.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.006.name: Crest
A02.3.02.006.definition: a showy tuft or process on the head of an animal and especially a bird  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.007.name: Body
A02.3.02.007.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.008.name: Tubercle
A02.3.02.008.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.010.name: Angle
A02.3.02.010.definition: a corner whether constituting a projecting part or a partially enclosed space  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.012.name: Crest
A02.3.02.012.definition: a showy tuft or process on the head of an animal and especially a bird  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.013.name: (Cervical rib)
A02.3.02.013.definition: a supernumerary rib sometimes found in the neck above the usual first rib (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.02.015.name: Scalene tubercle
A02.3.02.015.definition: a tubercle on the upper surface of the first rib that serves for insertion of the scalenus anterior (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Tuberosidad para el músculo serrato anterior

A02.3.03.001.name: Sternum
A02.3.03.001.definition: a compound ventral bone or cartilage that lies in the median central part of the body of most vertebrates above fishes and that in humans is about seven inches (18 centimeters) long, consists in the adult of three parts, and connects with the clavicles and the cartilages of the upper seven pairs of ribs —called also breastbone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.03.003.name: Clavicular notch
A02.3.03.003.definition: a notch on each side of the upper part of the manubrium that is the site of articulation with a clavicle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.03.005.name: Sternal angle
A02.3.03.005.definition: the angle formed by the joining of the manubrium to the gladiolus of the sternum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.03.007.name: Xiphoid process
A02.3.03.007.definition: the smallest and lowest division of the human sternum that is cartilaginous early in life but becomes more or less ossified during adulthood —called also ensiform cartilage, ensiform process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.3.04.002.name: Thoracic cavity
A02.3.04.002.definition: the division of the body cavity that lies above the diaphragm, is bounded peripherally by the wall of the chest, and contains the heart and lungs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.001.name: Scapula
A02.4.01.001.definition: either of a pair of large essentially flat and triangular bones lying one in each dorsolateral part of the thorax, being the principal bone of the corresponding half of the shoulder girdle, divided on the posterior surface into the supraspinous and infraspinous fossae by an oblique transverse bony process or spine terminating in the acromion, having a hook-shaped bony coracoid process on the anterior surface of the superior border of the bone, providing articulation for the humerus, and articulating with the corresponding clavicle —called also shoulder blade (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.003.name: Subscapular fossa
A02.4.01.003.definition: the concave depression of the anterior surface of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.005.name: Spine of scapula
A02.4.01.005.definition: a projecting triangular bony process on the dorsal surface of the scapula that divides it obliquely into the area of origin of parts of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles and that terminates in the acromion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.007.name: Supraspinous fossa
A02.4.01.007.definition: a smooth concavity above the spine on the dorsal surface of the scapula that gives origin to the supraspinatus muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.008.name: Infraspinous fossa
A02.4.01.008.definition: the part of the dorsal surface of the scapula below the spine of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.009.name: Acromion
A02.4.01.009.definition: the outer end of the spine of the scapula that protects the glenoid cavity, forms the outer angle of the shoulder, and articulates with the clavicle —called also acromial process, acromion process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.015.name: Suprascapular notch
A02.4.01.015.definition: a deep notch in the upper border of the scapula at the base of the coracoid process giving passage to the suprascapular nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.019.name: Glenoid cavity
A02.4.01.019.definition: the shallow cavity of the upper part of the scapula by which the humerus articulates with the shoulder girdle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.021.name: Infraglenoid tubercle
A02.4.01.021.definition: a tubercle on the scapula for the attachment of the long head of the triceps muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.01.023.name: Coracoid process
A02.4.01.023.definition: a process of the scapula in most mammals representing the remnant of the coracoid bone of lower vertebrates that has become fused with the scapula and in humans is situated on its superior border and serves for the attachment of various muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.02.001.name: Clavicle
A02.4.02.001.definition: a bone of the shoulder girdle that links the scapula and sternum, is situated just above the first rib on either side of the neck, and has the form of a narrow elongated S —called also collarbone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.02.010.name: Conoid tubercle
A02.4.02.010.definition: a prominence on the underside of the clavicle that forms one attachment of the conoid ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.001.name: Humerus
A02.4.04.001.definition: the longest bone of the upper arm or forelimb extending from the shoulder to the elbow, articulating above by a rounded head with the glenoid cavity, having below a broad articular surface divided by a ridge into a medial pulley-shaped portion and a lateral rounded eminence that articulate with the ulna and radius respectively, and providing various processes and modified surfaces for the attachment of muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.002.name: Head
A02.4.04.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.004.name: Surgical neck
A02.4.04.004.definition: a slightly narrowed part of the humerus below the greater and lesser tubercles that is frequently the site of fractures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.005.name: Greater tubercle
A02.4.04.005.definition: a prominence on the upper lateral part of the end of the humerus that serves as the insertion for the supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and teres minor (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.006.name: Lesser tubercle
A02.4.04.006.definition: a prominence on the upper anterior part of the end of the humerus that serves as the insertion for the subscapularis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.020.name: Deltoid tuberosity
A02.4.04.020.definition: a rough triangular bump on the outer side of the middle of the humerus that is the site of insertion of the deltoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.022.name: Capitulum
A02.4.04.022.definition: a rounded protuberance of an anatomical part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.023.name: Trochlea
A02.4.04.023.definition: an anatomical structure resembling a pulley: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.024.name: Olecranon fossa
A02.4.04.024.definition: the fossa at the distal end of the humerus into which the olecranon fits when the arm is in full extension (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.04.025.name: Coronoid fossa
A02.4.04.025.definition: a depression of the humerus into which the coronoid process fits when the arm is flexed (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.001.name: Radius
A02.4.05.001.definition: the bone on the thumb side of the human forearm or on the corresponding part of the forelimb of vertebrates above fishes that in humans is movably articulated with the ulna at both ends so as to permit partial rotation about that bone, that bears on its inner aspect somewhat distal to the head a prominence for the insertion of the biceps tendon, and that has the lower end broadened for articulation with the proximal bones of the carpus so that rotation of the radius involves also that of the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.002.name: Head
A02.4.05.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.005.name: Neck
A02.4.05.005.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.006.name: Shaft
A02.4.05.006.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.007.name: Radial tuberosity
A02.4.05.007.definition: an oval eminence on the medial side of the radius distal to the neck where the tendon of the biceps brachii muscle inserts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.05.019.name: Ulnar notch
A02.4.05.019.definition: the narrow medial concave surface on the lower end of the radius that articulates with the ulna (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.001.name: Ulna
A02.4.06.001.definition: the bone on the little-finger side of the human forearm that forms with the humerus the elbow joint and serves as a pivot in rotation of the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.002.name: Olecranon
A02.4.06.002.definition: the large process of the ulna that projects behind the elbow, forms the bony prominence of the elbow, and receives the insertion of the triceps muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.003.name: Coronoid process
A02.4.06.003.definition: the anterior process of the superior border of the ramus of the mandible  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.005.name: Radial notch
A02.4.06.005.definition: a narrow depression on the lateral side of the coronoid process of the ulna that articulates with the head of the radius and gives attachment to the annular ligament of the radius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.006.name: Trochlear notch
A02.4.06.006.definition: the deep depression in the proximal end of the ulna by which the ulna articulates with the trochlea of the humerus at the elbow —called also semilunar notch, sigmoid notch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.007.name: Shaft
A02.4.06.007.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.014.name: Supinator crest
A02.4.06.014.definition: a bony ridge on the upper lateral surface of the shaft of the ulna that is the origin for part of the supinator muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.06.015.name: Head
A02.4.06.015.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.003.name: Scaphoid
A02.4.08.003.definition: shaped like a boat : navicular  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.004.name: Tubercle
A02.4.08.004.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.007.name: Pisiform
A02.4.08.007.definition: resembling a pea in size or shape (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.008.name: Trapezium
A02.4.08.008.definition: a bone in the distal row of the carpus at the base of the thumb —called also greater multangular (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.009.name: Tubercle
A02.4.08.009.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.08.010.name: Trapezoid
A02.4.08.010.definition: a bone in the distal row of the carpus at the base of the index finger —called also lesser multangular, trapezoid bone, trapezoideum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.09.002.name: Base
A02.4.09.002.definition: that portion of a bodily organ or part by which it is attached to another more central structure of the organism  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.09.003.name: Shaft
A02.4.09.003.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.09.004.name: Head
A02.4.09.004.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.4.10.001.name: Phalanges
A02.4.10.001.definition: any of the digital bones of the hand or foot distal to the metacarpus or metatarsus of a vertebrate that in humans are three to each finger and toe with the exception of the thumb and big toe which have only two each (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.00.002.name: Pelvic girdle
A02.5.00.002.definition: a bony or cartilaginous arch that supports the hind limbs of a vertebrate, that corresponds to the shoulder girdle of the forelimbs but is usually more rigid and firmly attached to the spinal column, and that consists in lower forms of a single cartilage which is replaced in higher forms including humans by paired hip bones articulating solidly with the sacrum dorsally and with one another at the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.001.name: Hip bone
A02.5.01.001.definition: the large flaring bone that makes a lateral half of the pelvis in mammals and is composed of the ilium, ischium, and pubis which are consolidated into one bone in the adult —called also innominate bone, os coxae, pelvic bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.002.name: Acetabulum
A02.5.01.002.definition: the cup-shaped socket in the hip bone  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.005.name: Acetabular notch
A02.5.01.005.definition: a notch in the rim of the acetabulum through which blood vessels and nerves pass (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.007.name: Ischiopubic ramus
A02.5.01.007.definition: the flattened inferior projection of the hip bone below the obturator foramen consisting of the united inferior rami of the pubis and ischium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.008.name: Obturator foramen
A02.5.01.008.definition: an opening that is the largest foramen in the human body, is situated between the ischium and pubis of the hip bone, and is closed by the obturator membrane except for the obturator canal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.101.name: Ilium
A02.5.01.101.definition: the dorsal, upper, and largest one of the three bones composing either lateral half of the pelvis that in humans is broad and expanded above and narrower below where it joins with the ischium and pubis to form part of the acetabulum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.106.name: Iliac crest
A02.5.01.106.definition: the thick curved upper border of the ilium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.111.name: Anterior superior iliac spine
A02.5.01.111.definition: a projection at the anterior end of the iliac crest —called also anterior superior spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.112.name: Anterior inferior iliac spine
A02.5.01.112.definition: a projection on the anterior margin of the ilium that is situated below the anterior superior iliac spine and is separated from it by a notch —called also anterior inferior spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.113.name: Posterior superior iliac spine
A02.5.01.113.definition: a projection at the posterior end of the iliac crest —called also posterior superior spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.114.name: Posterior inferior iliac spine
A02.5.01.114.definition: a projection on the posterior margin of the ilium that is situated below the posterior superior iliac spine and is separated from it by a notch —called also posterior inferior spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.115.name: Iliac fossa
A02.5.01.115.definition: the inner concavity of the ilium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.201.name: Ischium
A02.5.01.201.definition: the dorsal and posterior of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis consisting in humans of a thick portion, a large rough eminence on which the body rests when sitting, and a forwardly directed ramus which joins that of the pubis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.202.name: Body
A02.5.01.202.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.203.name: Ramus
A02.5.01.203.definition: a projecting part, elongated process, or branch: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.204.name: Ischial tuberosity
A02.5.01.204.definition: a bony swelling on the posterior part of the superior ramus of the ischium that gives attachment to various muscles and bears the weight of the body in sitting (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.205.name: Ischial spine
A02.5.01.205.definition: a thin pointed triangular eminence that projects from the dorsal border of the ischium and gives attachment to the gemellus superior on its external surface and to the coccygeus, levator ani, and pelvic fascia on its internal surface (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.301.name: Pubis
A02.5.01.301.definition: the ventral and anterior of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis that in humans consists of two rami diverging posteriorly from the region of the pubic symphysis with the superior ramus extending to the acetabulum of which it forms a part and uniting there with the ilium and ischium and the inferior ramus extending below the obturator foramen where it unites with the ischium —called also pubic bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.302.name: Body
A02.5.01.302.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.303.name: Pubic tubercle
A02.5.01.303.definition: a rounded eminence on the upper margin of each pubis near the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.305.name: Pubic crest
A02.5.01.305.definition: the border of a pubis between its pubic tubercle and the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.01.310.name: Obturator groove
A02.5.01.310.definition: a groove in the inferior surface of the superior ramus of the pubis that is converted to the obturator canal when covered over by part of the obturator membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.02.001.name: Pelvis
A02.5.02.001.definition: a basin-shaped structure in the skeleton of many vertebrates that is formed by the pelvic girdle together with the sacrum and often various coccygeal and caudal vertebrae and that in humans is composed of the two hip bones bounding it on each side and in front while the sacrum and coccyx complete it behind  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.02.002.name: Pelvic cavity
A02.5.02.002.definition: the cavity of the pelvis comprising in humans a broad upper and a more contracted lower part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.02.003.name: Pubic arch
A02.5.02.003.definition: the notch formed by the inferior rami of the two conjoined pubic bones as they diverge from the midline (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.02.004.name: Subpubic angle
A02.5.02.004.definition: the angle that is formed just below the pubic symphysis by the meeting of the inferior ramus of the pubis on one side with the corresponding part on the other side and that is usually less than 90\u00b0 in the male and usually more than 90\u00b0 in the female (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.02.009.name: Pelvic outlet
A02.5.02.009.definition: the irregular bony opening bounded by the lower border of the pelvis and closed by muscle and other soft tissues through which the terminal parts of the excretory, reproductive, and digestive systems pass to communicate with the surface of the body —called also outlet of the pelvis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.001.name: Femur
A02.5.04.001.definition: the proximal bone of the hind or lower limb that is the longest and largest bone in the human body, extends from the hip to the knee, articulates above with the acetabulum by a rounded head connected with the shaft of the bone by an oblique neck bearing a pair of trochanters for the attachment of muscles, and articulates with the tibia below by a pair of condyles —called also thigh bone  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.002.name: Head
A02.5.04.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.004.name: Neck
A02.5.04.004.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.006.name: Trochanteric fossa
A02.5.04.006.definition: a depression at the base of the internal surface of the greater trochanter of the femur for the attachment of the tendon of the obturator externus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.009.name: Intertrochanteric line
A02.5.04.009.definition: a line on the anterior surface of the femur that runs obliquely from the greater trochanter to the lesser trochanter (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.013.name: Linea aspera
A02.5.04.013.definition: a longitudinal ridge on the posterior surface of the middle third of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.017.name: Gluteal tuberosity
A02.5.04.017.definition: the lateral ridge of the linea aspera of the femur that gives attachment to the gluteus maximus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.021.name: Medial condyle
A02.5.04.021.definition: a condyle on the inner side of the lower extremity of the femur; also : a corresponding eminence on the upper part of the tibia that articulates with the medial condyle of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.023.name: Adductor tubercle
A02.5.04.023.definition: a tubercle on the proximal part of the medial epicondyle of the femur that is the site of insertion of the adductor magnus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.04.024.name: Lateral condyle
A02.5.04.024.definition: a condyle on the outer side of the lower extremity of the femur; also : a corresponding eminence on the upper part of the tibia that articulates with the lateral condyle of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.05.001.name: Patella
A02.5.05.001.definition: a thick flat triangular movable bone that forms the anterior point of the knee, protects the front of the joint, increases the leverage of the quadriceps, and is usually regarded as a sesamoid bone since it is developed in the tendon of the quadriceps and in structure is similar to other sesamoid bones —called also kneecap, kneepan (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.06.001.name: Tibia
A02.5.06.001.definition: the inner and usually larger of the two bones of the leg between the knee and ankle that articulates above with the femur and below with the talus —called also shinbone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.06.003.name: Medial condyle
A02.5.06.003.definition: a condyle on the inner side of the lower extremity of the femur; also : a corresponding eminence on the upper part of the tibia that articulates with the medial condyle of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.06.004.name: Lateral condyle
A02.5.06.004.definition: a condyle on the outer side of the lower extremity of the femur; also : a corresponding eminence on the upper part of the tibia that articulates with the lateral condyle of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.06.011.name: Shaft
A02.5.06.011.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.07.001.name: Fibula
A02.5.07.001.definition: the outer or postaxial and usually the smaller of the two bones of the hind or lower limb below the knee that is the slenderest bone of the human body in proportion to its length, articulates above with the external tuberosity of the tibia and below with the talus, and has its lower end forming the external malleolus of the ankle —called also calf bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.07.002.name: Head
A02.5.07.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.07.005.name: Neck
A02.5.07.005.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.07.006.name: Shaft
A02.5.07.006.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.10.001.name: Talus
A02.5.10.001.definition: the human astragalus that bears the weight of the body and together with the tibia and fibula forms the ankle joint —called also anklebone  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.10.002.name: Head
A02.5.10.002.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.11.001.name: Calcaneus
A02.5.11.001.definition: a tarsal bone that in humans is the large bone of the heel —called also heel bone, os calcis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.11.006.name: Sustentaculum tali
A02.5.11.006.definition: a medial process of the calcaneus supporting part of the talus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.12.002.name: Tuberosity
A02.5.12.002.definition: a rounded prominence; especially : a large prominence on a bone usually serving for the attachment of muscles or ligaments (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.16.001.name: Cuboid
A02.5.16.001.definition: relating to or being the cuboid  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)
