A02.5.16.003.name: Tuberosity
A02.5.16.003.definition: a rounded prominence; especially : a large prominence on a bone usually serving for the attachment of muscles or ligaments (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.17.002.name: Base
A02.5.17.002.definition: that portion of a bodily organ or part by which it is attached to another more central structure of the organism  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.17.003.name: Shaft
A02.5.17.003.definition: a long slender cylindrical body or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.17.004.name: Head
A02.5.17.004.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A02.5.18.001.name: Phalanges
A02.5.18.001.definition: any of the digital bones of the hand or foot distal to the metacarpus or metatarsus of a vertebrate that in humans are three to each finger and toe with the exception of the thumb and big toe which have only two each (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.000.name: Joints
A03.0.00.000.definition: the point of contact between elements of an animal skeleton whether movable or rigidly fixed together with the surrounding and supporting parts (as membranes, tendons, or ligaments) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.001.name: Joint
A03.0.00.001.definition: the point of contact between elements of an animal skeleton whether movable or rigidly fixed together with the surrounding and supporting parts (as membranes, tendons, or ligaments) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.003.name: Synarthrosis
A03.0.00.003.definition: an immovable articulation in which the bones are united by intervening fibrous connective tissues (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.005.name: Syndesmosis
A03.0.00.005.definition: an articulation in which the contiguous surfaces of the bones are rough and are bound together by a ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.006.name: Gomphosis
A03.0.00.006.definition: an immovable articulation in which a hard part is received into a bone cavity (as the teeth into the jaws) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.007.name: Interosseous membrane
A03.0.00.007.definition: either of two thin strong sheets of fibrous tissue:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.008.name: Suture
A03.0.00.008.definition: a stitch made with a suture  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.014.name: Schindylesis
A03.0.00.014.definition: an articulation in which one bone is received into a groove or slit in another (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.016.name: Synchondrosis
A03.0.00.016.definition: an immovable skeletal articulation in which the union is cartilaginous (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.017.name: Symphysis
A03.0.00.017.definition: an immovable or more or less movable articulation of various bones in the median plane of the body  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.025.name: Labrum
A03.0.00.025.definition: an upper or anterior mouthpart of an arthropod consisting of a single median piece in front of or above the mandibles  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.026.name: Joint capsule
A03.0.00.026.definition: a ligamentous sac that surrounds the articular cavity of a freely movable joint, is attached to the bones, completely encloses the joint, and is composed of an outer fibrous membrane and an inner synovial membrane —called also articular capsule, capsular ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.028.name: Synovial membrane
A03.0.00.028.definition: the dense connective-tissue membrane that secretes synovial fluid and that lines the ligamentous surfaces of joint capsules, tendon sheaths where free movement is necessary, and bursae (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.031.name: Synovial fluid
A03.0.00.031.definition: a transparent viscid lubricating fluid secreted by a membrane of an articulation, bursa, or tendon sheath —called also joint fluid, synovia (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.033.name: Meniscus
A03.0.00.033.definition: a crescent or crescent-shaped body  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.034.name: Ligaments
A03.0.00.034.definition: a tough band of tissue that serves to connect the articular extremities of bones or to support or retain an organ in place and is usually composed of coarse bundles of dense white fibrous tissue parallel or closely interlaced, pliant, and flexible, but not extensible  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.045.name: Pivot joint
A03.0.00.045.definition: an anatomical articulation that consists of a bony pivot in a ring of bone and ligament (as that of the dens and atlas) and that permits rotatory movement only —called also trochoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.046.name: Hinge joint
A03.0.00.046.definition: a joint between bones (as at the elbow or knee) that permits motion in only one plane; especially : ginglymus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.048.name: Saddle joint
A03.0.00.048.definition: a joint (as the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb) with saddle-shaped articular surfaces that are convex in one direction and concave in another and that permit movements in all directions except axial rotation (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.050.name: Ball and socket joint
A03.0.00.050.definition: an articulation (as the hip joint) in which the rounded head of one bone fits into a cuplike cavity of the other and admits movement in any direction —called also enarthrosis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.052.name: Amphiarthrosis
A03.0.00.052.definition: a slightly movable articulation (as a symphysis or a syndesmosis) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.053.name: Abduction
A03.0.00.053.definition: to draw away (as a limb) from a position near or parallel to the median axis of the body; also : to move (similar parts) apart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.054.name: Adduction
A03.0.00.054.definition: the action of adducting : the state of being adducted (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.057.name: Circumduction
A03.0.00.057.definition: movement of a limb or extremity so that the distal end describes a circle while the proximal end remains fixed (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.058.name: Flexion
A03.0.00.058.definition: a bending movement around a joint in a limb (as the knee or elbow) that decreases the angle between the bones of the limb at the joint  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.059.name: Extension
A03.0.00.059.definition: the stretching of a fractured or dislocated limb so as to restore it to its natural position  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.060.name: Pronation
A03.0.00.060.definition: rotation of an anatomical part towards the midline: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.061.name: Supination
A03.0.00.061.definition: rotation of the forearm and hand so that the palm faces forward or upward and the radius lies parallel to the ulna; also : a corresponding movement of the foot and leg in which the foot rolls outward with an elevated arch so that in walking the foot tends to come down on its outer edge  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.0.00.063.name: Reposition
A03.0.00.063.definition: to return to or place in a normal or proper position (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.01.003.name: Stylohyoid ligament
A03.1.01.003.definition: a band of fibrous tissue connecting the tip of the styloid process of the temporal bone to the ceratohyal of the hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.002.name: Coronal suture
A03.1.02.002.definition: a suture extending across the skull between the parietal and frontal bones —called also frontoparietal suture (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.003.name: Sagittal suture
A03.1.02.003.definition: the deeply serrated articulation between the two parietal bones in the median plane of the top of the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.006.name: Sphenofrontal suture
A03.1.02.006.definition: the suture occurring between the greater wing of the sphenoid and the frontal bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.009.name: Sphenoparietal suture
A03.1.02.009.definition: the suture occurring between the greater wing of the sphenoid bone and the parietal bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.022.name: Sphenozygomatic suture
A03.1.02.022.definition: the suture occurring between the greater wing of the sphenoid bone and the zygomatic bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.02.026.name: Nasomaxillary suture
A03.1.02.026.definition: the suture uniting the nasal bone and the maxilla (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.03.002.name: Periodontium
A03.1.03.002.definition: the supporting structures of the teeth including the cementum, the periodontal ligament, the bone of the alveolar process, and the gums (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.03.004.name: Gum
A03.1.03.004.definition: the tissue that surrounds the necks of teeth and covers the alveolar parts of the jaws; broadly : the alveolar portion of a jaw with its enveloping soft tissues (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.05.002.name: Spheno-occipital synchondrosis
A03.1.05.002.definition: the cartilaginous junction between the basisphenoid and basioccipital bones of the mammalian skull that in humans is usually closed by the age of 25 (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.07.001.name: Temporomandibular joint
A03.1.07.001.definition: the diarthrosis between the temporal bone and mandible that includes the condyloid process below separated by an articular disk from the glenoid fossa above and that allows for the opening, closing, protrusion, retraction, and lateral movement of the mandible —abbreviation TMJ (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.07.003.name: Lateral ligament
A03.1.07.003.definition: any of various ligaments (as the lateral collateral ligament of the knee) that are in a lateral position or that prevent lateral dislocation of a joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.07.007.name: Sphenomandibular ligament
A03.1.07.007.definition: a flat thin band of fibrous tissue derived from Meckel's cartilage which extends downward from the sphenoid bone to the lingula of the mandibular foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.1.07.008.name: Stylomandibular ligament
A03.1.07.008.definition: a band of deep fascia that connects the styloid process of the temporal bone to the gonial angle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.01.003.name: Ligamenta flava
A03.2.01.003.definition: any of a series of ligaments of yellow elastic tissue connecting the laminae of adjacent vertebrae from the axis to the sacrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.01.006.name: Ligamentum nuchae
A03.2.01.006.definition: a medium ligament of the back of the neck that is rudimentary in humans but highly developed and composed of yellow elastic tissue in many quadrupeds where it assists in supporting the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.01.009.name: Transverse ligaments
A03.2.01.009.definition: any of various ligaments situated transversely with respect to a bodily axis or part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.02.004.name: Anulus fibrosus
A03.2.02.004.definition: a ring of fibrous tissue (such as that surrounding a heart valve); especially : the outer portion of an intervertebral disk that surrounds the nucleus pulposus and is composed chiefly of layers of collagen fibers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.02.005.name: Nucleus pulposus
A03.2.02.005.definition: an elastic pulpy mass lying in the center of each intervertebral fibrocartilage and regarded as a remnant of the notochord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.04.002.name: Alar ligaments
A03.2.04.002.definition: either of a pair of strong rounded fibrous cords of which one arises on each side of the cranial part of the dens, passes obliquely and laterally upward, and inserts on the medial side of a condyle of the occipital bone —called also check ligament  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.04.003.name: Apical ligament of dens
A03.2.04.003.definition: a fibrous cord between the two alar ligaments that extends from the tip of the dens to the anterior margin of the foramen magnum —called also apical dental ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.04.007.name: Tectorial membrane
A03.2.04.007.definition: a membrane having the consistency of jelly that covers the surface of the organ of Corti (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.07.001.name: Lumbosacral joint
A03.2.07.001.definition: the joint between the fifth lumbar vertebra and the sacrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.2.07.002.name: Iliolumbar ligament
A03.2.07.002.definition: a ligament connecting the transverse process of the last lumbar vertebra with the iliac crest (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.03.004.name: Coracoclavicular ligament
A03.5.03.004.definition: a ligament that joins the clavicle and the coracoid process of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.03.006.name: Conoid ligament
A03.5.03.006.definition: the posterior fasciculus of the coracoclavicular ligament connecting the conoid tubercle and the base of the coracoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.08.002.name: Glenoid labrum
A03.5.08.002.definition: a fibrocartilaginous ligament forming the margin of the glenoid cavity of the shoulder joint that serves to broaden and deepen the cavity and gives attachment to the long head of the biceps brachii —called also labrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.09.001.name: Elbow joint
A03.5.09.001.definition: the joint between the human forearm and the upper arm that supports the outer curve of the arm when bent —called also elbow joint  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.09.004.name: Proximal radio-ulnar joint
A03.5.09.004.definition: a pivot joint between the upper end of the radius and the ring formed by the radial notch of the ulna and its annular ligament that permits rotation of the proximal head of the radius —called also superior radioulnar joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.09.005.name: Ulnar collateral ligament
A03.5.09.005.definition: a triangular ligament of the elbow that connects the medial epicondyle of the humerus with the medial edge of the coronoid process and the olecranon of the ulna, that helps to stabilize the elbow joint, and that is often injured in sports (as baseball) which involve repeated overhand throwing —called also medial collateral ligament, UCL  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.09.006.name: Radial collateral ligament
A03.5.09.006.definition: a triangular ligament of the elbow that connects the lateral epicondyle with the lateral side of the annular ligament and helps to stabilize the elbow joint —called also lateral collateral ligament  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.10.001.name: Distal radio-ulnar joint
A03.5.10.001.definition: a pivot joint between the lower end of the ulna and the ulnar notch on the lower end of the radius that permits rotation of the distal end of the radius around the longitudinal axis of the ulna —called also inferior radioulnar joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.11.002.name: Wrist joint
A03.5.11.002.definition: the articulation at the wrist (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.11.007.name: Ulnar collateral ligament of wrist joint

A03.5.11.201.name: Carpal tunnel
A03.5.11.201.definition: a passage between the flexor retinaculum of the hand and the carpal bones that is sometimes a site of compression of the median nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.11.302.name: Articular disk
A03.5.11.302.definition: a cartilage (as the meniscus of the temporomandibular joint) interposed between two articular surfaces and partially or completely separating the joint cavity into two compartments (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.11.502.name: Collateral ligaments
A03.5.11.502.definition: any of various ligaments on one or the other side of a hinge joint (as the knee, elbow, or the joints between the phalanges of the toes and fingers): as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.5.11.602.name: Collateral ligaments
A03.5.11.602.definition: any of various ligaments on one or the other side of a hinge joint (as the knee, elbow, or the joints between the phalanges of the toes and fingers): as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.01.002.name: Obturator membrane
A03.6.01.002.definition: a firm fibrous membrane covering most of the obturator foramen except for the obturator canal and serving as origin of the obturator externus and obturator internus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.01.003.name: Obturator canal
A03.6.01.003.definition: the small patent opening of the obturator foramen through which nerves and vessels pass and which is formed by the obturator groove covered over by part of the obturator membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.02.001.name: Pubic symphysis
A03.6.02.001.definition: the rather rigid articulation of the two pubic bones in the midline of the lower anterior part of the abdomen —called also symphysis pubis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.03.001.name: Sacro-iliac joint
A03.6.03.001.definition: the joint or articulation between the sacrum and ilium —called also sacroiliac, sacroiliac articulation (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.03.005.name: Sacrotuberous ligament
A03.6.03.005.definition: a thin fan-shaped ligament on each side of the body that is attached above to the posterior superior and posterior inferior iliac spines and to the sacrum and coccyx, that passes obliquely downward to insert into the inner margin of the ischial tuberosity, and that with the sacrospinous ligament closes off the lesser sciatic notch to form the lesser sciatic foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.03.007.name: Sacrospinous ligament
A03.6.03.007.definition: a ligament on each side of the body that is attached by a broad base to the lateral margins of the sacrum and coccyx and passes to the ischial spine and that closes off the greater sciatic notch to form the greater sciatic foramen and with the sacrotuberous ligament closes off the lesser sciatic notch to form the lesser sciatic foramen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.06.001.name: Synovial joints of free lower limb
