A03.6.07.001.name: Hip joint
A03.6.07.001.definition: the ball-and-socket joint comprising the articulation between the femur and the hip bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.07.003.name: Iliofemoral ligament
A03.6.07.003.definition: a ligament that extends from the anterior inferior iliac spine to the intertrochanteric line of the femur and divides below into two branches of which one is fixed to the distal part and the other to the proximal part of the intertrochanteric line —called also Y ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.07.007.name: Pubofemoral ligament
A03.6.07.007.definition: a ligament of the hip joint that extends from the superior ramus of the pubis to the capsule of the hip joint near the neck of the femur and that acts to prevent excessive extension and abduction of the thigh —called also pubocapsular ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.07.008.name: Acetabular labrum
A03.6.07.008.definition: a fibrocartilaginous ligament that forms a rim around most of the acetabulum of the hip joint and serves to increase the depth and surface area of the socket articulating with the head of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ligamento de la cabeza del fémur

A03.6.08.007.name: Anterior cruciate ligament
A03.6.08.007.definition: a cruciate ligament of each knee that is attached in front to the more medial aspect of the tibia, that passes upward, backward, and laterally through the middle of the knee crossing the posterior cruciate ligament to attach to the femur, that functions to prevent hyperextension of the knee and to keep the tibia from sliding forward in relation to the femur, and that is subject to sports injury especially by tearing —called also ACL (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.08.008.name: Posterior cruciate ligament
A03.6.08.008.definition: a cruciate ligament of each knee that is attached medially in back between the condyles of the tibia, that passes upward and forward through the middle of the knee crossing the anterior cruciate ligament to attach to the medial aspect of the femur, that functions to prevent hyperflexion of the knee and to keep the tibia from sliding backward in relation to the femur when the knee is flexed, and that is stronger and less subject to sports injury by tearing than the anterior cruciate ligament —called also PCL (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.08.013.name: Oblique popliteal ligament
A03.6.08.013.definition: a strong broad flat fibrous ligament that passes obliquely across and strengthens the posterior part of the knee and is derived especially from the tendon of the semimembranosus muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.08.014.name: Arcuate popliteal ligament
A03.6.08.014.definition: a triangular ligamentous band in the posterior part of the knee that passes medially downward from the lateral condyle of the femur to the area between the condyles of the tibia and to the head of the fibula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.08.015.name: Patellar ligament
A03.6.08.015.definition: the part of the tendon of the quadriceps that extends from the patella to the tibia (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ligamento anterlor de la cabeza del peroné
Ligamento posterior de la cabeza del peroné

A03.6.10.008.name: Lateral ligament
A03.6.10.008.definition: any of various ligaments (as the lateral collateral ligament of the knee) that are in a lateral position or that prevent lateral dislocation of a joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.10.203.name: Plantar calcaneonavicular ligament
A03.6.10.203.definition: an elastic ligament of the sole of the foot that connects the calcaneus and navicular bone and supports the head of the talus —called also spring ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.10.512.name: Calcaneonavicular ligament
A03.6.10.512.definition: an elastic ligament of the sole of the foot that connects the calcaneus and navicular bone and supports the head of the talus —called also spring ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.10.513.name: Calcaneocuboid ligament
A03.6.10.513.definition: either of two ligaments of the tarsus connecting the calcaneus and the cuboid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.10.802.name: Collateral ligaments
A03.6.10.802.definition: any of various ligaments on one or the other side of a hinge joint (as the knee, elbow, or the joints between the phalanges of the toes and fingers): as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A03.6.10.902.name: Collateral ligaments
A03.6.10.902.definition: any of various ligaments on one or the other side of a hinge joint (as the knee, elbow, or the joints between the phalanges of the toes and fingers): as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.000.name: Muscles
A04.0.00.000.definition: a body tissue consisting of long cells that contract when stimulated and produce motion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.001.name: Head
A04.0.00.001.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.003.name: Attachment
A04.0.00.003.definition: a strong emotional bond that an infant forms with a caregiver (such as a mother) especially when viewed as a basis for normal emotional and social development; also : the process by which an infant forms an attachment  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.021.name: Adductor muscle
A04.0.00.021.definition: a muscle of the foot that adducts and flexes the big toe and helps to support the arch of the foot —called also adductor hallucis muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.024.name: Extensor muscle
A04.0.00.024.definition: a muscle serving to extend a bodily part (as a limb) —called also extensor muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.030.name: Compartment
A04.0.00.030.definition: a painful condition resulting from the expansion or overgrowth of enclosed tissue (as of a leg muscle) within its anatomical enclosure (as a muscular sheath) producing pressure that interferes with circulation and adversely affects the function and health of the tissue itself —called also compartmental syndrome (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.031.name: Fascia
A04.0.00.031.definition: a sheet of connective tissue (as an aponeurosis) covering or binding together body structures; also : tissue occurring in such a sheet (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.041.name: Epimysium
A04.0.00.041.definition: the external connective-tissue sheath of a muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.042.name: Perimysium
A04.0.00.042.definition: the connective-tissue sheath that surrounds a muscle and forms sheaths for the bundles of muscle fibers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.043.name: Endomysium
A04.0.00.043.definition: the delicate connective tissue surrounding the individual muscular fibers within the smallest bundles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.044.name: Tendon
A04.0.00.044.definition: a tough cord or band of dense white fibrous connective tissue that unites a muscle with some other part, transmits the force which the muscle exerts, and is continuous with the connective-tissue epimysium and perimysium of the muscle and when inserted into a bone with the periosteum of the bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.047.name: Aponeurosis
A04.0.00.047.definition: any of the broad flat sheets of dense fibrous collagenous connective tissue that cover, invest, and form the terminations and attachments of various muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.0.00.048.name: Tendinous arch
A04.0.00.048.definition: a thickened arch of fascia which gives origin to muscles or ligaments or through which pass vessels or nerves; especially : a thickening in the pelvic fascia that gives attachment to supporting ligaments (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.01.001.name: Extra-ocular muscles
A04.1.01.001.definition: any of six small voluntary muscles that pass between the eyeball and the orbit and control the movement and stabilization of the eyeball in relation to the orbit —abbreviation EOM (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Músculos de los huesecillos de los huesos

A04.1.03.003.name: Occipitofrontalis
A04.1.03.003.definition: a fibrous and muscular sheet on each side of the vertex of the skull that extends from the eyebrow to the occiput, that is composed of the frontalis muscle in front and the occipitalis muscle in back with the galea aponeurotica in between, and that acts to draw back the scalp to raise the eyebrow and wrinkle the forehead —called also epicranius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.008.name: Procerus
A04.1.03.008.definition: a facial muscle that arises from the nasal bone and a cartilage in the side of the nose and that inserts into the skin of the forehead between the eyebrows (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.009.name: Nasalis
A04.1.03.009.definition: a small muscle on each side of the nose that constricts the nasal aperture by the action of a triangular transverse portion which draws the lateral part of the aperture upward and a quadrangular alar portion which draws it downward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.013.name: Orbicularis oculi
A04.1.03.013.definition: the muscle encircling the opening of the orbit and functioning to close the eyelids (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.020.name: Auricularis anterior
A04.1.03.020.definition: any of three muscles attaching the cartilage of the external ear to the skull:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.021.name: Auricularis superior
A04.1.03.021.definition: any of three muscles attaching the cartilage of the external ear to the skull:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.022.name: Auricularis posterior
A04.1.03.022.definition: any of three muscles attaching the cartilage of the external ear to the skull:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.023.name: Orbicularis oris
A04.1.03.023.definition: a muscle made up of several layers of fibers passing in different directions that encircles the mouth and controls most movements of the lips (as compressing, closing, or pursing movements) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Músculo depresor del ángulo de la boca

A04.1.03.028.name: Risorius
A04.1.03.028.definition: a narrow band of muscle fibers arising from the fascia over the masseter muscle, inserted into the tissues at the corner of the mouth, and acting to retract the angle of the mouth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.029.name: Zygomaticus major
A04.1.03.029.definition: a slender band of muscle on each side of the face that arises from the zygomatic bone, inserts into the orbicularis oris and skin at the corner of the mouth, and acts to pull the corner of the mouth upward and backward when smiling or laughing (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.030.name: Zygomaticus minor
A04.1.03.030.definition: a slender band of muscle on each side of the face that arises from the zygomatic bone, inserts into the upper lip between the zygomaticus major and the levator labii superioris, and acts to raise the upper lip upward and laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.031.name: Levator labii superioris
A04.1.03.031.definition: a facial muscle arising from the lower margin of the orbit and inserting into the muscular substance of the upper lip which it elevates —called also quadratus labii superioris (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.032.name: Levator labii superioris alaeque nasi

term_localized.la: M. levator labii superioris alaeque nasi
term_localized.es: Músculo elevador del labio superior y del ala de la nariz

A04.1.03.032.definition: a muscle that arises from the nasal process of the maxilla, that passes downward and laterally, that divides into a part inserting into the alar cartilage and one inserting into the upper lip, and that dilates the nostril and raises the upper lip (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.034.name: Levator anguli oris

term_localized.es: Músculo elevador del ángulo de la boca

A04.1.03.034.definition: a facial muscle that arises from the maxilla, inclines downward to be inserted into the corner of the mouth, and draws the lips up and back —called also caninus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.035.name: Modiolus

term_localized.es: Modiolo del ángulo de la boca

A04.1.03.035.definition: a central bony column in the cochlea of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.036.name: Buccinator
A04.1.03.036.definition: a thin broad muscle forming the wall of the cheek and serving to compress the cheek against the teeth and to retract the angle of the mouth —called also buccinator muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.03.037.name: Mentalis
A04.1.03.037.definition: a muscle that originates in the incisive fossa of the mandible, inserts in the skin of the chin, and raises the chin and pushes up the lower lip (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.04.002.name: Masseter
A04.1.04.002.definition: a large muscle that raises the lower jaw and assists in mastication, arises from the zygomatic arch and the zygomatic process of the temporal bone, and is inserted into the mandibular ramus and gonial angle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.04.005.name: Temporalis
A04.1.04.005.definition: a large muscle in the temporal fossa that serves to raise the lower jaw and is composed of fibers that arise from the surface of the temporal fossa and converge to an aponeurosis which contracts into a thick flat tendon inserted into the coronoid process of the mandible —called also temporalis muscle, temporal muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.04.013.name: Temporal fascia
A04.1.04.013.definition: a broad fascia covering the temporalis and attached below to the zygomatic arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.1.06.001.name: Muscles of soft palate and fauces

term_localized.en: Muscles of soft palate and fauces
term_localized.es: Músculos del paladar blando y de las fauces

A04.2.01.001.name: Platysma
A04.2.01.001.definition: a broad thin layer of muscle that is situated on each side of the neck immediately under the superficial fascia belonging to the group of facial muscles, that is innervated by the facial nerve, and that draws the lower lip and the corner of the mouth to the side and down and when moved forcefully expands the neck and draws its skin upward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Anterior rami of C2-C6 spinal nerves

A04.2.01.003.name: Longus capitis
A04.2.01.003.definition: a muscle of either side of the front and upper portion of the neck that arises from the third to sixth cervical vertebrae, is inserted into the basilar portion of the occipital bone, and bends the neck forward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Anterior rami of C1-C3 spinal nerves
Anterior rami of C3-C8 spinal nerves
Anterior rami of C7-C8 spinal nerves

A04.2.01.008.name: Sternocleidomastoid
A04.2.01.008.definition: a thick superficial muscle on each side that arises by one head from the first segment of the sternum and by a second from the inner part of the clavicle, that inserts into the mastoid process and occipital bone, and that acts especially to bend, rotate, flex, and extend the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Músculo recto anterior de la cabeza
Músculo recto lateral de la cabeza

nerves: Branches from loop between C1 and C2 spinal nerves

A04.2.02.004.name: Rectus capitis posterior major

term_localized.es: Músculo recto posterior mayor de la cabeza

A04.2.02.004.definition: a muscle on each side of the back of the neck that arises from the spinous process of the axis, inserts into the lateral aspect of the inferior nuchal line and the adjacent inferior area of the occipital bone, and acts to extend and rotate the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

origin: Posterior tubercle of posterior arch of vertebra C1
insertion: Lateral part of inferior nuchal line of occipital bone

A04.2.02.005.name: Rectus capitis posterior minor

term_localized.es: Músculo recto posterior menor de la cabeza

A04.2.02.005.definition: a muscle on each side of the back of the neck that arises from the posterior arch of the atlas, inserts especially into the medial aspect of the inferior nuchal line, and acts to extend the head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: Medial part of inferior nuchal line of occipital bone

term_localized.es: Músculo oblicuo menor de la cabeza

insertion: Occipital bone between superior and inferior nuchal lines

term_localized.es: Músculo oblicuo mayor de la cabeza

origin: Posterior tubercle of posterior arch of vertebra C2

A04.2.03.001.name: Suprahyoid muscles
A04.2.03.001.definition: any of several muscles (as the mylohyoid and geniohyoid) passing upward to the jaw and face from the hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.2.03.002.name: Digastric
A04.2.03.002.definition: having two bellies separated by a median tendon  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

arteries: Submental branch of the facial artery
nerves: Digastric (preparotid) branch of facial nerve (CN VII)

A04.2.03.006.name: Mylohyoid
A04.2.03.006.definition: of, indicating, or adjoining the mylohyoid muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.2.03.007.name: Geniohyoid
A04.2.03.007.definition: of or relating to the chin and hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.2.04.002.name: Sternohyoid
A04.2.04.002.definition: an infrahyoid muscle on each side of the midline that arises from the medial end of the clavicle and the first segment of the sternum, inserts into the body of the hyoid bone, and acts to depress the hyoid bone and the larynx (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

origin: Manubrium of sternum and medial end of clavicle

A04.2.04.003.name: Omohyoid
A04.2.04.003.definition: of or relating to the shoulder and the hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.2.04.006.name: Sternothyroid
A04.2.04.006.definition: an infrahyoid muscle on each side of the body below the sternohyoid that arises from the sternum and from the cartilage of the first and sometimes of the second ribs, inserts into the thyroid cartilage, and acts to draw the larynx downward by depressing the thyroid cartilage (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

origin: Posterior surface of manubrium of sternum

A04.2.04.007.name: Thyrohyoid
A04.2.04.007.definition: of, relating to, or supplying the thyrohyoid muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.2.05.003.name: Suprasternal space
A04.2.05.003.definition: a long narrow space in the lower part of the deep fascia of the cervical region containing areolar tissue, the sternal part of the sternocleidomastoid muscles, and the lower part of the anterior jugular veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ligamento suspensor de la glándula tiroidea

A04.3.01.001.name: Trapezius
A04.3.01.001.definition: a large flat triangular superficial muscle of each side of the upper back that arises from the occipital bone, the ligamentum nuchae, and the spinous processes of the last cervical and all the thoracic vertebrae, is inserted into the outer part of the clavicle, the acromion, and the spine of the scapula, and serves chiefly to rotate the scapula so as to present the glenoid cavity upward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

Descending part: Medial third of superior nuchal line
Spinous processes of cervical vertebrae/Nuchal ligament
Transverse part: Broad aponeurosis at spinous processes of vertebrae T1-T4 (or C7-T3)
Ascending part: Spinous processes of vertebrae T5-T12 (or T2-T12)

A04.3.01.006.name: Latissimus dorsi
A04.3.01.006.definition: a broad flat superficial muscle of the lower part of the back that originates mostly in a broad aponeurosis attached to the spinous processes of the vertebrae of the lower back, the supraspinal ligament, and the crest of the ilium, that is inserted into the bicipital groove of the humerus, and that extends, adducts, and rotates the arm medially and draws the shoulder downward and backward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.01.009.name: Levator scapulae
A04.3.01.009.definition: a back muscle that arises in the transverse processes of the first four cervical vertebrae and descends to insert into the vertebral border of the scapula which it elevates (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

origin: Posterior surface of the medial scapular border
insertion: Transverse process of the atlas and axis, posterior tubercles C3 and C4

nerves: Anterior rami of the nerves C3 and C4

A04.3.01.010.name: Serratus posterior inferior
A04.3.01.010.definition: a thin quadrilateral muscle at the junction of the thoracic and lumbar regions that arises chiefly from the spinous processes of the lowest two thoracic and first two or three lumbar vertebrae, is inserted into the lowest four ribs, and acts to counteract the pull of the diaphragm on the ribs to which it is attached (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.01.011.name: Serratus posterior superior
A04.3.01.011.definition: a thin quadrilateral muscle of the upper and dorsal part of the thorax that arises chiefly from the spinous processes of the lowest cervical and the first two or three thoracic vertebrae, is inserted into the second to fifth ribs, and acts to elevate the upper ribs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Aponeurosis del músculo erector de la columna

A04.3.02.005.name: Iliocostalis
A04.3.02.005.definition: the lateral division of the sacrospinalis muscle that helps to keep the trunk erect and consists of three parts:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Lateral branches of dorsal rami spinal nerves

A04.3.02.006.name: Iliocostalis lumborum
A04.3.02.006.definition: a muscle that extends from the ilium to the lower ribs and acts to draw the trunk to the same side or to depress the ribs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.009.name: Iliocostalis cervicis
A04.3.02.009.definition: a muscle that extends from the ribs to the cervical transverse processes and acts to draw the neck to the same side and to elevate the ribs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.010.name: Longissimus
A04.3.02.010.definition: the intermediate division of the sacrospinalis muscle that consists of the longissimus capitis, longissimus cervicis, and longissimus thoracis; also : any of these three muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Lateral branches of dorsal rami spinal nerves

A04.3.02.011.name: Longissimus thoracis
A04.3.02.011.definition: a muscle that arises as the middle and largest division of the sacrospinalis muscle, that is attached by some of its fibers to the lumbar vertebrae, that is inserted into all the thoracic vertebrae and the lower 9 or 10 ribs, and that depresses the ribs and with the longissimus cervicis extends the spinal column and bends it to one side —called also longissimus dorsi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.013.name: Longissimus cervicis
A04.3.02.013.definition: a slender muscle medial to the longissimus thoracis that arises by long thin tendons from the transverse processes of the upper four or five thoracic vertebrae, is inserted by similar tendons into the transverse processes of the second to sixth cervical vertebrae, and extends the spinal column and bends it to one side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.014.name: Longissimus capitis
A04.3.02.014.definition: a long slender muscle between the longissimus cervicis and the semispinalis capitis that arises by tendons from the upper thoracic and lower cervical vertebrae, is inserted into the posterior margin of the mastoid process, and extends the head and bends and rotates it to one side —called also trachelomastoid muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.015.name: Spinalis
A04.3.02.015.definition: the most medial division of the sacrospinalis situated next to the spinal column and acting to extend it or any of the three muscles making up this division:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Lateral branches of dorsal rami spinal nerves

A04.3.02.016.name: Spinalis thoracis
A04.3.02.016.definition: an upward continuation of the sacrospinalis that is situated medially to and blends with the longissimus thoracis, arises from the spinous processes of the first two lumbar and last two thoracic vertebrae, and inserts into the spinous processes of the upper thoracic vertebrae (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.017.name: Spinalis cervicis
A04.3.02.017.definition: an inconstant muscle that arises especially from the spinous processes of the lower cervical and upper thoracic vertebrae and inserts especially into the spinous process of the axis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.018.name: Spinalis capitis
A04.3.02.018.definition: a muscle that arises with, inserts with, and is intimately associated with the semispinalis capitis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.102.name: Splenius
A04.3.02.102.definition: either of two flat oblique muscles on each side of the back of the neck and upper thoracic region:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.103.name: Splenius capitis
A04.3.02.103.definition: a flat muscle on each side of the back of the neck and the upper thoracic region that arises from the caudal half of the ligamentum nuchae and the spinous processes of the seventh cervical and the first three or four thoracic vertebrae, that is inserted into the occipital bone and the mastoid process of the temporal bone, and that rotates the head to the side on which it is located and with the help of the muscle on the opposite side extends it (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: Superior nuchal line of occipital bone

A04.3.02.104.name: Splenius cervicis
A04.3.02.104.definition: a flat narrow muscle on each side of the back of the neck and the upper thoracic region that arises from the spinous processes of the third to sixth thoracic vertebrae, is inserted into the transverse processes of the first two or three cervical vertebrae, and acts to rotate the head to the side on which it is located and with the help of the muscle on the opposite side to extend and arch the neck (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Posterior rami of C6-C8 spinal nerves

A04.3.02.202.name: Multifidus
A04.3.02.202.definition: a muscle of the fifth and deepest layer of the back filling up the groove on each side of the spinous processes of the vertebrae from the sacrum to the skull and consisting of many fasciculi that pass upward and inward to the spinous processes and help to erect and rotate the spine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.206.name: Semispinalis
A04.3.02.206.definition: any of three muscles of the cervical and thoracic parts of the spinal column that arise from transverse processes of the vertebrae and pass to spinous processes higher up and that help to form a layer underneath the sacrospinalis muscle:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.207.name: Semispinalis thoracis
A04.3.02.207.definition: a deep longitudinal muscle of the back that arises from the transverse processes of the lower five thoracic vertebrae, is inserted into the spinous processes of the upper four thoracic and lower two cervical vertebrae, and with the semispinalis cervicis acts to extend the spinal column and rotate it toward the opposite side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.3.02.208.name: Semispinalis cervicis
A04.3.02.208.definition: a deep longitudinal muscle of the back that arises from the transverse processes of the upper five or six thoracic vertebrae, is inserted into the cervical spinous processes from the axis to the fifth cervical vertebra, and with the semispinalis thoracis acts to extend the spinal column and rotate it toward the opposite side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Medial branches of posterior rami of spinal nerves

A04.3.02.209.name: Semispinalis capitis
A04.3.02.209.definition: a deep longitudinal muscle of the back that arises especially from the transverse processes of the upper six or seven thoracic and the seventh cervical vertebrae, is inserted on the outer surface of the occipital bone between two ridges behind the foramen magnum, and acts to extend and rotate the head —called also complexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: Between superior and inferior nuchal lines of occipital bone

nerves: Descending branches of greater occipital nerve (C2)

A04.3.02.210.name: Rotatores
A04.3.02.210.definition: a muscle that partially rotates a part on its axis; specifically : any of several small muscles in the dorsal region of the spine arising from the upper and back part of a transverse process and inserted into the lamina of the vertebra above (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Dorsal rami of the spinal nerves

A04.3.02.301.name: Interspinales
A04.3.02.301.definition: any of various short muscles that have their origin on the superior surface of the spinous process of one vertebra and their insertion on the inferior surface of the contiguous vertebra above (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: Inferior border of spinous process above

A04.3.02.401.name: Intertransversarii
A04.3.02.401.definition: a series of small muscles connecting the transverse processes of contiguous vertebrae and most highly developed in the neck (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.01.001.name: (Sternalis)
A04.4.01.001.definition: a muscle that sometimes occurs on the surface of the pectoralis major at its sternal end and that has its fibers running parallel to the sternum and perpendicular to the pectoralis major (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.01.007.name: Subclavius
A04.4.01.007.definition: a small muscle on each side of the body that arises from the junction of the first rib and its cartilage, inserts into the inferior surface of the clavicle, and acts to stabilize the clavicle by depressing and drawing forward its lateral end during movements of the shoulder joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.01.008.name: Serratus anterior
A04.4.01.008.definition: a thin muscular sheet of the thorax that arises from the first eight or nine ribs and from the intercostal muscles between them, is inserted into the ventral side of the medial margin of the scapula, and acts to stabilize the scapula by holding it against the chest wall and to rotate it in raising the arm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.01.009.name: Levatores costarum
A04.4.01.009.definition: a series of 12 muscles on each side that arise from the transverse processes of the seventh cervical and upper 11 thoracic vertebrae, that pass obliquely downward and laterally to insert into the outer surface of the rib immediately below or in the case of the lowest four muscles of the series divide into two fasciculi of which one inserts as described and the other inserts into the second rib below, and that raise the ribs increasing the volume of the thoracic cavity and extend, bend, and rotate the spinal column (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Músculos elevadores largos de las costillas
Músculos elevadores cortos de las costillas

A04.4.01.012.name: External intercostal muscle
A04.4.01.012.definition: intercostal muscle —called also external intercostal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: External labia of superior border of rib below

A04.4.01.013.name: Internal intercostal muscle
A04.4.01.013.definition: intercostal muscle —called also internal intercostal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

insertion: Internal labia of superior border of rib below

A04.4.01.015.name: Subcostales
A04.4.01.015.definition: any of a variable number of small muscles that arise on the inner surface of a rib, are inserted into the inner surface of the second or third rib below, and probably function to draw adjacent ribs together (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.01.016.name: Transversus thoracis
A04.4.01.016.definition: a thin flat sheet of muscle and tendon fibers of the anterior wall of the chest that arises especially from the xiphoid process and lower third of the sternum, inserts into the costal cartilages of the second to sixth ribs, and acts to draw the ribs downward —called also transverse thoracic muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.001.name: Diaphragm
A04.4.02.001.definition: a body partition of muscle and connective tissue; specifically : the partition separating the chest and abdominal cavities in mammals  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.005.name: Median arcuate ligament
A04.4.02.005.definition: a tendinous arch that lies in front of the aorta and that connects the attachments of the lumbar portion of the diaphragm to the lumbar vertebrae on each side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.006.name: Medial arcuate ligament
A04.4.02.006.definition: an arched band of fascia that covers the upper part of the psoas major muscle, extends from the body of the first or second lumbar vertebra to the transverse process of the first and sometimes also the second lumbar vertebra, and provides attachment for part of the lumbar portion of the diaphragm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.007.name: Lateral arcuate ligament
A04.4.02.007.definition: a fascial band that is formed by part of the quadratus lumborum muscle, extends from the tip of the transverse process of the first lumbar vertebra to the twelfth rib, and provides attachment for part of the diaphragm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.010.name: Aortic hiatus
A04.4.02.010.definition: an opening in the diaphragm through which the aorta passes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.4.02.013.name: Central tendon
A04.4.02.013.definition: a 3-lobed aponeurosis located near the central portion of the diaphragm caudal to the pericardium and composed of intersecting planes of collagenous fibers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.001.name: Rectus abdominis
A04.5.01.001.definition: a long flat muscle on either side of the linea alba extending along the whole length of the front of the abdomen, arising from the pubic crest and symphysis, inserted into the cartilages of the fifth, sixth, and seventh ribs, and acting to flex the spinal column, tense the anterior wall of the abdomen, and assist in compressing the contents of the abdomen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Vaina de los músculos rectos abdominales

A04.5.01.007.name: Pyramidalis
A04.5.01.007.definition: a small triangular muscle of the lower front part of the abdomen that is situated in front of and in the same sheath with the rectus and functions to tense the linea alba (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.009.name: Inguinal ligament
A04.5.01.009.definition: the thickened lower border of the aponeurosis of the external oblique muscle of the abdomen that extends from the anterior superior iliac spine to the pubic tubercle, is continuous with the fascia lata near the thigh, and forms the external pillar of the superficial inguinal ring and a part of the anterior boundary of the femoral ring —called also Poupart's ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.013.name: Superficial inguinal ring
A04.5.01.013.definition: the inguinal ring that is the external opening of the inguinal canal —called also external inguinal ring (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.019.name: Transversus abdominis
A04.5.01.019.definition: a flat muscle with transverse fibers that forms the innermost layer of the anterolateral wall of the abdomen and ends in a broad aponeurosis which joins that of the opposite side at the linea alba with its upper three fourths passing behind the rectus abdominis muscle and the lower fourth in front of it and that acts to constrict the abdominal viscera and assist in expulsion of the contents of various abdominal organs (as in defecation, vomiting, and childbirth) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

nerves: Anterior rami of spinal nerves T7-L1

A04.5.01.021.name: Deep inguinal ring
A04.5.01.021.definition: the internal opening of the inguinal canal —called also internal inguinal ring (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.022.name: Linea alba
A04.5.01.022.definition: a median vertical tendinous line on the mammalian abdomen formed of fibers from the aponeuroses of the two rectus abdominis muscles and extending from the xiphoid process to the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.025.name: Linea semilunaris
A04.5.01.025.definition: a curved line on the ventral abdominal wall parallel to the midline and halfway between it and the side of the body that marks the lateral border of the rectus abdominis muscle —called also semilunar line (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.026.name: Inguinal canal
A04.5.01.026.definition: a passage about one and one half inches (4 centimeters) long that lies parallel to and a half inch above the inguinal ligament: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.01.027.name: Quadratus lumborum
A04.5.01.027.definition: a quadrilateral-shaped muscle of the abdomen that arises from the iliac crest and the iliolumbar ligament, inserts into the lowest rib and the upper four lumbar vertebrae, and functions especially to flex the trunk laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Fascia propia de los órganos intraperitoneales

A04.5.02.009.name: Iliac fascia
A04.5.02.009.definition: an aponeurotic layer lining the back part of the abdominal cavity and covering the inner surface of the psoas and iliacus muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.02.011.name: Transversalis fascia
A04.5.02.011.definition: the whole deep layer of fascia lining the abdominal wall; also : the part of this covering the inner surface of the transversus abdominis and separating it from the peritoneum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.03.001.name: Pelvic fascia
A04.5.03.001.definition: the fascia lining the pelvic cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Fascia propia de los órganos intraperitoneales
Fascia propia de los órganos extraperitoneales
Arco tendinoso de la fascia pelviana

A04.5.03.013.name: Pubovesical ligament
A04.5.03.013.definition: any of three strands of pelvic fascia in the female that correspond to the puboprostatic ligament in the male and that support the bladder passing from its neck to the pubic symphysis or to the pubis on one side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.04.001.name: Pelvic diaphragm
A04.5.04.001.definition: the muscular floor of the pelvis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.04.002.name: Levator ani
A04.5.04.002.definition: a broad thin muscle that is attached in a sheet to each side of the inner surface of the pelvis and descends to form the floor of the pelvic cavity where it supports the viscera and surrounds structures which pass through it and inserts into the sides of the apex of the coccyx, the margins of the anus, the side of the rectum, and the central tendinous point of the perineum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.04.003.name: Pubococcygeus
A04.5.04.003.definition: the inferior subdivision of the levator ani that arises from the dorsal surface of the pubis along a line extending from the lower part of the pubic symphysis to the obturator canal, that inserts especially into the coccyx, that acts to help support the pelvic viscera, to draw the lower end of the rectum toward the pubis, and to constrict the rectum and in the female the vagina, and that contains bands of fibers comprising the puborectalis, the levator prostatae in the male, and the pubovaginalis in the female (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.04.007.name: Puborectalis
A04.5.04.007.definition: a band of muscle fibers that is part of the pubococcygeus, that passes from the pubic symphysis to interdigitate with the contralateral band of fibers forming a sling around the rectum at its junction with the anal canal, and that acts to hold the rectum and anal canal at right angles to each other except during defecation (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.5.04.008.name: Iliococcygeus
A04.5.04.008.definition: a muscle of the pelvis that is a subdivision of the levator ani, has its origin at the pubic symphysis and the tendon which arches over the obturator internus, inserts on the coccyx and perineal body, and helps support the pelvic viscera (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: (Arco tendinoso del músculo elevador del ano)

A04.5.04.019.name: Attachment of superficial external anal sphincter

term_localized.en: Attachment of superficial external anal sphincter
term_localized.la: Insertio partis superficialis musculi sphincteris ani externi
term_localized.es: Inserción de la porción superficial del músculo esfínter externo del ano

A04.6.02.001.name: Muscles
A04.6.02.001.definition: a body tissue consisting of long cells that contract when stimulated and produce motion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.002.name: Deltoid
A04.6.02.002.definition: a large triangular muscle that covers the shoulder joint, serves to raise the arm laterally, arises from the upper anterior part of the outer third of the clavicle and from the acromion and spine of the scapula, and is inserted into the outer side of the middle of the shaft of the humerus —called also deltoid muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.006.name: Supraspinatus
A04.6.02.006.definition: a muscle of the back of the shoulder that arises from the supraspinous fossa of the scapula, that inserts into the top of the greater tubercle of the humerus, that is one of the muscles making up the rotator cuff of the shoulder, and that rotates the humerus laterally and helps to abduct the arm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.008.name: Infraspinatus
A04.6.02.008.definition: a muscle that occupies the chief part of the infraspinous fossa of the scapula, is inserted into the greater tubercle of the humerus, and rotates the arm laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.010.name: Teres minor
A04.6.02.010.definition: a long cylindrical muscle that arises from the upper two-thirds of the axillary border of the scapula, passes behind the long head of the triceps to insert chiefly on the greater tubercle of the humerus, contributes to the formation of the rotator cuff of the shoulder, and acts to rotate the arm laterally and draw the humerus toward the glenoid fossa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.011.name: Teres major
A04.6.02.011.definition: a thick somewhat flattened muscle that arises chiefly from the lower third of the axillary border of the scapula, passes in front of the long head of the triceps to insert on the medial border of the bicipital groove of the humerus, and functions in opposition to the muscles comprising the rotator cuff by extending the arm when it is in the flexed position and by rotating it medially (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.012.name: Subscapularis
A04.6.02.012.definition: a large triangular muscle that fills up the subscapular fossa, that arises from the surface of the scapula, that is inserted into the lesser tubercle of the humerus, and that stabilizes the shoulder joint as part of the rotator cuff and rotates the humerus medially when the arm is held by the side of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.013.name: Biceps brachii
A04.6.02.013.definition: a muscle having two heads: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.014.name: Long head
A04.6.02.014.definition: the longest of the three heads of the triceps muscle that arises from the infraglenoid tubercle of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.016.name: Bicipital aponeurosis
A04.6.02.016.definition: an aponeurosis that is given off as a broad medial expansion of the tendon of the biceps muscle at the elbow and that descends medially over the brachial artery to fuse with the deep fascia covering the origins of the flexor muscles of the forearm —called also lacertus fibrosus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.017.name: Coracobrachialis
A04.6.02.017.definition: a muscle extending between the coracoid process and the middle of the medial surface of the humerus —called also coracobrachialis muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.018.name: Brachialis
A04.6.02.018.definition: a flexor that lies in front of the lower part of the humerus whence it arises and is inserted into the ulna (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.020.name: Long head
A04.6.02.020.definition: the longest of the three heads of the triceps muscle that arises from the infraglenoid tubercle of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.023.name: Anconeus
A04.6.02.023.definition: a small triangular extensor muscle that is superficially situated behind and below the elbow and that extends the forearm —called also anconeus muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.025.name: Pronator teres
A04.6.02.025.definition: a muscle of the forearm arising from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the coronoid process of the ulna, inserting into the lateral surface of the middle third of the radius, and serving to pronate and flex the forearm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.028.name: Flexor carpi radialis
A04.6.02.028.definition: a superficial muscle of the palmar side of the forearm that flexes the hand and assists in abducting it (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.029.name: Palmaris longus
A04.6.02.029.definition: a superficial muscle of the forearm lying on the medial side of the flexor carpi radialis that arises especially from the medial epicondyle of the humerus, inserts especially into the palmar aponeurosis, and acts to flex the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.030.name: Flexor carpi ulnaris
A04.6.02.030.definition: a superficial muscle of the ulnar side of the forearm that flexes the hand and assists in adducting it (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.033.name: Flexor digitorum superficialis

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor superficial de los dedos

A04.6.02.033.definition: a superficial muscle of the palmar side of the forearm that flexes especially the second phalanges of the four fingers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.036.name: Flexor digitorum profundus

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor profundo de los dedos

A04.6.02.036.definition: a deep muscle of the ulnar side of the forearm that flexes especially the terminal phalanges of the four fingers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.037.name: Flexor pollicis longus
A04.6.02.037.definition: a muscle of the radial side of the forearm that flexes especially the second phalanx of the thumb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.038.name: Pronator quadratus
A04.6.02.038.definition: a deep muscle of the forearm passing transversely from the ulna to the radius and serving to pronate the forearm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.039.name: Brachioradialis
A04.6.02.039.definition: a flexor of the radial side of the forearm arising from the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserted into the styloid process of the radius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.040.name: Extensor carpi radialis longus

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor radial largo del carpo

A04.6.02.040.definition: a long muscle on the radial side of the back of the forearm that extends and abducts the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.041.name: Extensor carpi radialis brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor radial corto del carpo

A04.6.02.041.definition: a short muscle on the radial side of the back of the forearm that extends and may abduct the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.042.name: Extensor digitorum
A04.6.02.042.definition: a muscle on the dorsum of the foot that extends the toes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.044.name: Extensor digiti minimi
A04.6.02.044.definition: a slender muscle on the medial side of the extensor digitorum communis that extends the little finger (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.045.name: Extensor carpi ulnaris
A04.6.02.045.definition: a muscle on the ulnar side of the back of the forearm that extends and adducts the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.048.name: Supinator
A04.6.02.048.definition: a muscle that produces the motion of supination; specifically : a deeply situated muscle of the forearm that arises in two layers from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and adjacent parts of the ligaments and bones of the elbow and that passes over the head of the radius to insert into its neck and the lateral surface of its shaft (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.049.name: Abductor pollicis longus
A04.6.02.049.definition: a muscle of the forearm that abducts the thumb and wrist (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.050.name: Extensor pollicis brevis
A04.6.02.050.definition: a muscle that arises from the dorsal surface of the radius, extends the first phalanx of the thumb, and adducts the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.051.name: Extensor pollicis longus
A04.6.02.051.definition: a muscle that arises dorsolaterally from the middle part of the ulna, extends the second phalanx of the thumb, and abducts the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.052.name: Extensor indicis
A04.6.02.052.definition: a thin muscle that arises from the ulna in the more distal part of the forearm and extends the index finger (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.053.name: Palmaris brevis
A04.6.02.053.definition: a short transverse superficial muscle of the ulnar side of the palm of the hand that arises from the flexor retinaculum and palmar aponeurosis, inserts into the skin on the ulnar edge of the palm, and functions to tense and stabilize the palm (as in making a fist or catching a ball) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.054.name: Abductor pollicis brevis
A04.6.02.054.definition: a thin flat muscle of the hand that abducts the thumb at right angles to the plane of the palm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.055.name: Flexor pollicis brevis
A04.6.02.055.definition: a short muscle of the palm that flexes and adducts the thumb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.058.name: Opponens pollicis
A04.6.02.058.definition: a small triangular muscle of the hand that is located below the abductor pollicis brevis, arises from the trapezium and the flexor retinaculum of the hand, is inserted along the radial side of the metacarpal of the thumb, and functions to abduct, flex, and rotate the metacarpal of the thumb in opposing the thumb and fingers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.059.name: Adductor pollicis
A04.6.02.059.definition: a muscle of the hand with two heads that adducts the thumb by bringing it toward the palm —called also adductor pollicis muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.062.name: Abductor digiti minimi
A04.6.02.062.definition: a muscle of the hand that abducts the little finger and flexes the phalanx nearest the hand  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.063.name: Flexor digiti minimi brevis
A04.6.02.063.definition: a muscle of the ulnar side of the palm of the hand that flexes the little finger  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.02.064.name: Opponens digiti minimi
A04.6.02.064.definition: a triangular muscle of the hand that arises from the hamate and adjacent flexor retinaculum, is inserted along the ulnar side of the metacarpal of the little finger, and functions to abduct, flex, and rotate the fifth metacarpal in opposing the little finger and thumb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.03.001.name: Fascia
A04.6.03.001.definition: a sheet of connective tissue (as an aponeurosis) covering or binding together body structures; also : tissue occurring in such a sheet (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.03.010.name: Extensor retinaculum
A04.6.03.010.definition: either of two fibrous bands of fascia crossing the front of the ankle:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.03.011.name: Superficial transverse metacarpal ligament
A04.6.03.011.definition: a transverse ligamentous band across the palm of the hand in the superficial fascia at the base of the fingers —called also superficial transverse ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.03.012.name: Palmar aponeurosis
A04.6.03.012.definition: an aponeurosis of the palm of the hand that consists of a superficial longitudinal layer continuous with the tendon of the palmaris longus and of a deeper transverse layer —called also palmar fascia (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.6.03.013.name: Flexor retinaculum
A04.6.03.013.definition: a fibrous band of fascia on the medial side of the ankle that extends downward from the medial malleolus of the tibia to the calcaneus and that covers over the bony grooves containing the tendons of the flexor muscles, the posterior tibial artery and vein, and the tibial nerve as they pass into the sole of the foot  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.001.name: Muscles
A04.7.02.001.definition: a body tissue consisting of long cells that contract when stimulated and produce motion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.002.name: Iliopsoas
A04.7.02.002.definition: a muscle consisting of the iliacus and psoas major muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.003.name: Iliacus
A04.7.02.003.definition: a muscle of the iliac region of the abdomen that flexes the thigh or bends the pelvis and lumbar region forward, has its origin from the iliac fossa, iliac crest, the base of the sacrum, and adjoining parts, and is inserted into the outer side of the tendon of the psoas major, the capsule of the hip joint, and the lesser trochanter of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.004.name: Psoas major
A04.7.02.004.definition: the larger of the two psoas muscles that arises from the anterolateral surfaces of the lumbar vertebrae, passes beneath the inguinal ligament to insert with the iliacus into the lesser trochanter of the femur, and serves especially to flex the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.005.name: (Psoas minor)
A04.7.02.005.definition: the smaller of the two psoas muscles that arises from the last dorsal and first lumbar vertebrae and inserts into the brim of the pelvis, that functions to flex the trunk and the lumbar spinal column, and that is often absent (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.006.name: Gluteus maximus
A04.7.02.006.definition: the outermost of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the sacrum, coccyx, back part of the ilium and adjacent structures, that is inserted into the fascia lata of the thigh and the gluteal tuberosity of the femur, and that acts to extend and laterally rotate the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.007.name: Gluteus medius
A04.7.02.007.definition: the middle of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the outer surface of the ilium, that is inserted into the greater trochanter of the femur, and that acts to abduct and medially rotate the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.008.name: Gluteus minimus
A04.7.02.008.definition: the innermost of the three muscles in each buttock that arises from the outer surface of the ilium, that is inserted into the greater trochanter of the femur, and that acts similarly to the gluteus medius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.010.name: Tensor fasciae latae

term_localized.es: Músculo tensor de la fascia lata

A04.7.02.010.definition: a muscle that arises especially from the anterior part of the iliac crest and from the anterior superior iliac spine, is inserted into the iliotibial band of the fascia lata about one third of the way down the thigh, and acts to flex and abduct the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.011.name: Piriformis
A04.7.02.011.definition: a muscle that arises from the front of the sacrum, passes out of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, is inserted into the upper border of the greater trochanter of the femur, and rotates the thigh laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.012.name: Obturator internus
A04.7.02.012.definition: a muscle that arises from the margin of the obturator foramen and from the obturator membrane, that inserts into the greater trochanter of the femur by way of tendons passing through the greater sciatic foramen, and that acts to rotate the thigh laterally when it is extended and to abduct it in the flexed position (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.013.name: Gemellus superior
A04.7.02.013.definition: either of two small muscles of the hip that insert into the tendon of the obturator internus:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.014.name: Gemellus inferior
A04.7.02.014.definition: either of two small muscles of the hip that insert into the tendon of the obturator internus:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.015.name: Quadratus femoris
A04.7.02.015.definition: a small flat muscle of the gluteal region that arises from the ischial tuberosity, inserts into the greater trochanter and adjacent region of the femur, and serves to rotate the thigh laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.016.name: Sartorius
A04.7.02.016.definition: a muscle that arises from the anterior superior iliac spine, crosses the front of the thigh obliquely to insert on the upper part of the inner surface of the tibia, is the longest muscle in the human body, and acts to flex, abduct, and rotate the thigh laterally at the hip joint and to flex the leg at the knee joint and to rotate it medially in a way that enables one to sit with the heel of one leg on the knee of the opposite leg (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.018.name: Rectus femoris
A04.7.02.018.definition: a division of the quadriceps muscle lying in the anterior middle region of the thigh, arising from the ilium by two heads, inserted into the tuberosity of the tibia by a narrow flattened tendon, and acting to flex the thigh at the hip and with the rest of the quadriceps to extend the leg at the knee (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.021.name: Vastus lateralis
A04.7.02.021.definition: the division of the quadriceps muscle that covers the outer anterior aspect of the femur, arises chiefly from the femur, and inserts into the outer border of the patella by a flat tendon which blends with that of the other divisions of the muscle and sends an expansion to the capsule of the knee —called also vastus externus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.022.name: Vastus intermedius
A04.7.02.022.definition: the division of the quadriceps muscle that arises from and covers the front of the shaft of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.023.name: Vastus medialis
A04.7.02.023.definition: the division of the quadriceps muscle that covers the inner anterior aspect of the femur, arises chiefly from the femur and the adjacent intermuscular septum, inserts into the inner border of the patella and into the tendon of the other divisions of the muscle, sends also a tendinous expansion to the capsule of the knee joint, and is closely and in the upper part often inseparably united with the vastus intermedius —called also vastus internus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.025.name: Pectineus
A04.7.02.025.definition: a flat quadrangular muscle of the upper front and inner aspect of the thigh that arises mostly from the iliopectineal line of the pubis and is inserted along the pectineal line of the femur (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.030.name: Gracilis
A04.7.02.030.definition: the most superficial muscle of the inside of the thigh that arises from the lower part of the pubic symphysis and the anterior half of the pubic arch and that has its tendon inserted into the inner surface of the shaft of the tibia below the tuberosity, and that acts to adduct the thigh and to flex the leg at the knee and to assist in rotating it medially (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.031.name: Obturator externus
A04.7.02.031.definition: a flat triangular muscle that arises especially from the medial side of the obturator foramen made up of the rami of the pubis and ischium and from the medial part of the obturator membrane, that inserts by a tendon into the trochanteric fossa of the femur, and that acts to rotate the thigh laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.032.name: Biceps femoris
A04.7.02.032.definition: a muscle having two heads: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.033.name: Long head
A04.7.02.033.definition: the longest of the three heads of the triceps muscle that arises from the infraglenoid tubercle of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.035.name: Semitendinosus
A04.7.02.035.definition: a fusiform muscle of the posterior and inner part of the thigh that arises from the ischial tuberosity along with the biceps femoris, that is inserted by a long round tendon which forms part of the inner hamstring into the inner surface of the upper part of the shaft of the tibia, and that acts to flex the leg and rotate it medially and to extend the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.036.name: Semimembranosus
A04.7.02.036.definition: a large muscle of the inner part and back of the thigh that arises by a thick tendon from the back part of the tuberosity of the ischium, is inserted into the medial condyle of the tibia, and acts to flex the leg and rotate it medially and to extend the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.038.name: Extensor digitorum longus

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor largo de los dedos

A04.7.02.038.definition: a pennate muscle on the lateral part of the front of the leg that extends the four small toes and dorsally flexes and pronates the foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.040.name: Extensor hallucis longus

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor largo del dedo gordoh

A04.7.02.040.definition: a long thin muscle situated on the shin that extends the big toe and dorsiflexes and supinates the foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.044.name: Gastrocnemius
A04.7.02.044.definition: the largest and most superficial muscle of the calf of the leg that arises by two heads from the condyles of the femur and has its tendon of insertion incorporated as part of the Achilles tendon —called also gastrocnemius muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.047.name: Soleus
A04.7.02.047.definition: a broad flat muscle of the calf of the leg that lies deep to the gastrocnemius, arises from the back and upper part of the tibia and fibula and from a tendinous arch between them, inserts by a tendon that unites with that of the gastrocnemius to form the Achilles tendon, and acts to flex the foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.049.name: Plantaris
A04.7.02.049.definition: a small muscle of the calf of the leg that arises from the lower end of the femur and the posterior ligament of the knee joint, is inserted with the Achilles tendon by a very long slender tendon into the calcaneus, and weakly flexes the leg at the knee and the foot at the ankle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.050.name: Popliteus
A04.7.02.050.definition: a flat muscle that originates from the lateral condyle of the femur, forms part of the floor of the popliteal space, and functions to flex the leg and rotate the femur medially (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.052.name: Flexor digitorum longus

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor largo de los dedos

A04.7.02.052.definition: a muscle of the tibial side of the leg that flexes the terminal phalanx of each of the four small toes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.053.name: Flexor hallucis longus

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor largo del dedo gordo

A04.7.02.053.definition: a long deep muscle of the fibular side of the leg that flexes especially the second phalanx of the big toe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.054.name: Extensor hallucis brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor corto del dedo gordo

A04.7.02.054.definition: the part of the extensor digitorum brevis that extends the big toe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.055.name: Extensor digitorum brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo extensor corto de los dedos

A04.7.02.055.definition: a muscle on the dorsum of the foot that extends the toes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.056.name: Abductor hallucis
A04.7.02.056.definition: a muscle of the foot that abducts the big toe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.057.name: Flexor hallucis brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor corto del dedo gordo

A04.7.02.057.definition: a short muscle of the sole of the foot that flexes the proximal phalanx of the big toe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.060.name: Adductor hallucis
A04.7.02.060.definition: a muscle of the foot that adducts and flexes the big toe and helps to support the arch of the foot —called also adductor hallucis muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.063.name: Abductor digiti minimi
A04.7.02.063.definition: a muscle of the hand that abducts the little finger and flexes the phalanx nearest the hand  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.065.name: (Opponens digiti minimi)
A04.7.02.065.definition: a triangular muscle of the hand that arises from the hamate and adjacent flexor retinaculum, is inserted along the ulnar side of the metacarpal of the little finger, and functions to abduct, flex, and rotate the fifth metacarpal in opposing the little finger and thumb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.066.name: Flexor digiti minimi brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor corto del quinto dedo

A04.7.02.066.definition: a muscle of the ulnar side of the palm of the hand that flexes the little finger  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.067.name: Flexor digitorum brevis

term_localized.es: Músculo flexor corto de los dedos

A04.7.02.067.definition: a muscle of the middle part of the sole of the foot that flexes the second phalanx of each of the four small toes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.02.068.name: Quadratus plantae
A04.7.02.068.definition: a muscle of the sole of the foot that arises by two heads from the calcaneus, inserts into the lateral side of the tendons of the flexor digitorum longus, and aids in flexing the toes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.001.name: Fascia
A04.7.03.001.definition: a sheet of connective tissue (as an aponeurosis) covering or binding together body structures; also : tissue occurring in such a sheet (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.002.name: Fascia lata
A04.7.03.002.definition: the deep fascia that forms a complete sheath for the thigh and has an opening in front just below the inguinal ligament for the passage of the great saphenous vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.003.name: Iliotibial tract
A04.7.03.003.definition: a fibrous thickening of the fascia lata that extends from the iliac crest down the lateral part of the thigh to the lateral condyle of the tibia and that provides stability to the knee and assists with flexion and extension of the knee —called also iliotibial tract, IT band (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.009.name: Iliac fascia
A04.7.03.009.definition: an aponeurotic layer lining the back part of the abdominal cavity and covering the inner surface of the psoas and iliacus muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.012.name: Femoral canal
A04.7.03.012.definition: the space that is situated between the femoral vein and the inner wall of the femoral sheath, is from a quarter to half an inch (6 to 13 millimeters) long, and extends from the femoral ring to the saphenous opening (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.013.name: Femoral triangle
A04.7.03.013.definition: an area in the upper anterior part of the thigh bounded by the inguinal ligament, the sartorius, and the adductor longus —called also femoral trigone, Scarpa's triangle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.014.name: Femoral ring
A04.7.03.014.definition: the oval upper opening of the femoral canal often the seat of a hernia (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.016.name: Saphenous opening
A04.7.03.016.definition: a passage for the great saphenous vein in the fascia lata of the thigh —called also fossa ovalis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.019.name: Inferior horn
A04.7.03.019.definition: the cornu in the lateral ventricle of each cerebral hemisphere that curves downward into the temporal lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.7.03.020.name: Cribriform fascia
A04.7.03.020.definition: the perforated fascia covering the saphenous opening in the fascia lata of the thigh and giving passage to various blood and lymph vessels (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Tabique intermuscular anterior de la pierna
Tabique intermuscular posterior de la pierna

A04.7.03.026.name: Flexor retinaculum
A04.7.03.026.definition: a fibrous band of fascia on the medial side of the ankle that extends downward from the medial malleolus of the tibia to the calcaneus and that covers over the bony grooves containing the tendons of the flexor muscles, the posterior tibial artery and vein, and the tibial nerve as they pass into the sole of the foot  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Retináculo superior de los músculos fibulares
Retináculo inferior de los músculos fibulares

A04.8.01.001.name: Subcutaneous bursa
A04.8.01.001.definition: a bursa lying between the skin and a bony process (as the olecranon of the elbow) or a ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.8.01.005.name: Tendon sheath
A04.8.01.005.definition: a synovial sheath covering a tendon (as in the hand or foot) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.8.01.008.name: Mesotendon
A04.8.01.008.definition: a fold of synovial membrane connecting a tendon to its synovial sheath (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

Bolsa subcutánea de la prominencia laríngea

A04.8.03.004.name: Subacromial bursa
A04.8.03.004.definition: a bursa lying between the acromion and the capsule of the shoulder joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A04.8.03.005.name: Subdeltoid bursa
A04.8.03.005.definition: the bursa that lies beneath the deltoid muscle and separates it from the capsule of the shoulder joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.00.001.name: Mouth
A05.1.00.001.definition: the natural opening through which food passes into the animal body and which in vertebrates is typically bounded externally by the lips and internally by the pharynx and encloses the tongue, gums, and teeth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.001.name: Oral cavity
A05.1.01.001.definition: the cavity of the mouth; especially : the part of the mouth behind the gums and teeth that is bounded above by the hard and soft palates and below by the tongue and by the mucous membrane connecting it with the inner part of the mandible (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.005.name: Lips
A05.1.01.005.definition: either of the two fleshy folds which surround the opening of the mouth in humans and many other vertebrates and in humans are organs of speech essential to certain articulations; also : the pinkish or reddish margin of a human lip composed of nonglandular mucous membrane and usually exposed when the mouth takes on its natural set  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.007.name: Philtrum
A05.1.01.007.definition: the vertical groove on the median line of the upper lip (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.008.name: Tubercle
A05.1.01.008.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.014.name: Cheek
A05.1.01.014.definition: the fleshy side of the face below the eye and above and to the side of the mouth; broadly : the lateral aspect of the head  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.102.name: Palate
A05.1.01.102.definition: the roof of the mouth separating the mouth from the nasal cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.103.name: Hard palate
A05.1.01.103.definition: the bony anterior part of the palate forming the roof of the mouth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.104.name: Soft palate
A05.1.01.104.definition: the membranous and muscular fold suspended from the posterior margin of the hard palate and partially separating the mouth cavity from the pharynx (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.01.107.name: Incisive papilla
A05.1.01.107.definition: a small fold of mucous membrane situated at the anterior end of the raphe of the hard palate near the openings of the incisive canals (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.003.name: Parotid gland
A05.1.02.003.definition: a salivary gland that is situated on each side of the face below and in front of the ear, in humans is the largest of the salivary glands, is of pure serous type, and communicates with the mouth by the parotid duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.007.name: Parotid duct
A05.1.02.007.definition: the duct of the parotid gland opening on the inner surface of the cheek opposite the second upper molar tooth —called also Stensen's duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.008.name: Sublingual gland
A05.1.02.008.definition: a small salivary gland on each side of the mouth lying beneath the mucous membrane in a fossa in the mandible near the symphysis —called also sublingual salivary gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.011.name: Submandibular gland
A05.1.02.011.definition: a salivary gland inside of and near the lower edge of the mandible on each side and discharging by Wharton's duct into the mouth under the tongue —called also mandibular gland, submandibular salivary gland, submaxillary gland, submaxillary salivary gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.014.name: Labial glands
A05.1.02.014.definition: one of the small tubular mucous and serous glands lying beneath the mucous membrane of the lips (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.015.name: Buccal glands
A05.1.02.015.definition: any of the small racemose mucous glands in the mucous membrane lining the cheeks (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.017.name: Palatine glands
A05.1.02.017.definition: any of numerous small mucous glands in the palate opening into the mouth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.02.018.name: Lingual glands
A05.1.02.018.definition: either of two mucus-secreting glands of the tip of the tongue of which one is located on each side of the frenulum on the underside of the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.001.name: Teeth
A05.1.03.001.definition: any of the hard bony appendages that are borne on the jaws and serve especially for the prehension and mastication of food (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.009.name: Crown
A05.1.03.009.definition: the topmost part of the skull or head  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.010.name: Cusp
A05.1.03.010.definition: a point on the grinding surface of a tooth  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.013.name: Tubercle
A05.1.03.013.definition: a small knobby prominence or excrescence: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.015.name: Triangular ridge
A05.1.03.015.definition: a triangular surface that slopes downward from the tip of a cusp of a molar or premolar toward the center of its occlusal surface (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.029.name: Clinical crown
A05.1.03.029.definition: the part of a tooth that projects above the gums (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.030.name: Neck
A05.1.03.030.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.031.name: Root
A05.1.03.031.definition: the usually underground part of a seed plant body that functions as an organ of absorption, aeration, and food storage or as a means of anchorage and support and that differs from a stem especially in lacking nodes, buds, and leaves  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.044.name: Cingulum
A05.1.03.044.definition: a ridge about the base of the crown of a tooth  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.047.name: Pulp cavity
A05.1.03.047.definition: the central cavity of a tooth containing the dental pulp and being made up of the root canal and the pulp chamber (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.049.name: Root canal
A05.1.03.049.definition: the part of the pulp cavity lying in the root of a tooth —called also pulp canal  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.050.name: Apical foramen
A05.1.03.050.definition: the opening of the pulp canal in the root of a tooth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.051.name: Dental pulp
A05.1.03.051.definition: the highly vascular sensitive tissue occupying the central cavity of a tooth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.054.name: Dental papilla
A05.1.03.054.definition: the mass of mesenchyme that occupies the cavity of each enamel organ and gives rise to the dentin and the pulp of the tooth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.055.name: Dentine
A05.1.03.055.definition: a calcareous material similar to bone but harder and denser that composes the principal mass of a tooth, is formed by the odontoblasts of the surface of the dental papilla, and consists of a matrix containing minute parallel tubules which open into the pulp cavity and during life contain processes of the cells of the pulp (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.056.name: Enamel
A05.1.03.056.definition: the intensely hard calcareous substance that forms a thin layer partly covering the teeth of many vertebrates including humans, is the hardest substance of the animal body, and consists of minute prisms secreted by ameloblasts, arranged at right angles to the surface, and bound together by a cement substance (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.058.name: Periodontium
A05.1.03.058.definition: the supporting structures of the teeth including the cementum, the periodontal ligament, the bone of the alveolar process, and the gums (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.061.name: Canine fossa
A05.1.03.061.definition: a depression external to and somewhat above the prominence on the surface of the superior maxillary bone caused by the socket of the canine tooth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.077.name: Permanent teeth
A05.1.03.077.definition: one of the second set of teeth of a mammal that follow the milk teeth, typically persist into old age, and in humans are 32 in number including 4 incisors, 2 canines, and 10 premolars and molars in each jaw (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.03.078.name: (Diastema)
A05.1.03.078.definition: a space between teeth in a jaw (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.001.name: Tongue
A05.1.04.001.definition: a process of the floor of the mouth that is attached basally to the hyoid bone, that consists essentially of a mass of extrinsic muscle attaching its base to other parts, intrinsic muscle by which parts of the structure move in relation to each other, and an epithelial covering rich in sensory end organs and small glands, and that functions especially in taking and swallowing food and as a speech organ (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.021.name: (Thyroglossal duct)
A05.1.04.021.definition: a temporary duct connecting the embryonic thyroid gland and the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.022.name: Lingual tonsil
A05.1.04.022.definition: a variable mass or group of small nodules of lymphoid tissue lying at the base of the tongue just anterior to the epiglottis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.101.name: Genioglossus
A05.1.04.101.definition: a fan-shaped muscle that arises from the superior mental spine, inserts on the hyoid bone and into the tongue, and serves to advance and retract and also to depress the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.102.name: Hyoglossus
A05.1.04.102.definition: a flat muscle on each side of the tongue connecting it with the body and the thyrohyal of the hyoid bone —called also hyoglossus muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.103.name: Chondroglossus
A05.1.04.103.definition: a muscle arising from the lesser cornu of the hyoid bone and blending with the intrinsic muscles of the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.105.name: Styloglossus
A05.1.04.105.definition: a muscle that arises from the styloid process of the temporal bone, inserts along the side and underpart of the tongue, and functions to draw the tongue upwards (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.1.04.110.name: Palatoglossus
A05.1.04.110.definition: a thin muscle that arises from the soft palate on each side, contributes to the structure of the palatoglossal arch, and is inserted into the side and dorsum of the tongue —called also glossopalatinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.001.name: Fauces
