A05.2.01.001.definition: the narrow passage from the mouth to the pharynx situated between the soft palate and the base of the tongue —called also isthmus of the fauces (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.002.name: (Isthmus of fauces)
A05.2.01.002.definition: the narrow passage from the mouth to the pharynx situated between the soft palate and the base of the tongue —called also isthmus of the fauces (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.003.name: Soft palate
A05.2.01.003.definition: the membranous and muscular fold suspended from the posterior margin of the hard palate and partially separating the mouth cavity from the pharynx (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.004.name: Uvula
A05.2.01.004.definition: the pendent fleshy lobe in the middle of the posterior border of the soft palate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.005.name: Palatoglossal arch
A05.2.01.005.definition: the more anterior of the two ridges of soft tissue at the back of the mouth on each side that curves downward from the uvula to the side of the base of the tongue forming a recess for the palatine tonsil as it diverges from the palatopharyngeal arch and that is composed of part of the palatoglossus with its covering of mucous membrane —called also anterior pillar of the fauces, glossopalatine arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.008.name: (Semilunar fold)
A05.2.01.008.definition: a small fold of membrane in the inner corner of the eye that is a vestige of a nictitating membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.101.name: Palatine aponeurosis
A05.2.01.101.definition: a thin fibrous lamella attached to the posterior part of the hard palate that supports the soft palate, includes the tendon of the tensor veli palatini, and supports the other muscles of the palate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.102.name: Levator veli palatini

term_localized.es: Músculo elevador del velo del paladar

A05.2.01.102.definition: a muscle arising from the temporal bone and the cartilage of the eustachian tube and descending to insert into the midline of the soft palate which it elevates especially to close the nasopharynx while swallowing is taking place to prevent regurgitation of liquid or solid matter through the nose (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.103.name: Tensor veli palatini

term_localized.es: Músculo tensor del velo del paladar

A05.2.01.103.definition: a ribbonlike muscle of the palate that arises from the scaphoid fossa, from the spine of the sphenoid bone, and from the lateral cartilaginous wall of the eustachian tube, that is attached by a tendon which hooks around the pterygoid plate of the sphenoid bone to insert especially into the soft palate, and that acts especially to tense the soft palate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.2.01.105.name: Palatopharyngeus
A05.2.01.105.definition: a longitudinal muscle of the pharynx that arises from the soft palate, contributes to the structure of the palatopharyngeal arch, and is inserted into the thyroid cartilage and the wall of the pharynx —called also pharyngopalatinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.001.name: Pharynx
A05.3.01.001.definition: the part of the digestive and respiratory tracts situated between the cavity of the mouth and the esophagus and in humans being a conical musculomembranous tube about four and a half inches (11.43 centimeters) long that is continuous above with the mouth and nasal passages, communicates through the eustachian tubes with the ears, and extends downward past the opening into the larynx to the lower border of the cricoid cartilage where it is continuous with the esophagus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.003.name: Nasopharynx
A05.3.01.003.definition: the upper part of the pharynx continuous with the nasal passages (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.006.name: Pharyngeal tonsil
A05.3.01.006.definition: a mass of lymphoid tissue at the back of the pharynx between the eustachian tubes that is usually best developed in young children, is commonly atrophied in the adult, and is markedly subject to hypertrophy and adenoid formation especially in children —called also nasopharyngeal tonsil (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.010.name: (Pharyngeal bursa)
A05.3.01.010.definition: a crypt in the pharyngeal tonsil that represents a communication existing during fetal life between the pharynx and the tip of the notochord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Orificio faríngeo de la trompa auditiva

A05.3.01.012.name: Torus tubarius
A05.3.01.012.definition: a protrusion on the lateral wall of the nasopharynx marking the pharyngeal end of the cartilaginous part of the eustachian tube (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.019.name: Oropharynx
A05.3.01.019.definition: the part of the pharynx that is below the soft palate and above the epiglottis and is continuous with the mouth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.023.name: Laryngopharynx
A05.3.01.023.definition: the lower part of the pharynx lying behind or adjacent to the larynx (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.028.name: Submucosa
A05.3.01.028.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.029.name: Mucosa
A05.3.01.029.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.102.name: Pterygomandibular raphe
A05.3.01.102.definition: a fibrous seam that descends from the pterygoid hamulus of the medial pterygoid plate to the mylohyoid line of the mandible and that separates and gives rise to the superior constrictor of the pharynx and the buccinator (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.103.name: Superior constrictor

term_localized.es: Músculo constrictor superior de la faringe

A05.3.01.103.definition: a 4-sided muscle of the pharynx that arises from the posterior and medial parts of the pterygoid plate, from the pterygomandibular raphe, from the alveolar process above the end of the mylohyoid line, and from the side of the tongue, that inserts into the median line at the back of the pharynx, and that acts to constrict part of the pharynx in swallowing —called also constrictor pharyngis superior, superior pharyngeal constrictor muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.108.name: Middle constrictor

term_localized.es: Músculo constrictor medío de la farínge

A05.3.01.108.definition: a fan-shaped muscle of the pharynx that arises from the ceratohyal and thyrohyal of the hyoid bone and from the stylohyoid ligament, inserts into the median line at the back of the pharynx, and acts to constrict part of the pharynx in swallowing —called also constrictor pharyngis medius, middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.111.name: Inferior constrictor

term_localized.es: Músculo constrictor ínferíor de la farínge

A05.3.01.111.definition: a muscle of the pharynx that is the thickest of its three constrictors, arises from the surface and side of the cricoid and thyroid cartilages, inserts into the median line at the back of the pharynx, and acts to constrict part of the pharynx in swallowing —called also constrictor pharyngis inferior, inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.114.name: Stylopharyngeus
A05.3.01.114.definition: a slender muscle that arises from the base of the styloid process of the temporal bone, inserts into the side of the pharynx, and acts with the contralateral muscle in swallowing to increase the transverse diameter of the pharynx by drawing its sides upward and laterally (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.115.name: Salpingopharyngeus
A05.3.01.115.definition: a muscle of the pharynx that arises from the inferior part of the eustachian tube near its opening and passes downward to join the posterior part of the palatopharyngeus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.3.01.119.name: Parapharyngeal space
A05.3.01.119.definition: a space bounded medially by the superior constrictor of the pharynx, laterally by the medial pterygoid muscle, posteriorly by the cervical vertebrae, and below by the muscles arising from the styloid process (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.4.01.001.name: Oesophagus
A05.4.01.001.definition: a muscular tube that in adult humans is about nine inches (23 centimeters) long and passes from the pharynx down the neck between the trachea and the spinal column and behind the left bronchus where it pierces the diaphragm slightly to the left of the middle line and joins the cardiac end of the stomach (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.4.01.007.name: Serosa
A05.4.01.007.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.4.01.009.name: Adventitia
A05.4.01.009.definition: the outer layer that makes up a tubular organ or structure and especially a blood vessel, is composed of collagenous and elastic fibers, and is not covered with peritoneum —called also tunica adventitia, tunica externa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.4.01.014.name: Submucosa
A05.4.01.014.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.4.01.015.name: Mucosa
A05.4.01.015.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.001.name: Stomach
A05.5.01.001.definition: a saclike expansion of the digestive tract of a vertebrate communicating anteriorly with the esophagus and posteriorly with the duodenum and being typically a simple often curved sac with an outer serous coat, a strong complex muscular wall that contracts rhythmically, and a mucous lining membrane that contains gastric glands  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.004.name: Greater curvature
A05.5.01.004.definition: the boundary of the stomach that forms a long usually convex curve on the left from the opening for the esophagus to the opening into the duodenum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.005.name: Lesser curvature
A05.5.01.005.definition: the boundary of the stomach that in humans forms a relatively short concave curve on the right from the opening for the esophagus to the opening into the duodenum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.007.name: Cardia
A05.5.01.007.definition: the opening of the esophagus into the stomach  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.017.name: Pylorus
A05.5.01.017.definition: the opening from the vertebrate stomach into the intestine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.019.name: Serosa
A05.5.01.019.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.024.name: Pyloric sphincter
A05.5.01.024.definition: the circular fold of mucous membrane containing a ring of circularly disposed muscle fibers that closes the vertebrate pylorus —called also pyloric valve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.026.name: Submucosa
A05.5.01.026.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.027.name: Mucosa
A05.5.01.027.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.5.01.033.name: Gastric glands
A05.5.01.033.definition: any of various glands in the walls of the stomach that secrete gastric juice (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.01.001.name: Small intestine
A05.6.01.001.definition: the part of the intestine that lies between the stomach and colon, consists of duodenum, jejunum, and ileum, secretes digestive enzymes, and is the chief site of the absorption of digested nutrients —called also small bowel (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.01.002.name: Serosa
A05.6.01.002.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.01.008.name: Submucosa
A05.6.01.008.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.01.009.name: Mucosa
A05.6.01.009.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.02.001.name: Duodenum
A05.6.02.001.definition: the first, shortest, and widest part of the small intestine that in humans is about 10 inches (25 centimeters) long and that extends from the pylorus to the undersurface of the liver where it descends for a variable distance and receives the bile and pancreatic ducts and then bends to the left and finally upward to join the jejunum near the second lumbar vertebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.03.001.name: Jejunum
A05.6.03.001.definition: the section of the small intestine that comprises the first two fifths beyond the duodenum and that is larger, thicker-walled, and more vascular and has more circular folds and fewer Peyer's patches than the ileum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.6.04.001.name: Ileum
A05.6.04.001.definition: the last division of the small intestine that constitutes the part between the jejunum and large intestine and in humans forms the last three fifths of the part of the small intestine beyond the end of the duodenum and that is smaller and thinner-walled than the jejunum with fewer circular folds but more numerous Peyer's patches (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.01.001.name: Large intestine
A05.7.01.001.definition: the more terminal division of the vertebrate intestine that is wider and shorter than the small intestine, typically divided into cecum, colon, and rectum, and concerned especially with the resorption of water and the formation of feces (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.01.002.name: Serosa
A05.7.01.002.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.01.004.name: Muscular coat
A05.7.01.004.definition: an outer layer of smooth muscle surrounding a hollow or tubular organ (as the bladder, esophagus, large intestine, small intestine, stomach, ureter, uterus, and vagina) that often consists of an inner layer of circular fibers serving to narrow the lumen of the organ and an outer layer of longitudinal fibers serving to shorten its length —called also muscularis externa, tunica muscularis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.01.005.name: Submucosa
A05.7.01.005.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.01.006.name: Mucosa
A05.7.01.006.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.02.001.name: Caecum
A05.7.02.001.definition: a cavity open at one end (as the blind end of a duct); especially : the blind pouch at the beginning of the large intestine into which the ileum opens from one side and which is continuous with the colon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.02.007.name: Appendix
A05.7.02.007.definition: a bodily outgrowth or process; specifically : vermiform appendix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.001.name: Colon
A05.7.03.001.definition: the part of the large intestine that extends from the cecum to the rectum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.002.name: Ascending colon
A05.7.03.002.definition: the part of the large intestine that extends from the cecum to the bend on the right side below the liver (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.004.name: Transverse colon
A05.7.03.004.definition: the part of the large intestine that extends across the abdominal cavity joining the ascending colon to the descending colon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.006.name: Descending colon
A05.7.03.006.definition: the part of the large intestine on the left side that extends from the bend below the spleen to the sigmoid colon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.007.name: Sigmoid colon
A05.7.03.007.definition: the contracted and crooked part of the colon immediately above the rectum —called also pelvic colon, sigmoid flexure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.03.013.name: Taeniae coli
A05.7.03.013.definition: any of three external longitudinal muscle bands of the large intestine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.04.001.name: Rectum
A05.7.04.001.definition: the terminal part of the intestine from the sigmoid colon to the anus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.04.011.name: Rectococcygeus
A05.7.04.011.definition: a band of smooth muscle extending from the coccyx to the posterior wall of the rectum and serving to retract and elevate the rectum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.05.001.name: Anal canal
A05.7.05.001.definition: the terminal section of the rectum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.7.05.013.name: Anus
A05.7.05.013.definition: the posterior opening of the digestive tract (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.001.name: Liver
A05.8.01.001.definition: a large very vascular glandular organ of vertebrates that secretes bile and causes important changes in many of the substances contained in the blood which passes through it (as by converting sugars into glycogen which it stores up until required and by forming urea), that in humans is the largest gland in the body, weighs from 40 to 60 ounces (1100 to 1700 grams), is a dark red color, and occupies the upper right portion of the abdominal cavity immediately below the diaphragm, that is divided by fissures into five lobes, and that receives blood both from the hepatic artery and the portal vein and returns it to the systemic circulation by the hepatic veins  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.011.name: Ligamentum venosum
A05.8.01.011.definition: a cord of tissue connected to the liver that is the vestige of the ductus venosus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.016.name: Porta hepatis
A05.8.01.016.definition: the fissure running transversely on the underside of the liver where most of the vessels enter or leave —called also transverse fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.029.name: Quadrate lobe
A05.8.01.029.definition: a small lobe of the liver on the underside of the right lobe to the left of the fissure for the gallbladder (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.030.name: Caudate lobe
A05.8.01.030.definition: a lobe of the liver bounded on the right by the inferior vena cava, on the left by the fissure of the ductus venosus, and connected with the right lobe by a narrow prolongation —called also spigelian lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.01.033.name: Hepatic segmentation: lobes, parts, divisions and segments

term_localized.en: Hepatic segmentation: lobes, parts, divisions and segments
term_localized.la: Segmentatio hepatis: lobi, partes, divisiones et segmenta

A05.8.01.052.name: Serosa
A05.8.01.052.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.02.001.name: Gallbladder
A05.8.02.001.definition: a membranous muscular sac in which bile from the liver is stored —called also cholecyst (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.02.006.name: Serosa
A05.8.02.006.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.02.009.name: Mucosa
A05.8.02.009.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.02.011.name: Cystic duct
A05.8.02.011.definition: the duct from the gallbladder that unites with the hepatic duct to form the common bile duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.8.02.013.name: Bile duct
A05.8.02.013.definition: a duct by which bile passes from the liver or gallbladder to the duodenum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.9.01.001.name: Pancreas
A05.9.01.001.definition: a large lobulated gland that in humans lies in front of the upper lumbar vertebrae and behind the stomach and is somewhat hammer-shaped and firmly attached anteriorly to the curve of the duodenum with which it communicates through one or more pancreatic ducts and that consists of (1) tubular acini secreting digestive enzymes which pass to the intestine and function in the breakdown of proteins, fats, and carbohydrates; (2) modified acinar cells that form islets of Langerhans between the tubules and secrete the hormones insulin and glucagon; and (3) a firm connective-tissue capsule that extends supportive strands into the organ (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.9.01.003.name: Uncinate process
A05.9.01.003.definition: a hooklike body part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.9.01.015.name: Pancreatic duct
A05.9.01.015.definition: a duct connecting the pancreas with the intestine:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A05.9.01.017.name: Accessory pancreatic duct
A05.9.01.017.definition: a duct of the pancreas that branches from the chief pancreatic duct and opens into the duodenum above it —called also duct of Santorini (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.0.00.000.name: Respiratory system
A06.0.00.000.definition: a system of organs functioning in respiration and consisting especially of the nose, nasal passages, nasopharynx, larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs —called also respiratory tract (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.01.001.name: Nose
A06.1.01.001.definition: the part of the face that bears the nostrils and covers the anterior part of the nasal cavity; broadly : this part together with the nasal cavity  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.01.006.name: Nasal cartilages
A06.1.01.006.definition: any of the cartilages forming the anterior part of the nose (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.01.016.name: Vomeronasal cartilage
A06.1.01.016.definition: a narrow process of cartilage between the vomer and the cartilage of the nasal septum —called also Jacobson's cartilage (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.001.name: Nasal cavity
A06.1.02.001.definition: the vaulted chamber that lies between the floor of the cranium and the roof of the mouth of higher vertebrates extending from the external nares to the pharynx, being enclosed by bone or cartilage and usually incompletely divided into lateral halves by the septum of the nose, and having its walls lined with mucous membrane that is rich in venous plexuses and ciliated in the lower part which forms the beginning of the respiratory passage and warms and filters the inhaled air and that is modified as sensory epithelium in the upper olfactory part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.002.name: Nares
A06.1.02.002.definition: either of the pair of openings of the nose (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.003.name: Choana
A06.1.02.003.definition: either of the pair of posterior apertures of the nasal cavity that open into the nasopharynx —called also posterior naris (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.004.name: Nasal septum
A06.1.02.004.definition: the bony and cartilaginous partition between the nasal passages (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.008.name: Vomeronasal organ
A06.1.02.008.definition: either of a pair of small blind pouches or tubes in many vertebrates that are situated one on either side of the nasal septum or in the buccal cavity and that are reduced to rudimentary pits in adult humans but are developed in reptiles, amphibians, and some mammals as chemoreceptors —called also Jacobson's organ, organ of Jacobson (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.017.name: Mucosa
A06.1.02.017.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.02.022.name: Spheno-ethmoidal recess
A06.1.02.022.definition: a small space between the sphenoid bone and the superior nasal concha into which the sphenoid sinus opens (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.03.001.name: Paranasal sinuses
A06.1.03.001.definition: any of various sinuses (as the maxillary sinus and frontal sinus) in the bones of the face and head that are lined with mucous membrane derived from and continuous with the lining of the nasal cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.03.002.name: Maxillary sinus
A06.1.03.002.definition: an air cavity in the body of the maxilla that communicates with the middle meatus of the nose —called also antrum of Highmore (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.03.003.name: Sphenoidal sinus
A06.1.03.003.definition: either of two irregular cavities in the body of the sphenoid bone that communicate with the nasal cavities (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.03.004.name: Frontal sinus
A06.1.03.004.definition: either of two air spaces lined with mucous membrane each of which lies within the frontal bone above one of the orbits (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.1.03.005.name: Ethmoidal cells
A06.1.03.005.definition: the cavities in the lateral masses of the ethmoid bone that are partly completed by adjoining bones and communicate with the nasal cavity —called also ethmoidal cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.01.001.name: Larynx
A06.2.01.001.definition: the modified upper part of the respiratory passage of air-breathing vertebrates that is bounded above by the glottis, is continuous below with the trachea, has a complex cartilaginous or bony skeleton capable of limited motion through the action of associated muscles, and in humans, most other mammals, and a few lower forms has a set of elastic vocal cords that play a major role in sound production and speech —called also voice box (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.02.002.name: Thyroid cartilage
A06.2.02.002.definition: the chief cartilage of the larynx that consists of two broad lamellae joined at an angle and that forms the Adam's apple (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.02.011.name: Inferior horn
A06.2.02.011.definition: the cornu in the lateral ventricle of each cerebral hemisphere that curves downward into the temporal lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.02.013.name: Thyrohyoid membrane
A06.2.02.013.definition: a broad fibroelastic sheet that connects the upper margin of the thyroid cartilage and the upper margin of the back of the hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.03.001.name: Cricoid cartilage
A06.2.03.001.definition: a cartilage of the larynx which articulates with the lower cornua of the thyroid cartilage and with which the arytenoid cartilages articulate —called also cricoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.04.005.name: Vocal process
A06.2.04.005.definition: the anterior angle of the arytenoid cartilage on each side of the larynx to which the vocal ligament of the corresponding side is attached (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.04.007.name: Colliculus
A06.2.04.007.definition: an anatomical prominence; especially : any of the four prominences constituting the corpora quadrigemina (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.05.001.name: Corniculate cartilage
A06.2.05.001.definition: either of two small nodules of yellow elastic cartilage articulating with the apex of the arytenoid —called also cartilage of Santorini (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.06.001.name: Cuneiform cartilage
A06.2.06.001.definition: either of a pair of rods of yellow elastic cartilage of which each lies on one side of the larynx in an aryepiglottic fold just below the arytenoid cartilage —called also cartilage of Wrisberg (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.07.001.name: Epiglottis
A06.2.07.001.definition: a thin lamella of yellow elastic cartilage that ordinarily projects upward behind the tongue and just in front of the glottis and that with the arytenoid cartilages serves to cover the glottis during the act of swallowing (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.07.005.name: Thyro-epiglottic ligament
A06.2.07.005.definition: a long narrow ligamentous cord connecting the thyroid cartilage and epiglottis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.08.001.name: Cricothyroid
A06.2.08.001.definition: relating to or connecting the cricoid cartilage and the thyroid cartilage (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.08.007.name: Vocalis
A06.2.08.007.definition: a small muscle that is the medial part of the thyroarytenoid, originates in the lamina of the thyroid cartilage, inserts in the vocal process of the arytenoid cartilage, and modulates the tension of the true vocal cords (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.08.008.name: Thyro-arytenoid
A06.2.08.008.definition: a broad thin muscle that arises especially from the thyroid cartilage, inserts into the arytenoid cartilage, and functions to relax and shorten the vocal cords by drawing the arytenoid cartilage forward and to narrow the rima glottidis by rotating the arytenoid cartilage inward causing the vocal cords to approach each other —called also thyroarytenoid muscle, thyroarytenoideus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.011.name: Laryngeal saccule
A06.2.09.011.definition: a membranous sac in the larynx located between the false vocal cords and the inner surface of the thyroid cartilage and containing mucus-secreting glands whose secretion lubricates the vocal cords —called also laryngeal pouch, laryngeal sac (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.012.name: Glottis
A06.2.09.012.definition: the space between one of the true vocal cords and the arytenoid cartilage on one side of the larynx and those of the other side; also : the structures that surround this space (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.014.name: Rima glottidis
A06.2.09.014.definition: the passage in the glottis between the true vocal cords (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.019.name: Mucosa
A06.2.09.019.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.023.name: Vestibular ligament
A06.2.09.023.definition: the narrow band of fibrous tissue contained in each of the false vocal cords and stretching between the thyroid and arytenoid cartilages (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.2.09.025.name: Vocal ligament
A06.2.09.025.definition: the band of yellow elastic tissue contained in each true vocal cord and stretching between the thyroid and arytenoid cartilages —called also inferior thyroarytenoid ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.3.01.001.name: Trachea
A06.3.01.001.definition: the main trunk of the system of tubes by which air passes to and from the lungs that is about four inches (10 centimeters) long and somewhat less than an inch (2.5 centimeters) in diameter, extends down the front of the neck from the larynx, divides in two to form the bronchi, has walls of fibrous and muscular tissue stiffened by incomplete cartilaginous rings which keep it from collapsing, and is lined with mucous membrane whose epithelium is composed of columnar ciliated mucus-secreting cells —called also windpipe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.3.01.005.name: Trachealis
A06.3.01.005.definition: a muscle associated with the trachea that in humans consists of smooth muscle fibers extending transversely between the ends of the tracheal rings and the intervals between them at the back of the trachea (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.3.01.010.name: Mucosa
A06.3.01.010.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.4.01.001.name: Bronchi
A06.4.01.001.definition: either of the two primary divisions of the trachea that lead respectively into the right and the left lung; broadly : bronchial tube (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.4.01.002.name: Bronchial tree
A06.4.01.002.definition: the bronchi together with their branches (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Bronquio superior de la língula (B IV)
Bronquio inferior de la língula (B V)

A06.4.02.028.name: Submucosa
A06.4.02.028.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.4.02.029.name: Mucosa
A06.4.02.029.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.4.02.030.name: Bronchial glands
A06.4.02.030.definition: any of the lymphatic glands situated at the bifurcation of the trachea and along the bronchi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.5.01.001.name: Lungs
A06.5.01.001.definition: one of the usually two compound saccular organs that constitute the basic respiratory organ of air-breathing vertebrates, that normally occupy the entire lateral parts of the thorax and consist essentially of an inverted tree of intricately branched bronchioles communicating with thin-walled terminal alveoli swathed in a network of delicate capillaries where the actual gaseous exchange of respiration takes place, and that in humans are somewhat flattened with a broad base resting against the diaphragm and have the right lung divided into three lobes and the left into two lobes  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.5.01.021.name: Oblique fissure
A06.5.01.021.definition: either of two fissures of the lungs of which the one on the left side of the body separates the superior lobe of the left lung from the inferior lobe and the one on the right separates the superior and middle lobes of the right lung from the inferior lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A06.5.02.026.name: Bronchioles
A06.5.02.026.definition: a minute thin-walled branch of a bronchus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.0.00.000.name: Thoracic cavity
A07.0.00.000.definition: the division of the body cavity that lies above the diaphragm, is bounded peripherally by the wall of the chest, and contains the heart and lungs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.01.001.name: Pleural cavity
A07.1.01.001.definition: the space that is formed when the two layers of the pleura spread apart —called also pleural space (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.02.001.name: Pleura
A07.1.02.001.definition: either of a pair of two-walled sacs of serous membrane each of which lines one lateral half of the thorax, has an inner visceral layer closely adherent to the corresponding lung, is reflected at the root of the lung to form a parietal layer that adheres to the walls of the thorax, the pericardium, the upper surface of the diaphragm, and adjacent parts, and contains a small amount of serous fluid that minimizes the friction of respiratory movements (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.02.003.name: Serosa
A07.1.02.003.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.02.010.name: Serosa
A07.1.02.010.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.02.017.name: Pulmonary ligament
A07.1.02.017.definition: a supporting fold of pleura that extends from the lower part of the lung on its surface opposite the mediastinum to the pericardium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.02.101.name: Mediastinum
A07.1.02.101.definition: the space in the chest between the pleural sacs of the lungs that contains all the viscera of the chest except the lungs and pleurae; also : this space with its contents  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A07.1.03.001.name: Pericardial cavity
A07.1.03.001.definition: the fluid-filled space between the two layers of the pericardium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.0.00.000.name: Urinary system
A08.0.00.000.definition: the organs of the urinary tract comprising the kidneys, ureters, urinary bladder, and urethra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.01.001.name: Kidney
A08.1.01.001.definition: one of a pair of vertebrate organs situated in the body cavity near the spinal column that excrete waste products of metabolism, in humans are bean-shaped organs about 41\/2 inches (111\/2 centimeters) long lying behind the peritoneum in a mass of fatty tissue, and consist chiefly of nephrons by which urine is secreted, collected, and discharged into the renal pelvis whence it is conveyed by the ureter to the bladder  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.01.005.name: Renal sinus
A08.1.01.005.definition: the main cavity of the kidney that is an expansion behind the hilum and contains the renal pelvis, calyxes, and the major renal vessels (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.01.027.name: Renal papilla
A08.1.01.027.definition: the apex of a renal pyramid which projects into the lumen of a calyx of the kidney and through which collecting ducts discharge urine (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.03.008.name: Vasa recta
A08.1.03.008.definition: numerous small vessels that arise from the terminal branches of arteries supplying the intestine, encircle the intestine, and divide into more branches between its layers  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.05.001.name: Renal pelvis
A08.1.05.001.definition: a funnel-shaped structure in each kidney that is formed at one end by the expanded upper portion of the ureter lying in the renal sinus and at the other end by the union of the calyxes of the kidney (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.05.009.name: Adventitia
A08.1.05.009.definition: the outer layer that makes up a tubular organ or structure and especially a blood vessel, is composed of collagenous and elastic fibers, and is not covered with peritoneum —called also tunica adventitia, tunica externa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.1.05.011.name: Mucosa
A08.1.05.011.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.2.01.001.name: Ureter
A08.2.01.001.definition: either of the paired ducts that carry away urine from a kidney to the bladder or cloaca and that in humans are slender membranous epithelium-lined flat tubes about sixteen inches (41 centimeters) long which open above into the pelvis of a kidney and below into the back part of the same side of the bladder at a very oblique angle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.2.01.005.name: Adventitia
A08.2.01.005.definition: the outer layer that makes up a tubular organ or structure and especially a blood vessel, is composed of collagenous and elastic fibers, and is not covered with peritoneum —called also tunica adventitia, tunica externa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.2.01.007.name: Mucosa
A08.2.01.007.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.3.01.001.name: Urinary bladder
A08.3.01.001.definition: a distensible membranous sac that serves for the temporary retention of the urine, is situated in the pelvis in front of the rectum, receives the urine from the two ureters and discharges it at intervals into the urethra through an orifice closed by a sphincter, is lined with transitional hypoblastic epithelium, and develops from the proximal part of the allantois of the embryo (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.3.01.007.name: Median umbilical ligament
A08.3.01.007.definition: a fibrous cord extending from the urinary bladder to the navel that is the remnant of the fetal urachus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.3.01.008.name: Serosa
A08.3.01.008.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.3.01.014.name: Detrusor
A08.3.01.014.definition: the outer largely longitudinally arranged musculature of the bladder wall —called also detrusor muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Porción del cuello de la vesícula

A08.3.01.022.name: Submucosa
A08.3.01.022.definition: a supporting layer of loose connective tissue directly under a mucous membrane —called also tela submucosa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A08.3.01.023.name: Mucosa
A08.3.01.023.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.01.001.name: Ovary
A09.1.01.001.definition: one of the typically paired essential female reproductive organs that produce eggs and in vertebrates female sex hormones, that occur in the adult human as oval flattened bodies about one and a half inches (four centimeters) long suspended from the dorsal surface of the broad ligament of either side, that arise from the mesonephros, and that consist of a vascular fibrous stroma enclosing developing egg cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.01.009.name: Tunica albuginea
A09.1.01.009.definition: a white fibrous capsule especially of the testis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.01.015.name: Corpus luteum
A09.1.01.015.definition: a yellowish mass of progesterone-secreting endocrine tissue that consists of pale secretory cells derived from granulosa cells, that forms immediately after ovulation from the ruptured graafian follicle in the mammalian ovary, and that regresses rather quickly if the ovum is not fertilized but persists throughout the ensuing pregnancy if it is fertilized (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.01.017.name: Ligament of ovary
A09.1.01.017.definition: a rounded cord of fibrous and muscular tissue extending from each superior angle of the uterus to the inner extremity of the ovary of the same side —called also ovarian ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.01.018.name: Suspensory ligament of ovary
A09.1.01.018.definition: a fold of peritoneum that consists of a part of the broad ligament that is attached to the ovary near the end joining the fallopian tube and that contains blood and lymph vessels passing to and from the ovary —called also infundibulopelvic ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.003.name: Infundibulum
A09.1.02.003.definition: any of various conical or dilated organs or parts:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.004.name: Fimbriae
A09.1.02.004.definition: a bordering fringe especially at the entrance of the fallopian tubes  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.006.name: Ampulla
A09.1.02.006.definition: a saccular anatomic swelling or pouch: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.007.name: Isthmus
A09.1.02.007.definition: a contracted anatomical part or passage connecting two larger structures or cavities: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.010.name: Serosa
A09.1.02.010.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.02.013.name: Mucosa
A09.1.02.013.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.001.name: Uterus
A09.1.03.001.definition: an organ in female mammals for containing and usually for nourishing the young during development prior to birth that consists of a greatly modified and enlarged section of an oviduct (as in rodents and marsupials) or of the two oviducts united (as in the higher primates including humans), that has thick walls consisting of an outer serous layer, a very thick middle layer of smooth muscle, and an inner mucous layer containing numerous glands, and that during pregnancy undergoes great increase in size and change in the condition of its walls —called also womb (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.018.name: Cervical canal
A09.1.03.018.definition: the passage through the cervix uteri (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.021.name: Parametrium
A09.1.03.021.definition: the connective tissue and fat adjacent to the uterus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.023.name: Serosa
A09.1.03.023.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.025.name: Myometrium
A09.1.03.025.definition: the muscular layer of the wall of the uterus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.027.name: Endometrium
A09.1.03.027.definition: the mucous membrane lining the uterus that is composed of three layers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.028.name: Uterine glands
A09.1.03.028.definition: any of the branched tubular glands in the mucous membrane of the uterus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.03.032.name: Uterosacral ligament
A09.1.03.032.definition: a fibrous fascial band on each side of the uterus that passes along the lateral wall of the pelvis from the uterine cervix to the sacrum and that serves to support the uterus and hold it in place —called also sacrouterine ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.04.001.name: Vagina
A09.1.04.001.definition: a canal in a female mammal that leads from the uterus to the external orifice opening into the vestibule between the labia minora (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.04.008.name: Hymen
A09.1.04.008.definition: a fold of mucous membrane partly or wholly closing the orifice of the vagina (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.04.011.name: Mucosa
A09.1.04.011.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.05.001.name: Epoophoron
A09.1.05.001.definition: a rudimentary organ homologous with the male epididymis that lies in the broad ligament of the uterus and consists of a number of small tubules which are the remains of the tubules of the mesonephros of the embryo and which open into Gartner's duct —called also organ of Rosenm\u00fcller, parovarium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.1.06.001.name: Paroophoron
A09.1.06.001.definition: a group of rudimentary tubules in the broad ligament between the epoophoron and the uterus that constitutes a remnant of the lower part of the mesonephros in the female corresponding to the paradidymis of the male (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.001.name: Pudendum
A09.2.01.001.definition: the external genital organs of a human; especially : the external genitalia of a woman : vulva —usually used in plural (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.002.name: Mons pubis
A09.2.01.002.definition: a rounded eminence of fatty tissue upon the pubic symphysis especially of the human female (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.004.name: Anterior commissure
A09.2.01.004.definition: a band of nerve fibers crossing from one side of the brain to the other just anterior to the third ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.005.name: Posterior commissure
A09.2.01.005.definition: a bundle of white matter crossing from one side of the brain to the other just rostral to the superior colliculi and above the opening of the aqueduct of Sylvius into the third ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.006.name: Pudendal cleft
A09.2.01.006.definition: the opening between the labia majora —called also rima pudendi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.012.name: Vestibule

term_localized.es: Fosa del vestíbulo de la vagina

A09.2.01.012.definition: any of various bodily cavities especially when serving as or resembling an entrance to some other cavity or space: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.01.013.name: Bulb of vestibule
A09.2.01.013.definition: a structure in the female vulva that is homologous to the bulb of the penis and the adjoining corpus spongiosum in the male and that consists of an elongated mass of erectile tissue on each side of the vaginal and urethral openings united anteriorly to the contralateral mass by a narrow median band passing along the lower surface of the clitoris (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.02.001.name: Clitoris
A09.2.02.001.definition: a female erogenous organ that consists of an externally visible, highly innervated small conical structure or glans that lies at the anterior junction of the labia minora above the urethral opening and is continuous internally with a short body of paired cylinders of vascular, erectile corpus cavernosum tissue which branch into curved extensions or crura attaching to the pubic arch and with two elongated masses of erectile tissue (the bulb of the vestibule) situated near each side of the vaginal and urethral openings (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.2.03.004.name: Urethral crest
A09.2.03.004.definition: a narrow longitudinal fold or ridge along the posterior wall or floor of the female urethra or the prostatic portion of the male urethra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Músculo esfínter externo de la uretra

A09.2.03.012.name: Mucosa
A09.2.03.012.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.001.name: Testis
A09.3.01.001.definition: a typically paired male reproductive gland that usually consists largely of seminiferous tubules from the epithelium of which spermatozoa develop, that contains androgen-secreting Leydig cells in the interstitial tissue, that corresponds to the ovary of the female and in craniate vertebrates develops from the genital ridges of the embryo, and that in most mammals descends into the scrotum before the attainment of sexual maturity and in many cases before birth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.008.name: Tunica vaginalis
A09.3.01.008.definition: a pouch of serous membrane covering the testis and derived from the peritoneum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.014.name: Serosa
A09.3.01.014.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.016.name: Mucosa
A09.3.01.016.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.022.name: Seminiferous tubules
A09.3.01.022.definition: any of the coiled threadlike tubules that make up the bulk of the testis and are lined with a layer of epithelial cells from which the spermatozoa are produced (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.01.024.name: Rete testis
A09.3.01.024.definition: the network of tubules in the mediastinum testis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.02.001.name: Epididymis
A09.3.02.001.definition: a system of ductules that emerges posteriorly from the testis, holds sperm during maturation, and forms a tangled mass before uniting into a single coiled duct which comprises the highly convoluted body and tail of the system and is continuous with the vas deferens (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.03.001.name: (Paradidymis)
A09.3.03.001.definition: a group of coiled tubules situated in front of the lower end of the spermatic cord above the enlarged upper extremity of the epididymis and considered to be a remnant of tubes of the mesonephros (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.04.001.name: Spermatic cord
A09.3.04.001.definition: a cord that suspends the testis within the scrotum, contains the vas deferens and vessels and nerves of the testis, and extends from the deep inguinal ring through the inguinal canal and superficial inguinal ring downward into the scrotum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.04.003.name: Cremaster
A09.3.04.003.definition: a thin muscle consisting of loops of fibers derived from the internal oblique muscle and descending upon the spermatic cord to surround and suspend the testicle —called also cremaster muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.05.008.name: Adventitia
A09.3.05.008.definition: the outer layer that makes up a tubular organ or structure and especially a blood vessel, is composed of collagenous and elastic fibers, and is not covered with peritoneum —called also tunica adventitia, tunica externa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.05.010.name: Mucosa
A09.3.05.010.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.06.002.name: Adventitia
A09.3.06.002.definition: the outer layer that makes up a tubular organ or structure and especially a blood vessel, is composed of collagenous and elastic fibers, and is not covered with peritoneum —called also tunica adventitia, tunica externa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.06.004.name: Mucosa
A09.3.06.004.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.07.001.name: Ejaculatory duct
A09.3.07.001.definition: either of the paired ducts in the human male that are formed by the junction of the duct from the seminal vesicle with the vas deferens, pass through the prostate, and open into or close to the prostatic utricle —called also ductus ejaculatorius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.3.08.010.name: Right and left lobes of prostate

term_localized.en: Right and left lobes of prostate

A09.3.08.018.name: Parenchyma
A09.3.08.018.definition: the essential and distinctive tissue of an organ or an abnormal growth as distinguished from its supportive framework (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.01.001.name: Penis
A09.4.01.001.definition: the male erectile copulatory organ of a higher vertebrate animal developing from the genital tubercle that in mammals including humans usually functions as the channel by which urine and semen are discharged from the body and is typically a cylindrical organ that is suspended from the pubic arch, contains a pair of large lateral corpora cavernosa and a smaller ventromedial corpus cavernosum containing the urethra, and has a terminal glans enclosing the ends of the corpora cavernosa, covered by mucous membrane, and sheathed by a foreskin continuous with the skin covering the body of the organ (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.01.007.name: Glans penis
A09.4.01.007.definition: the rounded, highly innervated body that forms the extremity of the penis  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.01.011.name: Prepuce
A09.4.01.011.definition: foreskin; also : a similar fold investing the clitoris (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.01.012.name: Frenulum
A09.4.01.012.definition: a connecting fold of membrane serving to support or restrain a part (as the tongue) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.01.016.name: Bulb of penis
A09.4.01.016.definition: the proximal expanded part of the corpus cavernosum of the male urethra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Túnica albuginea de los cuerpos cavernosos

A09.4.02.004.name: Prostatic urethra
A09.4.02.004.definition: the part of the male urethra from the base of the prostate gland where the urethra begins as the outlet of the bladder to the point where it emerges from the apex of the prostate gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.02.007.name: Urethral crest
A09.4.02.007.definition: a narrow longitudinal fold or ridge along the posterior wall or floor of the female urethra or the prostatic portion of the male urethra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.02.009.name: Prostatic utricle
A09.4.02.009.definition: a small blind pouch that projects from the wall of the prostatic urethra into the prostate gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: M. esfínter interno de la uretra

A09.4.02.015.name: Mucosa
A09.4.02.015.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: M. esfínter externo de la uretra

A09.4.02.020.name: Mucosa
A09.4.02.020.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.02.022.name: Navicular fossa
A09.4.02.022.definition: the dilated terminal portion of the urethra in the glans penis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.02.029.name: Mucosa
A09.4.02.029.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.4.03.001.name: Scrotum
A09.4.03.001.definition: the external sac that in most mammals contains the testes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.5.00.001.name: Perineum
A09.5.00.001.definition: an area of tissue that marks externally the approximate boundary of the pelvic outlet and gives passage to the urogenital ducts and rectum; also : the area between the anus and the posterior part of the external genitalia especially in the female (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.5.00.005.name: Perineal body
A09.5.00.005.definition: a mass of muscle and fascia that separates the lower end of the vagina and the rectum in the female and the urethra and the rectum in the male (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A09.5.02.004.name: Ischiocavernosus
A09.5.02.004.definition: a muscle on each side that arises from the ischium near the crus of the penis or clitoris and is inserted on the crus near the pubic symphysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: M. esfínter externo de la uretra
Cuerpo adiposo de la fosa isquio-anal
Cavidades del abdomen y de la pelvis

A10.1.00.002.name: Pelvic cavity
A10.1.00.002.definition: the cavity of the pelvis comprising in humans a broad upper and a more contracted lower part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.01.003.name: Retropubic space
A10.1.01.003.definition: the potential space occurring between the pubic symphysis and the urinary bladder —called also space of Retzius (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.001.name: Peritoneal cavity
A10.1.02.001.definition: a space formed when the parietal and visceral layers of the peritoneum spread apart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.002.name: Peritoneum
A10.1.02.002.definition: the smooth transparent serous membrane that lines the cavity of the abdomen of a mammal, is folded inward over the abdominal and pelvic viscera, and consists of an outer layer closely adherent to the walls of the abdomen and an inner layer that folds to invest the viscera (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.003.name: Serosa
A10.1.02.003.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.005.name: Parietal peritoneum
A10.1.02.005.definition: the part of the peritoneum that lines the abdominal wall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.006.name: Visceral peritoneum
A10.1.02.006.definition: the part of the peritoneum that lines the abdominal viscera (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.007.name: Mesentery
A10.1.02.007.definition: one or more vertebrate membranes that consist of a double fold of the peritoneum and invest the intestines and their appendages and connect them with the dorsal wall of the abdominal cavity; specifically : such membranes connected with the jejunum and ileum in humans  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.009.name: Mesocolon
A10.1.02.009.definition: a mesentery joining the colon to the dorsal abdominal wall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.014.name: Meso-appendix
A10.1.02.014.definition: the mesentery of the vermiform appendix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.101.name: Lesser omentum
A10.1.02.101.definition: a part of the peritoneum attached to the liver and to the lesser curvature of the stomach and supporting the hepatic vessels (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.201.name: Greater omentum
A10.1.02.201.definition: a part of the peritoneum attached to the greater curvature of the stomach and to the colon and hanging down over the small intestine —called also caul, gastrocolic omentum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.203.name: Gastrosplenic ligament
A10.1.02.203.definition: a mesenteric fold passing from the greater curvature of the stomach to the spleen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.302.name: Coronary ligament
A10.1.02.302.definition: the folds of peritoneum connecting the posterior surface of the liver and the diaphragm  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.303.name: Falciform ligament
A10.1.02.303.definition: an anteroposterior fold of peritoneum attached to the under surface of the diaphragm and sheath of the rectus muscle and along a line on the anterior and upper surfaces of the liver extending back from the notch on the anterior margin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.404.name: Vestibule
A10.1.02.404.definition: any of various bodily cavities especially when serving as or resembling an entrance to some other cavity or space: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A10.1.02.425.name: Subphrenic space
A10.1.02.425.definition: a space on each side of the falciform ligament between the underside of the diaphragm and the upper side of the liver (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Triángulo parietal lateral de la pelvis

A11.0.00.000.name: Endocrine glands
A11.0.00.000.definition: a gland (as the thyroid or the pituitary) that produces an endocrine secretion —called also ductless gland, gland of internal secretion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.001.name: Pituitary gland
A11.1.00.001.definition: a small oval reddish gray very vascular endocrine organ that is attached to the infundibulum of the brain and occupies the sella turcica, that is present in all craniate vertebrates, that consists essentially of an epithelial anterior lobe derived from a diverticulum of the oral cavity and joined to a posterior lobe of nervous origin by a pars intermedia, and that has the several parts associated with various hormones which directly or indirectly affect most basic bodily functions and include substances exerting a controlling and regulating influence on other endocrine organs, controlling growth and development, or modifying the contraction of smooth muscle, renal function, and reproduction —called also hypophysis, pituitary body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.002.name: Adenohypophysis
A11.1.00.002.definition: the anterior part of the pituitary gland that is derived from the embryonic pharynx and is primarily glandular in nature —called also anterior lobe, anterior pituitary (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.003.name: Pars tuberalis
A11.1.00.003.definition: a thin plate of cells that is an extension of the adenohypophysis on the ventral or anterior aspect of the infundibulum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.004.name: Pars intermedia
A11.1.00.004.definition: a thin slip of tissue fused with the neurohypophysis and representing the remains of the posterior wall of Rathke's pouch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.005.name: Pars distalis
A11.1.00.005.definition: the anterior part of the adenohypophysis that is the major secretory part of the gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.006.name: Neurohypophysis
A11.1.00.006.definition: the portion of the pituitary gland that is derived from the embryonic brain, is composed of the infundibulum and neural lobe, and is concerned with the secretion of various hormones —called also posterior pituitary gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.1.00.007.name: Infundibulum
A11.1.00.007.definition: any of various conical or dilated organs or parts:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.2.00.001.name: Pineal gland
A11.2.00.001.definition: a small body that arises from the roof of the third ventricle and is enclosed by the pia mater and that functions primarily as an endocrine gland that produces melatonin —called also pineal, pineal body, pineal organ (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.3.00.002.name: Lobe
A11.3.00.002.definition: a curved or rounded projection or division: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.3.00.003.name: Isthmus
A11.3.00.003.definition: a contracted anatomical part or passage connecting two larger structures or cavities: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.3.00.004.name: (Pyramidal lobe)
A11.3.00.004.definition: a conical lobe of the thyroid gland that varies in shape and position but is often found on the cranial part of the isthmus joining the right and left lobes of the gland or on the adjacent part of either lobe and that may project upward to the hyoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.3.00.007.name: Stroma
A11.3.00.007.definition: the supporting framework of an animal organ typically consisting of connective tissue  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.3.00.008.name: Parenchyma
A11.3.00.008.definition: the essential and distinctive tissue of an organ or an abnormal growth as distinguished from its supportive framework (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.4.00.001.name: Parathyroid gland
A11.4.00.001.definition: any of usually four small endocrine glands that are adjacent to or embedded in the thyroid gland, are composed of irregularly arranged secretory epithelial cells lying in a stroma rich in capillaries, and produce parathyroid hormone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.5.00.007.name: Cortex
A11.5.00.007.definition: the outer or superficial part of an organ or body structure (as the kidney, adrenal gland, or a hair); especially : cerebral cortex  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.5.00.009.name: Hilum
A11.5.00.009.definition: a scar on a seed (as a bean) marking the point of attachment of the ovule  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A11.5.00.010.name: Central vein
A11.5.00.010.definition: any of the veins in the lobules of the liver that occur one in each lobule running from the apex to the base, receive blood from the sinusoids, and empty into the sublobular veins —called also intralobular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.001.name: Blood vessel
A12.0.00.001.definition: any of the vessels through which blood circulates in the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.003.name: Artery
A12.0.00.003.definition: any of the tubular branching muscular and elastic-walled vessels that carry blood from the heart through the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.005.name: Arteriole
A12.0.00.005.definition: any of the small terminal twigs of an artery that ends in capillaries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.008.name: Cistern
A12.0.00.008.definition: a fluid-containing sac or cavity in an organism (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.009.name: Blood
A12.0.00.009.definition: the fluid that circulates in the heart, arteries, capillaries, and veins of a vertebrate animal carrying nourishment and oxygen to and bringing away waste products from all parts of the body  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.011.name: Venous plexus
A12.0.00.011.definition: a plexus of veins that surrounds the rectum and empties especially into the rectal veins —called also rectal plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.015.name: Venous plexus
A12.0.00.015.definition: a plexus of veins that surrounds the rectum and empties especially into the rectal veins —called also rectal plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.016.name: Sinus venosus
A12.0.00.016.definition: an enlarged pouch that adjoins the heart, is formed by the union of the large systemic veins, and is the passage through which venous blood enters the heart in lower vertebrates and in embryos of higher forms (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.020.name: Valve
A12.0.00.020.definition: a bodily structure (as the mitral valve) that closes temporarily a passage or orifice or permits movement of fluid in one direction only  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.021.name: Cusp
A12.0.00.021.definition: a point on the grinding surface of a tooth  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.022.name: Cusp
A12.0.00.022.definition: a point on the grinding surface of a tooth  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.025.name: Capillary
A12.0.00.025.definition: resembling a hair especially in slender elongated form  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.027.name: Sinusoid
A12.0.00.027.definition: a minute endothelium-lined space or passage for blood in the tissues of an organ (as the liver) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.028.name: Vasa vasorum
A12.0.00.028.definition: small blood vessels that supply or drain the walls of the larger arteries and veins and connect with a branch of the same vessel or a neighboring vessel (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.030.name: Vein
A12.0.00.030.definition: any of the tubular branching vessels that carry blood from the capillaries toward the heart and have thinner walls than the arteries and often valves at intervals to prevent reflux of the blood which flows in a steady stream and is in most cases dark-colored due to the presence of reduced hemoglobin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.031.name: Vena comitans
A12.0.00.031.definition: a vein accompanying an artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.033.name: Emissary vein
A12.0.00.033.definition: any of the veins that pass through apertures in the skull and connect the venous sinuses of the dura mater with veins external to the skull (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.035.name: Deep vein
A12.0.00.035.definition: a condition marked by the formation of a thrombus within a deep vein (as of the leg or pelvis) that may be asymptomatic or be accompanied by symptoms (as swelling and pain) and that is potentially life threatening if dislodgment of the thrombus results in pulmonary embolism —abbreviation DVT (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.037.name: Venule
A12.0.00.037.definition: a small vein; especially : any of the minute veins connecting the capillaries with the larger systemic veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.043.name: Lymph
A12.0.00.043.definition: a usually clear coagulable fluid that passes from intercellular spaces of body tissue into the lymphatic vessels, is discharged into the blood by way of the thoracic duct and right lymphatic duct, and resembles blood plasma in containing white blood cells and especially lymphocytes but normally few red blood cells and no platelets (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.0.00.044.name: Lymphatic capillary
A12.0.00.044.definition: any of the smallest lymphatic vessels that are blind at one end and collect lymph in organs and tissues —called also lymph capillary (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.001.name: Heart
A12.1.00.001.definition: a hollow muscular organ of vertebrate animals that by its rhythmic contraction acts as a force pump maintaining the circulation of the blood and that in the human adult is about five inches (13 centimeters) long and three and one half inches (9 centimeters) broad, is of conical form, is placed obliquely in the chest with the broad end upward and to the right and the apex opposite the interval between the cartilages of the fifth and sixth ribs on the left side, is enclosed in a serous pericardium, and consists as in other mammals and in birds of four chambers divided into an upper pair of rather thin-walled atria which receive blood from the veins and a lower pair of thick-walled ventricles into which the blood is forced and which in turn pump it into the arteries  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.011.name: Coronary sulcus
A12.1.00.011.definition: a depression surrounding the heart at the atrioventricular junction and giving passage to coronary arteries, coronary veins, and the coronary sinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.013.name: Interventricular septum
A12.1.00.013.definition: the curved slanting wall that separates the right and left ventricles of the heart and is composed of a muscular lower part and a thinner more membranous upper part (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.017.name: Right or left atrium
A12.1.00.017.definition: a small vein that passes obliquely down the posterior surface of the left atrium, empties into the coronary sinus, and is a remnant of the left duct of Cuvier —called also oblique vein, oblique vein of left atrium, oblique vein of Marshall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.019.name: Interatrial septum
A12.1.00.019.definition: the wall separating the right and left atria of the heart —called also atrial septum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.022.name: Papillary muscles
A12.1.00.022.definition: one of the small muscular columns attached at one end to the chordae tendineae and at the other to the wall of the ventricle and that maintain tension on the chordae tendineae as the ventricle contracts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.023.name: Chordae tendineae
A12.1.00.023.definition: any of the delicate tendinous cords that are attached to the edges of the atrioventricular valves of the heart and to the papillary muscles and serve to prevent the valves from being pushed into the atrium during the ventricular contraction (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.00.029.name: Tendon of valve of inferior vena cava

term_localized.en: Tendon of valve of inferior vena cava
term_localized.es: Tendón de la válvula de la vena cava inferior
Orificio de las venas cardíacas míninas

A12.1.01.005.name: Fossa ovalis
A12.1.01.005.definition: a depression in the septum between the right and left atria that marks the position of the foramen ovale in the fetus  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.01.007.name: (Foramen ovale)
A12.1.01.007.definition: an opening in the septum between the two atria of the heart that is normally present only in the fetus  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.01.008.name: Musculi pectinati
A12.1.01.008.definition: small muscular ridges on the inner wall of the auricular appendage of the left and the right atria of the heart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Orificio de la vena cava inferior
Orificio de la vena cava superior
Válvula de la vena cava inferior

A12.1.02.003.name: Tricuspid valve
A12.1.02.003.definition: a valve that is situated at the opening of the right atrium of the heart into the right ventricle and that resembles the mitral valve in structure but consists of three triangular membranous flaps —called also right atrioventricular valve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.02.008.name: Conus arteriosus
A12.1.02.008.definition: a conical prolongation of the right ventricle from which the pulmonary arteries emerge —called also conus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.02.010.name: Pulmonary valve
A12.1.02.010.definition: a valve consisting of three semilunar cusps separating the pulmonary trunk from the right ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.03.001.name: Left atrium
A12.1.03.001.definition: a small vein that passes obliquely down the posterior surface of the left atrium, empties into the coronary sinus, and is a remnant of the left duct of Cuvier —called also oblique vein, oblique vein of left atrium, oblique vein of Marshall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.03.003.name: Musculi pectinati
A12.1.03.003.definition: small muscular ridges on the inner wall of the auricular appendage of the left and the right atria of the heart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.04.001.name: Left ventricle
A12.1.04.001.definition: a vein that ascends on the surface of the left ventricle facing the diaphragm and that usually empties into the coronary sinus —called also posterior vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.04.003.name: Mitral valve
A12.1.04.003.definition: a valve in the heart that guards the opening between the left atrium and the left ventricle, prevents the blood in the ventricle from returning to the atrium, and consists of two triangular flaps attached at their bases to the fibrous ring which surrounds the opening and connected at their margins with the ventricular walls by the chordae tendineae and papillary muscles —called also bicuspid valve, left atrioventricular valve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.04.012.name: Aortic valve
A12.1.04.012.definition: the semilunar valve separating the aorta from the left ventricle that prevents blood from flowing back into the left ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.05.001.name: Endocardium
A12.1.05.001.definition: a thin serous membrane lining the cavities of the heart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.06.001.name: Myocardium
A12.1.06.001.definition: the middle muscular layer of the heart wall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.06.004.name: Atrioventricular node
A12.1.06.004.definition: a small mass of tissue that is situated in the wall of the right atrium adjacent to the septum between the atria, passes impulses received from the sinoatrial node to the ventricles by way of the bundle of His, and in some pathological states replaces the sinoatrial node as pacemaker of the heart (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.08.001.name: Pericardium
A12.1.08.001.definition: the conical sac of serous membrane that encloses the heart and the roots of the great blood vessels of vertebrates and consists of an outer fibrous coat that loosely invests the heart and is prolonged on the outer surface of the great vessels except the inferior vena cava and a double inner serous coat of which one layer is closely adherent to the heart while the other lines the inner surface of the outer coat with the intervening space being filled with pericardial fluid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.1.08.008.name: Serosa
A12.1.08.008.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Pliegue de la vena cava izquierda

A12.2.00.001.name: Arteries
A12.2.00.001.definition: any of the tubular branching muscular and elastic-walled vessels that carry blood from the heart through the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.02.001.name: Aorta
A12.2.02.001.definition: the large arterial trunk that carries blood from the heart to be distributed by branch arteries through the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.03.001.name: Ascending aorta
A12.2.03.001.definition: the part of the aorta from its origin to the beginning of the arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.04.001.name: Arch of aorta
A12.2.04.001.definition: the curved transverse part of the aorta that connects the ascending aorta with the descending aorta —called also aortic arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.04.004.name: Brachiocephalic trunk
A12.2.04.004.definition: a short artery that arises from the arch of the aorta and divides into the carotid and subclavian arteries of the right side —called also brachiocephalic trunk, innominate artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.04.006.name: Common carotid artery
A12.2.04.006.definition: the part of either carotid artery between its point of origin and its division into the internal and external carotid arteries —called also common carotid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.04.007.name: Carotid body
A12.2.04.007.definition: a small body of vascular tissue that adjoins the carotid sinus, functions as a chemoreceptor sensitive to change in the oxygen content of blood, and mediates reflex changes in respiratory activity —called also carotid gland, glomus caroticum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)
