A12.2.04.008.name: Carotid sinus
A12.2.04.008.definition: a small but richly innervated arterial enlargement that is located near the point in the neck where the common carotid artery divides into the internal and the external carotid arteries and that functions in the regulation of heart rate and blood pressure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.001.name: External carotid artery
A12.2.05.001.definition: the outer branch of the carotid artery that supplies the face, tongue, and external parts of the head —called also external carotid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.015.name: Lingual artery
A12.2.05.015.definition: an artery arising from the external carotid artery between the superior thyroid and facial arteries and supplying the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.019.name: Deep lingual artery
A12.2.05.019.definition: the terminal part of the lingual artery supplying the tip of the tongue —called also ranine artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.020.name: Facial artery
A12.2.05.020.definition: an artery that arises from the external carotid artery just superior to the lingual artery and gives off a number of branches supplying the neck and face —called also external maxillary artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.023.name: Submental artery
A12.2.05.023.definition: a branch of the facial artery that branches off near the submandibular gland and is distributed to the muscles of the jaw (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.029.name: Angular artery
A12.2.05.029.definition: the terminal part of the facial artery that passes up alongside the nose to the inner angle of the orbit (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.030.name: Occipital artery
A12.2.05.030.definition: an artery that arises from the external carotid artery opposite to the origin of the facial artery, that passes posteriorly to the base of the skull where it turns upward and ascends within the superficial fascia of the scalp, and that supplies or gives off branches supplying structures and especially muscles of the back of the neck and head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.037.name: Posterior auricular artery
A12.2.05.037.definition: a small branch of the external carotid artery that supplies or gives off branches supplying the back of the ear and the adjacent region of the scalp, the middle ear, tympanic membrane, and mastoid cells —called also posterior auricular (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.045.name: Superficial temporal artery
A12.2.05.045.definition: the one of the two terminal branches of each external carotid artery that arises in the substance of the parotid gland, passes upward over the zygomatic process of the temporal bone, and is distributed by way of branches especially to the more superficial parts of the side of the face and head (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.047.name: Transverse facial artery
A12.2.05.047.definition: a large branch of the superficial temporal artery that arises in the parotid gland and supplies or gives off branches supplying the parotid gland, masseter muscle, and adjacent parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.053.name: Maxillary artery
A12.2.05.053.definition: an artery supplying the deep structures of the face (as the nasal cavities, palate, tonsils, and pharynx) and sending a branch to the meninges of the brain —called also internal maxillary artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.056.name: Inferior alveolar artery
A12.2.05.056.definition: a branch of the maxillary artery that is distributed to the mucous membrane of the mouth and through the mandibular canal to the teeth of the lower jaw —called also inferior dental artery, mandibular artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.059.name: Mental branch
A12.2.05.059.definition: a branch of the inferior alveolar artery on each side that emerges from the mental foramen and supplies blood to the chin —called also mental branch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.061.name: Middle meningeal artery
A12.2.05.061.definition: a branch of the first portion of the maxillary artery that is the largest artery supplying the dura mater, enters the cranium through the foramen spinosum, and divides into anterior and posterior branches in a groove in the greater wing of the sphenoid bone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Rama anastomótica con la arteria lagrimal

A12.2.05.075.name: Posterior superior alveolar artery
A12.2.05.075.definition: a branch of the maxillary artery that supplies the upper molar and bicuspid teeth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.05.078.name: Infra-orbital artery
A12.2.05.078.definition: a branch or continuation of the maxillary artery that runs along the infraorbital groove with the infraorbital nerve and passes through the infraorbital foramen to give off branches which supply the face just below the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.001.name: Internal carotid artery
A12.2.06.001.definition: the inner branch of the carotid artery that supplies the brain, eyes, and other internal structures of the head —called also internal carotid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.003.name: Carotid sinus
A12.2.06.003.definition: a small but richly innervated arterial enlargement that is located near the point in the neck where the common carotid artery divides into the internal and the external carotid arteries and that functions in the regulation of heart rate and blood pressure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.016.name: Ophthalmic artery
A12.2.06.016.definition: a branch of the internal carotid artery following the optic nerve through the optic foramen into the orbit and supplying the eye and adjacent structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.024.name: Central retinal artery
A12.2.06.024.definition: central artery of the retina (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.027.name: Lacrimal artery
A12.2.06.027.definition: a large branch of the ophthalmic artery that arises near the optic foramen, passes along the superior border of the lateral rectus, and supplies the lacrimal gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.028.name: Anastomotic branch with middle meningeal artery

term_localized.en: Anastomotic branch with middle meningeal artery
term_localized.la: R. anastomoticus cum a. meningea media
term_localized.es: Rama anastomótica con la a. meníngea media

A12.2.06.037.name: Supra-orbital artery
A12.2.06.037.definition: a branch of the ophthalmic artery supplying the orbit and parts of the forehead (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.06.048.name: Supratrochlear artery
A12.2.06.048.definition: one of the terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery that ascends upon the forehead from the inner angle of the orbit —called also frontal artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ramas de la rodilla de la cápsula interna

A12.2.07.009.name: Branches to internal capsule, posterior limb

term_localized.en: Branches to internal capsule, posterior limb
term_localized.es: Ramas del brazo posterior de la cápsula interna

A12.2.07.010.name: Branches to internal capsule, retrolentiform limb

term_localized.en: Branches to internal capsule, retrolentiform limb
term_localized.es: Ramas de la porción retrolenticular de la cápsula interna

A12.2.07.012.name: Branches to tail of caudate nucleus

term_localized.en: Branches to tail of caudate nucleus
term_localized.es: Ramas de la cola del núcleo caudado
Ramas de los núcleos del tálamo
Ramas de la base del pedúnculo

A12.2.07.081.name: Basilar artery
A12.2.07.081.definition: an unpaired artery that is formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries, runs forward within the skull just under the pons, divides into the two posterior cerebral arteries, and supplies the pons, cerebellum, posterior part of the cerebrum, and the inner ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.001.name: Subclavian artery
A12.2.08.001.definition: the proximal part of the main artery of the arm that arises on the right side from the brachiocephalic artery and on the left side from the arch of the aorta, that extends from its point of origin to the outer border of the first rib where it becomes the axillary artery and passes through the axilla and into the arm to become the brachial artery, and that supplies or gives off branches supplying the brain, neck, anterior wall of the thorax, and shoulder (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.002.name: Vertebral artery
A12.2.08.002.definition: a large branch of the subclavian artery that ascends through the foramina in the transverse processes of each of the cervical vertebrae except the last one or two, enters the cranium through the foramen magnum, and unites with the corresponding artery of the opposite side to form the basilar artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.012.name: Posterior inferior cerebellar artery
A12.2.08.012.definition: an artery that usually branches from the vertebral artery below its junction with the contralateral vertebral artery to form the basilar artery and that supplies much of the medulla oblongata, the inferior portion of the cerebellum, and part of the floor of the fourth ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.019.name: Anterior inferior cerebellar artery
A12.2.08.019.definition: an artery that arises from the basilar artery either alone or by a common trunk with the internal auditory artery, divides into branches distributed to the anterior parts of the inferior surface of the cerebellum, and gives off a branch that anastomoses with the posterior inferior cerebellar artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.025.name: Superior cerebellar artery
A12.2.08.025.definition: an artery that arises from the basilar artery just before it divides to form the posterior cerebral arteries and supplies or gives off branches supplying the superior part of the cerebellum, midbrain, pineal gland, and choroid plexus of the third ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.029.name: Internal thoracic artery
A12.2.08.029.definition: a branch of the subclavian artery of each side that runs down along the anterior wall of the trunk and rests against the costal cartilages (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.040.name: Musculophrenic artery
A12.2.08.040.definition: a branch of the internal mammary artery that gives off branches to the seventh, eighth, and ninth intercostal spaces as anterior intercostal arteries, to the pericardium, to the diaphragm, and to the abdominal muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.042.name: Thyrocervical trunk
A12.2.08.042.definition: a short thick branch of the subclavian artery that divides into the inferior thyroid, suprascapular, and transverse cervical arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.051.name: Suprascapular artery
A12.2.08.051.definition: a branch of the thyrocervical trunk that passes obliquely from within outward and over the suprascapular ligament to the back of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.053.name: Transverse cervical artery
A12.2.08.053.definition: an inconstant branch of the thyrocervical trunk or of the subclavian artery that when present supplies or divides into branches supplying the region at the base of the neck and the muscles of the scapula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.08.059.name: Costocervical trunk
A12.2.08.059.definition: a branch of the subclavian artery that divides to supply the first or first two intercostal spaces and the deep structures of the neck (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.002.name: Axillary artery
A12.2.09.002.definition: the part of the main artery of the arm that lies in the axilla and that is continuous with the subclavian artery above and the brachial artery below (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.005.name: Thoraco-acromial artery
A12.2.09.005.definition: a short branch of the axillary artery that divides into four branches supplying the region of the pectoralis muscles, deltoid, subclavius, and sternoclavicular joint (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.013.name: Subscapular artery
A12.2.09.013.definition: an artery that is usually the largest branch of the axillary artery, that arises opposite the lower border of the subscapularis muscle, and that passes down and back to the lower part of the scapula where it forms branches and anastomoses with arteries in that region (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.014.name: Thoracodorsal artery
A12.2.09.014.definition: an artery that is continuous with the axillary artery, accompanies the thoracodorsal nerve, and supplies or gives off branches supplying the subscapularis muscle, latissimus dorsi, serratus anterior, and the intercostal muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.016.name: Anterior circumflex humeral artery
A12.2.09.016.definition: an artery that branches from the axillary artery in the shoulder, curves around the front of the humerus, is distributed or gives off branches distributed especially to the shoulder joint, head of the humerus, biceps brachii, and deltoid muscle, and anastomoses with the posterior humeral circumflex artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.018.name: Brachial artery
A12.2.09.018.definition: the chief artery of the upper arm that is a direct continuation of the axillary artery and divides into the radial and ulnar arteries just below the elbow (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.025.name: Superior ulnar collateral artery
A12.2.09.025.definition: a long slender artery that arises from the brachial artery or one of its branches just below the middle of the upper arm, descends to the elbow following the course of the ulnar nerve, and terminates under the flexor carpi ulnaris by anastomosing with two other arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.026.name: Inferior ulnar collateral artery
A12.2.09.026.definition: a small artery that arises from the brachial artery just above the elbow and divides to form or gives off branches that anastomose with other arteries in the region of the elbow (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.027.name: Radial artery
A12.2.09.027.definition: the smaller of the two branches into which the brachial artery divides just below the bend of the elbow and which passes along the radial side of the forearm to the wrist then winds backward around the outer side of the carpus and enters the palm between the first and second metacarpal bones to form the deep palmar arch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.041.name: Ulnar artery
A12.2.09.041.definition: an artery that is the larger of the two terminal branches of the brachial artery, runs along the ulnar side of the forearm, and gives off near its origin the anterior and posterior ulnar recurrent arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.042.name: Ulnar recurrent artery
A12.2.09.042.definition: either of the two small branches of the ulnar artery arising from its medial side:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.09.047.name: Common interosseous artery
A12.2.09.047.definition: a short thick artery that arises from the ulnar artery near the proximal end of the radius on the dorsal side of the interosseous membrane and that divides into anterior and posterior branches which pass down the forearm toward the wrist (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.10.001.name: Descending aorta
A12.2.10.001.definition: the part of the aorta from the arch to its bifurcation into the two common iliac arteries that passes downward in the thoracic and abdominal cavities (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.11.001.name: Thoracic aorta
A12.2.11.001.definition: the part of the aorta that lies in the thorax and extends from the arch to the diaphragm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.11.020.name: Subcostal artery
A12.2.11.020.definition: either of a pair of arteries that are the most posterior branches of the thoracic aorta and follow a course beneath the last pair of ribs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.001.name: Abdominal aorta
A12.2.12.001.definition: the portion of the aorta between the diaphragm and the bifurcation into the right and left common iliac arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.004.name: Lumbar arteries
A12.2.12.004.definition: any artery of the usually four or occasionally five pairs that arise at the level of the lumbar vertebrae from the back of the aorta or in the case of the fifth pair from an artery arising from the aorta and that supply the muscles of the loins, the skin of the sides of the abdomen, and the spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.012.name: Coeliac trunk
A12.2.12.012.definition: a short thick artery arising from the aorta just below the diaphragm and dividing almost immediately into the gastric, hepatic, and splenic arteries — called also celiac axis, truncus celiacus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.016.name: Gastroduodenal artery
A12.2.12.016.definition: an artery that arises from the hepatic artery and divides to form the right gastroepiploic artery and a branch supplying the duodenum and pancreas (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.028.name: Right gastric artery
A12.2.12.028.definition: an artery that arises from the hepatic artery, passes to the left along the lesser curvature of the stomach while giving off a number of branches, and eventually joins a branch of the left gastric artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.040.name: Splenic artery
A12.2.12.040.definition: the branch of the celiac artery that carries blood to the spleen and sends branches also to the pancreas and the cardiac end of the stomach (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: A. de la cola del páncreas

A12.2.12.053.name: Superior mesenteric artery
A12.2.12.053.definition: a large artery that arises from the aorta just below the celiac artery at the level of the first lumbar vertebra and supplies the greater part of the small intestine, the cecum, the ascending colon, and the right half of the transverse colon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.059.name: Ileocolic artery
A12.2.12.059.definition: a branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the terminal part of the ileum and the beginning of the colon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.069.name: Inferior mesenteric artery
A12.2.12.069.definition: artery that arises just above the bifurcation of the abdominal aorta into the common iliac arteries and supplies the left half of the transverse colon, the descending colon, the sigmoid colon, and most of the rectum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.12.075.name: Renal artery
A12.2.12.075.definition: either of two branches of the abdominal aorta of which each supplies one of the kidneys, arises immediately below the origin of the corresponding superior mesenteric artery, divides into four or five branches which enter the hilum of the kidney, and gives off smaller branches to the ureter, adrenal gland, and adjoining structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.14.001.name: Common iliac artery
A12.2.14.001.definition: either of the large arteries supplying blood to the lower trunk and hind limbs and arising by bifurcation of the aorta which in humans occurs at the level of the fourth lumbar vertebra to form one vessel for each side of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.001.name: Internal iliac artery
A12.2.15.001.definition: the inner branch of the common iliac artery on either side of the body that soon breaks into several branches and supplies blood chiefly to the pelvic and gluteal areas — called also hypogastric artery, internal iliac artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.002.name: Iliolumbar artery
A12.2.15.002.definition: a branch of the internal iliac artery that supplies muscles in the lumbar region and the iliac fossa (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.008.name: Obturator artery
A12.2.15.008.definition: an artery that arises from the internal iliac artery or one of its branches, passes out through the obturator canal, and divides into two branches which are distributed to the muscles and fasciae of the hip and thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.020.name: Umbilical artery
A12.2.15.020.definition: either of a pair of arteries that arise from the hypogastric arteries of the mammalian fetus and pass through the umbilical cord to the placenta to which they carry the deoxygenated blood from the fetus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.038.name: Internal pudendal artery
A12.2.15.038.definition: a branch of the internal iliac artery that is distributed or gives off branches distributed especially to the external genitalia and the perineum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.15.040.name: Perineal artery
A12.2.15.040.definition: a branch of the internal pudendal artery that supplies the skin of the external genitalia and the superficial parts of the perineum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.16.002.name: External iliac artery
A12.2.16.002.definition: the outer branch of the common iliac artery on either side of the body that passes beneath the inguinal ligament to become the femoral artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.16.010.name: Femoral artery
A12.2.16.010.definition: the chief artery of the thigh that is a continuation of the external iliac artery lying in the anterior part of the thigh and is undivided until a point about two inches (5 centimeters) below the inguinal ligament where it divides into a large deep branch and a smaller superficial branch (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.16.033.name: Popliteal artery
A12.2.16.033.definition: the continuation of the femoral artery that after passing through the thigh crosses the popliteal space and soon divides into the anterior and posterior tibial arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: A. superior lateral de la rodilla
A. superior medial de la rodilla
A. inferior lateral de la rodilla
A. inferior medial de la rodilla

A12.2.16.048.name: Dorsalis pedis artery
A12.2.16.048.definition: an artery of the upper surface of the foot that is a direct continuation of the anterior tibial artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.2.16.051.name: (Arcuate artery)
A12.2.16.051.definition: any of several arteries that curve and arch: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.00.001.name: Veins
A12.3.00.001.definition: any of the tubular branching vessels that carry blood from the capillaries toward the heart and have thinner walls than the arteries and often valves at intervals to prevent reflux of the blood which flows in a steady stream and is in most cases dark-colored due to the presence of reduced hemoglobin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.01.002.name: Coronary sinus
A12.3.01.002.definition: a venous channel that is derived from the sinus venosus, is continuous with the largest of the cardiac veins, receives most of the blood from the walls of the heart, and empties into the right atrium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.01.007.name: Oblique vein of left atrium
A12.3.01.007.definition: a small vein that passes obliquely down the posterior surface of the left atrium, empties into the coronary sinus, and is a remnant of the left duct of Cuvier —called also oblique vein, oblique vein of left atrium, oblique vein of Marshall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ligamento de la vena cava izquierda

A12.3.02.001.name: Pulmonary veins
A12.3.02.001.definition: any of usually four veins comprising two from each lung that return oxygenated blood from the lungs to the superior part of the left atrium, that may include three veins from the right lung if the veins from all three lobes of the right lung remain separate, and that may include a single trunk from the left lung if its major veins unite before emptying into the left atrium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.02.108.name: Posterior vein
A12.3.02.108.definition: a vein that ascends on the surface of the left ventricle facing the diaphragm and that usually empties into the coronary sinus —called also posterior vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.02.202.name: Superior vein
A12.3.02.202.definition: either of two veins draining the intestine, passing between the two layers of the mesentery, and associated with the corresponding mesenteric arteries:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.02.402.name: Superior vein
A12.3.02.402.definition: either of two veins draining the intestine, passing between the two layers of the mesentery, and associated with the corresponding mesenteric arteries:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.03.001.name: Superior vena cava
A12.3.03.001.definition: a vein that is the second largest vein in the human body, is formed by the union of the two brachiocephalic veins at the level of the space between the first two ribs, and returns blood to the right atrium of the heart from the upper half of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.04.001.name: Brachiocephalic vein
A12.3.04.001.definition: either of two large veins that occur one on each side of the neck, receive blood from the head and neck, are formed by the union of the internal jugular and the subclavian veins, and unite to form the superior vena cava —called also innominate vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.04.009.name: Bronchial veins
A12.3.04.009.definition: any vein accompanying the bronchi and their branches and emptying into the azygos and superior intercostal veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.04.012.name: Vertebral vein
A12.3.04.012.definition: a tributary of the brachiocephalic vein that is formed by the union of branches originating in the occipital region and forming a plexus about the vertebral artery in its passage through the foramina of the cervical vertebrae and that receives various branches which join it near its termination (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.04.017.name: Deep cervical vein
A12.3.04.017.definition: a tributary of the vertebral vein that drains blood especially from the deeper parts of the back of the neck (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.001.name: Internal jugular vein
A12.3.05.001.definition: jugular vein —called also internal jugular (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Bulbo superior de la vena yugular
Bulbo inferior de la vena yugulari

A12.3.05.006.name: Pharyngeal plexus
A12.3.05.006.definition: a plexus formed by branches of the glossopharyngeal, vagus, and sympathetic nerves supplying the muscles and mucous membrane of the pharynx and adjoining parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.018.name: Facial vein
A12.3.05.018.definition: a vein that arises as the angular vein, drains the superficial structures of the face, and empties into the internal jugular vein —called also anterior facial vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.019.name: Angular vein
A12.3.05.019.definition: a vein that comprises the first part of the facial vein and runs obliquely down at the side of the upper part of the nose (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.021.name: Supra-orbital vein
A12.3.05.021.definition: a vein that drains the supraorbital region and unites with the frontal vein to form the angular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.027.name: Deep facial vein
A12.3.05.027.definition: a tributary of the facial vein that drains part of the pterygoid plexus and neighboring structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.036.name: Pterygoid plexus
A12.3.05.036.definition: a plexus of veins draining the region of the pterygoid muscles and emptying chiefly into the facial vein by way of the deep facial vein and into the maxillary vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.045.name: External jugular vein
A12.3.05.045.definition: jugular vein —called also external jugular (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.046.name: Posterior auricular vein
A12.3.05.046.definition: a vein formed from venous tributaries in the region behind the ear that joins with the posterior facial vein to form the external jugular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.102.name: Transverse sinus
A12.3.05.102.definition: either of two large venous sinuses of the cranium that begin at the bony protuberance on the middle of the inner surface of the occipital bone at the intersection of its bony ridges and that terminate at the jugular foramen on either side to become the internal jugular vein —called also lateral sinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.103.name: Confluence of sinuses
A12.3.05.103.definition: the junction of several of the sinuses of the dura mater in the internal occipital region —called also confluence of the sinuses, torcular Herophili (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.105.name: Occipital sinus
A12.3.05.105.definition: a single or paired venous sinus that arises near the margin of the foramen magnum by the union of several small veins, follows the internal occipital crest along the attached margin of the falx cerebelli, and empties into the confluence of sinuses or sometimes into one of the transverse sinuses (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.108.name: Sigmoid sinus
A12.3.05.108.definition: a sinus on each side of the brain that is a continuation of the transverse sinus on the same side, follows an S-shaped course to the jugular foramen, and empties into the internal jugular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.112.name: Straight sinus
A12.3.05.112.definition: a venous sinus of the brain that is located along the line of junction of the falx cerebri and tentorium cerebelli, is formed by the junction of the great cerebral vein and the inferior sagittal sinus, and passes posteriorly to terminate in the confluence of sinuses (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.116.name: Cavernous sinus
A12.3.05.116.definition: either of a pair of large venous sinuses situated in a groove at the side of the body of the sphenoid bone in the cranial cavity and opening behind into the petrosal sinuses (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.119.name: Sphenoparietal sinus
A12.3.05.119.definition: a venous sinus of the dura mater on each side of the cranium arising at a meningeal vein near the apex of the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone and draining into the anterior part of the cavernous sinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.05.302.name: Parietal emissary vein
A12.3.05.302.definition: a vein that passes from the superior sagittal sinus inside the skull through a foramen in the parietal bone to connect with veins of the scalp (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Pplexo venoso del conducto del hipogloso

A12.3.06.001.name: Cerebral veins
A12.3.06.001.definition: a broad unpaired vein formed by the junction of Galen's veins and uniting with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.06.005.name: Frontal veins
A12.3.06.005.definition: a vein of the middle of the forehead that unites with the supraorbital vein to form the angular vein near the inner angle of the orbit (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.06.007.name: Temporal veins
A12.3.06.007.definition: any of several veins draining the temporal region: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.06.016.name: Temporal veins
A12.3.06.016.definition: any of several veins draining the temporal region: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.06.027.name: Great cerebral vein
A12.3.06.027.definition: a broad unpaired vein formed by the junction of Galen's veins and uniting with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.06.054.name: Vein of lateral recess of fourth ventricle

term_localized.en: Vein of lateral recess of fourth ventricle
term_localized.es: V. del receso lateral del cuarto ventrículo

A12.3.06.111.name: Central retinal vein
A12.3.06.111.definition: central vein of the retina (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.001.name: Azygos vein
A12.3.07.001.definition: any of a system of three veins which drain the thoracic wall and much of the abdominal wall and which form a collateral circulation when either the inferior or superior vena cava is obstructed; especially : a vein that receives blood from the right half of the thoracic and abdominal walls, ascends along the right side of the spinal column, and empties into the superior vena cava (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.004.name: Hemi-azygos vein
A12.3.07.004.definition: a vein that receives blood from the lower half of the left thoracic wall and the left abdominal wall, ascends along the left side of the spinal column, and empties into the azygos vein near the middle of the thorax (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.005.name: Accessory hemi-azygos vein
A12.3.07.005.definition: a vein that drains the upper left side of the thoracic wall, descends along the left side of the spinal column, and empties into the azygos or hemiazygos veins near the middle of the thorax (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.007.name: Bronchial veins
A12.3.07.007.definition: any vein accompanying the bronchi and their branches and emptying into the azygos and superior intercostal veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.011.name: Ascending lumbar vein
A12.3.07.011.definition: a longitudinal vein on each side that connects the lumbar veins and is frequently the origin of the azygos vein on the right side and of the hemiazygos vein on the left (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.07.012.name: Lumbar veins
A12.3.07.012.definition: any vein of the four pairs collecting blood from the muscles and integument of the loins, the walls of the abdomen, and adjacent parts and emptying into the dorsal part of the inferior vena cava (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.002.name: Subclavian vein
A12.3.08.002.definition: the proximal part of the main vein of the arm that is a continuation of the axillary vein and extends from the level of the first rib to the sternal end of the clavicle where it unites with the internal jugular vein to form the brachiocephalic vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.005.name: Axillary vein
A12.3.08.005.definition: the large vein passing through the axilla continuous with the basilic vein below and the subclavian vein above (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.015.name: Cephalic vein
A12.3.08.015.definition: any of various superficial veins of the arm; specifically : a large vein of the upper arm lying along the outer edge of the biceps muscle and emptying into the axillary vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.018.name: Basilic vein
A12.3.08.018.definition: a vein of the upper arm lying along the inner border of the biceps muscle, draining the whole limb, and opening into the axillary vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.019.name: Median cubital vein
A12.3.08.019.definition: a continuation of the cephalic vein of the forearm that passes obliquely toward the inner side of the arm in the bend of the elbow to join with the ulnar veins in forming the basilic vein and is often selected for venipuncture (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.020.name: Median antebrachial vein
A12.3.08.020.definition: a vein that is usually present in the forearm, that drains the plexus of veins in the palm of the hand, and that runs up the little-finger side of the forearm to join the median cubital vein or may divide into two branches to join the cephalic and basilic veins or may be missing as a recognizably distinct vessel (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Red venosa dorsal de la mano

A12.3.08.029.name: Brachial veins
A12.3.08.029.definition: one of a pair of veins accompanying the brachial artery and uniting with each other and with the basilic vein to form the axillary vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.030.name: Ulnar veins
A12.3.08.030.definition: any of several deep veins of the forearm that accompany the ulnar artery and unite at the elbow with the radial veins to form the brachial veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.08.031.name: Radial veins
A12.3.08.031.definition: any of several deep veins of the forearm that accompany the radial artery and unite at the elbow with the ulnar veins to form the brachial veins (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.001.name: Inferior vena cava
A12.3.09.001.definition: a vein that is the largest vein in the human body, is formed by the union of the two common iliac veins at the level of the fifth lumbar vertebra, and returns blood to the right atrium of the heart from bodily parts below the diaphragm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.003.name: Lumbar veins
A12.3.09.003.definition: any vein of the four pairs collecting blood from the muscles and integument of the loins, the walls of the abdomen, and adjacent parts and emptying into the dorsal part of the inferior vena cava (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.004.name: Ascending lumbar vein
A12.3.09.004.definition: a longitudinal vein on each side that connects the lumbar veins and is frequently the origin of the azygos vein on the right side and of the hemiazygos vein on the left (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.005.name: Hepatic veins
A12.3.09.005.definition: any of the veins that carry the blood received from the hepatic artery and from the hepatic portal vein away from the liver and that in humans are usually three in number and open into the inferior vena cava (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.009.name: Renal veins
A12.3.09.009.definition: a short thick vein that is formed in each kidney by the convergence of the interlobar veins, leaves the kidney through the hilum, and empties into the inferior vena cava (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.09.015.name: Pampiniform plexus
A12.3.09.015.definition: a venous plexus that is associated with each testicular vein in the male and each ovarian vein in the female —called also pampiniform venous plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.002.name: Median sacral vein
A12.3.10.002.definition: an unpaired vein that accompanies the middle sacral artery and usually empties into the left common iliac vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.007.name: Obturator veins
A12.3.10.007.definition: a tributary of the internal iliac vein that accompanies the obturator artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.010.name: Rectal venous plexus
A12.3.10.010.definition: a plexus of veins that surrounds the rectum and empties especially into the rectal veins —called also rectal plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.012.name: Vesical venous plexus
A12.3.10.012.definition: a plexus of veins surrounding the neck of the bladder and the base of the prostate gland and draining eventually into the internal iliac vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.014.name: Deep dorsal vein of clitoris ♀-Deep dorsal vein of penis ♂

term_localized.en: Deep dorsal vein of clitoris ♀-Deep dorsal vein of penis ♂
term_localized.la: V. dorsalis profunda clitoridis ♀-V. dorsalis profunda penis ♂

A12.3.10.019.name: Internal pudendal vein
A12.3.10.019.definition: any of several veins that receive blood from the external genitalia and the perineum, accompany the internal pudendal artery, and unite to form a single vein that empties into the internal iliac vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.10.020.name: Deep veins of clitoris ♀-Deep veins of penis ♂

term_localized.en: Deep veins of clitoris ♀-Deep veins of penis ♂

A12.3.10.023.name: Vein of bulb of vestibule ♀-Vein of bulb of penis ♂

term_localized.en: Vein of bulb of vestibule ♀-Vein of bulb of penis ♂

A12.3.11.008.name: Superficial dorsal veins of clitoris ♀-Superficial dorsal veins of penis ♂

term_localized.en: Superficial dorsal veins of clitoris ♀-Superficial dorsal veins of penis ♂
term_localized.la: Vv. dorsales superficiales clitoridis ♀-Vv. dorsales superficiales penis ♂

A12.3.11.023.name: Femoral vein
A12.3.11.023.definition: the chief vein of the thigh that is a continuation of the popliteal vein, accompanies the femoral artery in the upper part of its course, and continues above the inguinal ligament as the external iliac vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.11.028.name: Popliteal vein
A12.3.11.028.definition: a vein formed by the union of the anterior and posterior tibial veins and ascending through the popliteal space to the thigh where it becomes the femoral vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.12.001.name: Hepatic portal vein
A12.3.12.001.definition: a portal vein carrying blood from the digestive organs and spleen to the liver where the nutrients carried by the blood are altered by hepatocytes before passing into the systemic circulation (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.12.010.name: Umbilical vein
A12.3.12.010.definition: a vein that passes through the umbilical cord to the fetus and returns the oxygenated and nutrient blood from the placenta to the fetus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.12.018.name: Superior mesenteric vein
A12.3.12.018.definition: one that drains blood from the small intestine, the cecum, the ascending colon, and the transverse colon, that accompanies the superior mesenteric artery, and that joins with the splenic vein to form the portal vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.12.028.name: Splenic vein
A12.3.12.028.definition: the vein that carries blood away from the spleen, that is formed by five or six large branches which unite a short distance from the spleen, and that joins the superior mesenteric vein to form the portal vein —called also lienal vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.3.12.032.name: Inferior mesenteric vein
A12.3.12.032.definition: one that is a continuation of the superior rectal vein, that returns blood from the rectum, the sigmoid colon, and the descending colon, that accompanies the inferior mesenteric artery, and that usually empties into the splenic vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.4.01.002.name: Jugular trunk
A12.4.01.002.definition: either of two major lymph vessels that drain the head and neck:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.4.01.003.name: Subclavian trunk
A12.4.01.003.definition: a large lymphatic vessel on each side of the body that receives lymph from the axilla and arms and that on the right side empties into the right lymphatic duct and on the left side into the thoracic duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.4.01.006.name: Right lymphatic duct
A12.4.01.006.definition: a short vessel that receives lymph from the right side of the head, neck, and thorax, the right arm, right lung, right side of the heart, and convex surface of the liver and that discharges it into the right subclavian vein at its junction with the right internal jugular vein (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.4.01.007.name: Thoracic duct
A12.4.01.007.definition: the main trunk of the system of lymphatic vessels that lies along the front of the spinal column, extends from a dilatation behind the aorta and opposite the second lumbar vertebra up through the thorax where it turns to the left and opens into the left subclavian vein, and receives chyle from the intestine and lymph from the abdomen, the lower limbs, and the entire left side of the body —called also left lymphatic duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A12.4.01.012.name: Cisterna chyli
A12.4.01.012.definition: a dilated lymph channel usually opposite the first and second lumbar vertebrae and marking the beginning of the thoracic duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.0.00.000.name: Lymphoid system
A13.0.00.000.definition: the part of the circulatory system that is concerned especially with collecting fluids and proteins that have escaped from cells and tissues and returning them to the blood, with the phagocytic removal of cellular debris and foreign material, and with immune responses, that overlaps and parallels the system of blood vessels in function and shares some constituents with it, and that consists mainly of the thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymph, lymph nodes, lymphatic vessels, lymphocytes, and bone marrow where stem cells differentiate into precursors of B cells and T cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.1.01.001.name: Bone marrow
A13.1.01.001.definition: a soft highly vascular modified connective tissue that occupies the cavities and cancellous part of most bones and occurs in two forms:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.1.02.001.name: Thymus
A13.1.02.001.definition: a glandular structure of largely lymphoid tissue that functions in cell-mediated immunity by being the site where T cells develop, that is present in the young of most vertebrates typically in the upper anterior chest or at the base of the neck, that arises from the epithelium of one or more embryonic branchial clefts, and that gradually decreases in size and activity after puberty (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.1.02.002.name: Lobe
A13.1.02.002.definition: a curved or rounded projection or division: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.001.name: Spleen
A13.2.01.001.definition: a highly vascular ductless abdominal organ of vertebrates that resembles a gland in organization but is closely associated with the circulatory system, that plays a role in the final destruction of red blood cells, filtration and storage of blood, and production of lymphocytes, and that in humans is a dark purplish flattened oblong object of a soft fragile consistency lying near the cardiac end of the stomach and consisting largely of blood and lymphoid tissue enclosed in a fibroelastic capsule from which trabeculae ramify through the tissue of the organ which is divisible into a loose friable red pulp in intimate connection with the blood supply and with red blood cells free in its interstices and a denser white pulp chiefly of lymphoid tissue condensed in masses about the small arteries (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.004.name: Splenic pulp
A13.2.01.004.definition: the characteristic tissue of the spleen (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.005.name: Red pulp
A13.2.01.005.definition: a parenchymatous tissue of the spleen that consists of loose plates or cords infiltrated with red blood cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.006.name: White pulp
A13.2.01.006.definition: a parenchymatous tissue of the spleen that consists of compact masses of lymphatic cells and that forms the Malpighian corpuscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.018.name: Serosa
A13.2.01.018.definition: a usually enclosing serous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.01.020.name: Penicilli
A13.2.01.020.definition: one of the small straight arteries of the red pulp of the spleen  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.03.001.name: Lymph node
A13.2.03.001.definition: any of the rounded masses of lymphoid tissue that are surrounded by a capsule of connective tissue, are distributed along the lymphatic vessels, and contain numerous lymphocytes which filter the flow of lymph passing through the node —called also lymph gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.03.002.name: Capsule
A13.2.03.002.definition: a membrane or saclike structure enclosing a part or organ  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.03.003.name: Trabeculae
A13.2.03.003.definition: a small bar, rod, bundle of fibers, or septal membrane in the framework of a bodily organ or part (as the spleen)  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.03.004.name: Hilum
A13.2.03.004.definition: a scar on a seed (as a bean) marking the point of attachment of the ovule  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.2.03.005.name: Cortex
A13.2.03.005.definition: the outer or superficial part of an organ or body structure (as the kidney, adrenal gland, or a hair); especially : cerebral cortex  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A13.3.00.001.name: Lymph nodes of head and neck

term_localized.en: Lymph nodes of head and neck
term_localized.es: Ganglios linfáticos de la cabeza y cuello
(Ganglio del arco de la vena ácigos)

A13.3.03.032.name: Node of anterior border of omental foramen

term_localized.en: Node of anterior border of omental foramen

A13.3.03.042.name: Right or middle or left colic nodes

term_localized.en: Right or middle or left colic nodes
term_localized.la: Nodi colici dextri or medii or sinistri

A14.0.00.000.name: Nervous system
A14.0.00.000.definition: the bodily system that in vertebrates is made up of the brain and spinal cord, nerves, ganglia, and parts of the receptor organs and that receives and interprets stimuli and transmits impulses to the effector organs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.0.00.002.name: Neuron
A14.0.00.002.definition: one of the cells that constitute nervous tissue, that have the property of transmitting and receiving nerve impulses, and that are composed of somewhat reddish or grayish protoplasm with a large nucleus containing a conspicuous nucleolus, irregular cytoplasmic granules, and cytoplasmic processes which are highly differentiated frequently as multiple dendrites or usually as solitary axons and which conduct impulses toward and away from the cell body : nerve cell (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.0.00.004.name: Synapse
A14.0.00.004.definition: the place at which a nerve impulse passes from one neuron to another  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.001.name: Central nervous system
A14.1.00.001.definition: the part of the nervous system which in vertebrates consists of the brain and spinal cord, to which sensory impulses are transmitted and from which motor impulses pass out, and which supervises and coordinates the activity of the entire nervous system (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.003.name: Nucleus
A14.1.00.003.definition: a cellular organelle of eukaryotes that is essential to cell functions (as reproduction and protein synthesis), is composed of nuclear sap and a nucleoprotein-rich network from which chromosomes and nucleoli arise, and is enclosed in a definite membrane  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.005.name: Nucleus of origin
A14.1.00.005.definition: a group of cell bodies in the brain from which nerve fibers of a cranial nerve arise or at which they terminate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.007.name: Column
A14.1.00.007.definition: a longitudinal subdivision of the spinal cord that resembles a column or pillar: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.008.name: Lamina
A14.1.00.008.definition: a thin plate or layer especially of an anatomical part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.009.name: White matter
A14.1.00.009.definition: neural tissue especially of the brain and spinal cord that consists largely of myelinated nerve fibers bundled into tracts, has a whitish color, and typically underlies the gray matter (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.010.name: Funiculus
A14.1.00.010.definition: any of various bodily structures more or less like a cord in form: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.011.name: Tract
A14.1.00.011.definition: a system of body parts or organs that act together to perform some function  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.012.name: Fasciculus
A14.1.00.012.definition: a slender bundle of fibers:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.013.name: Commissure
A14.1.00.013.definition: a point or line of union or junction between two anatomical parts (as the lips at their angles or adjacent heart valves)  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.014.name: Lemniscus
A14.1.00.014.definition: a band of fibers and especially nerve fibers —called also fillet (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.015.name: Fibre
A14.1.00.015.definition: a thread or a threadlike structure or object: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.019.name: Decussation
A14.1.00.019.definition: the action of intersecting or crossing (as of nerve fibers) especially in the form of an X  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.021.name: Reticular formation
A14.1.00.021.definition: a mass of nerve cells and fibers situated primarily in the brain stem and functioning upon stimulation especially in arousal of the organism —called also reticular substance (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.00.022.name: Ependyma
A14.1.00.022.definition: an epithelial membrane lining the ventricles of the brain and the canal of the spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.001.name: Meninges
A14.1.01.001.definition: any of the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord and include the arachnoid, dura mater, and pia mater (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.101.name: Dura mater
A14.1.01.101.definition: the tough fibrous membrane lined with endothelium on the inner surface that envelops the brain and spinal cord external to the arachnoid and pia mater, that in the cranium closely lines the bone, does not dip down between the convolutions, and contains numerous blood vessels and venous sinuses, and that in the spinal cord is separated from the bone by a considerable space and contains no venous sinuses —called also dura (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.103.name: Falx cerebri
A14.1.01.103.definition: the larger of the two folds of dura mater separating the hemispheres of the brain that lies between the cerebral hemispheres and contains the sagittal sinuses (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.104.name: Tentorium cerebelli
A14.1.01.104.definition: an arched fold of dura mater that covers the upper surface of the cerebellum, supports the occipital lobes of the cerebrum, and has its posterior and lateral border attached to the skull and its anterior border free (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.105.name: Tentorial notch
A14.1.01.105.definition: an oval opening that is bounded by the anterior border of the tentorium cerebelli, that surrounds the midbrain, and that gives passage to the posterior cerebral arteries —called also tentorial incisure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.106.name: Falx cerebelli
A14.1.01.106.definition: the smaller of the two folds of dura mater separating the hemispheres of the brain that lies between the lateral lobes of the cerebellum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.107.name: Diaphragma sellae
A14.1.01.107.definition: a small horizontal fold of the dura mater that roofs over the sella turcica and contains a small opening for passage of the infundibulum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.109.name: (Subdural space)
A14.1.01.109.definition: a fluid-filled space or potential space between the dura mater and the arachnoid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.202.name: Subarachnoid space
A14.1.01.202.definition: the space between the arachnoid and the pia mater through which the cerebrospinal fluid circulates and across which extend delicate trabeculae of connective tissue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.203.name: Cerebrospinal fluid
A14.1.01.203.definition: a liquid that is comparable to serum but contains less dissolved material, that is secreted from the blood into the lateral ventricles of the brain by the choroid plexus, circulates through the ventricles to the spaces between the meninges about the brain and spinal cord, and is resorbed into the blood through the subarachnoid sinuses, and that serves chiefly to maintain uniform pressure within the brain and spinal cord —called also spinal fluid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.205.name: Arachnoid granulations
A14.1.01.205.definition: any of the small whitish processes that are enlarged villi of the arachnoid membrane of the brain which protrude into the superior sagittal sinus and into depressions in the neighboring bone —called also arachnoid villus, pacchionian body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.301.name: Pia mater
A14.1.01.301.definition: the delicate and highly vascular membrane of connective tissue investing the brain and spinal cord, lying internal to the arachnoid and dura mater, dipping down between the convolutions of the brain, and sending an ingrowth into the anterior fissure of the spinal cord —called also pia (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.305.name: Tela choroidea
A14.1.01.305.definition: a fold of pia mater roofing a ventricle of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.306.name: Choroid plexus
A14.1.01.306.definition: a highly vascular portion of the pia mater that projects into the ventricles of the brain and secretes cerebrospinal fluid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.310.name: Denticulate ligament
A14.1.01.310.definition: a band of fibrous pia mater extending along the spinal cord on each side between the dorsal and ventral roots —called also dentate ligament (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.01.401.name: Filum terminale
A14.1.01.401.definition: the slender threadlike prolongation of the spinal cord below the origin of the lumbar nerves : the last portion of the pia mater (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.001.name: Spinal cord
A14.1.02.001.definition: the thick longitudinal cord of nervous tissue that in vertebrates extends along the back dorsal to the bodies of the vertebrae and is enclosed in the spinal canal formed by their neural arches, is continuous anteriorly with the medulla oblongata, gives off at intervals pairs of spinal nerves to the various parts of the trunk and limbs, serves not only as a pathway for nerve impulses to and from the brain but as a center for carrying out and coordinating many reflex actions independently of the brain, and is composed largely of white matter arranged in columns and tracts of longitudinal fibers about a large central core of gray matter somewhat H-shaped in cross section and pierced centrally by a small longitudinal canal continuous with the ventricles of the brain —called also medulla spinalis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.004.name: Conus medullaris
A14.1.02.004.definition: a tapering lower part of the spinal cord at the level of the first lumbar segment (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.007.name: Anterior median fissure
A14.1.02.007.definition: a groove along the anterior midline of the spinal cord that incompletely divides it into symmetrical halves —called also ventral median fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.008.name: Posterior median sulcus
A14.1.02.008.definition: a shallow groove along the midline of the posterior part of the spinal cord that separates the two posterior funiculi and is the external boundary of the posterior median septum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.009.name: Posterior median septum
A14.1.02.009.definition: a sheet of glial tissue in the midsagittal plane of the spinal cord that extends from the posterior median sulcus toward the gray commissure and that partitions the posterior part of the spinal cord into right and left halves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.019.name: Central canal
A14.1.02.019.definition: a minute canal running through the gray matter of the whole length of the spinal cord and continuous anteriorly with the ventricles of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.116.name: Apex
A14.1.02.116.definition: a narrowed or pointed end of an anatomical structure: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.118.name: Head
A14.1.02.118.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.120.name: Neck
A14.1.02.120.definition: the usually narrowed part of an animal that connects the head with the body; specifically : the cervical region of a vertebrate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.123.name: Base
A14.1.02.123.definition: that portion of a bodily organ or part by which it is attached to another more central structure of the organism  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.215.name: Lateral funiculus
A14.1.02.215.definition: a longitudinal division on each side of the spinal cord comprising white matter between the dorsal and ventral roots (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.219.name: Lateral corticospinal tract
A14.1.02.219.definition: a band of nerve fibers that descends in the lateral funiculus of the spinal cord and consists mostly of fibers arising in the motor cortex of the contralateral side of the brain and crossing over in the decussation of pyramids with some fibers arising in the motor cortex of the same side —called also crossed pyramidal tract (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.224.name: Spinotectal tract
A14.1.02.224.definition: an ascending tract of nerve fibers in each lateral funiculus of white matter of the spinal cord that passes upward and terminates in the superior colliculus of the opposite side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.02.239.name: Posterior funiculus
A14.1.02.239.definition: a longitudinal division on each side of the spinal cord comprising white matter between the dorsal root and the posterior median sulcus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Estructuras centrales de la médula espinal

A14.1.03.001.name: Brain
A14.1.03.001.definition: the portion of the vertebrate central nervous system enclosed in the skull and continuous with the spinal cord through the foramen magnum that is composed of neurons and supporting and nutritive structures (as glia) and that integrates sensory information from inside and outside the body in controlling autonomic function (as heartbeat and respiration), in coordinating and directing correlated motor responses, and in the process of learning  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.003.name: Myelencephalon
A14.1.03.003.definition: the posterior part of the developing vertebrate hindbrain or the corresponding part of the adult brain composed of the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.004.name: Metencephalon
A14.1.03.004.definition: the anterior segment of the developing vertebrate hindbrain or the corresponding part of the adult brain composed of the cerebellum and pons (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.007.name: Diencephalon
A14.1.03.007.definition: the posterior subdivision of the forebrain —called also betweenbrain, interbrain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.008.name: Telencephalon
A14.1.03.008.definition: the anterior subdivision of the embryonic forebrain or the corresponding part of the adult forebrain that includes the cerebral hemispheres and associated structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.009.name: Brainstem
A14.1.03.009.definition: the part of the brain composed of the midbrain, pons, and medulla oblongata and connecting the spinal cord with the forebrain and cerebrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.03.010.name: Pons
A14.1.03.010.definition: a broad mass of chiefly transverse nerve fibers in the mammalian brain stem lying ventral to the cerebellum at the anterior end of the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.001.name: Anterior median fissure
A14.1.04.001.definition: a groove along the anterior midline of the spinal cord that incompletely divides it into symmetrical halves —called also ventral median fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.003.name: Pyramid
A14.1.04.003.definition: a polyhedron having for its base a polygon and for faces triangles with a common vertex  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.007.name: Lateral funiculus
A14.1.04.007.definition: a longitudinal division on each side of the spinal cord comprising white matter between the dorsal and ventral roots (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.008.name: Inferior olive
A14.1.04.008.definition: a large gray nucleus that forms the interior of the olive on each side of the medulla oblongata and has connections with the thalamus, cerebellum, and spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.020.name: Posterior median sulcus
A14.1.04.020.definition: a shallow groove along the midline of the posterior part of the spinal cord that separates the two posterior funiculi and is the external boundary of the posterior median septum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.021.name: Obex
A14.1.04.021.definition: a thin triangular lamina of gray matter in the roof of the fourth ventricle of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.111.name: Medial lemniscus
A14.1.04.111.definition: a band of nerve fibers that transmits proprioceptive impulses from the spinal cord to the thalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.113.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
A14.1.04.113.definition: any of four longitudinal bundles of white matter of which there are two on each side that extend from the midbrain to the upper parts of the spinal cord where they are located close to the midline ventral to the gray commissure and that are composed of fibers especially from the vestibular nuclei (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.118.name: Olivocerebellar tract
A14.1.04.118.definition: a tract of fibers that arises in the olive on one side, crosses to the olive on the other, and enters the cerebellum by way of the inferior cerebellar peduncle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.119.name: Juxtarestiform body
A14.1.04.119.definition: a part of the inferior cerebellar peduncle containing nerve fibers that reciprocally connect the cerebellum and the vestibular nuclei of the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.243.name: Inferior vestibular nucleus
A14.1.04.243.definition: the one of the four vestibular nuclei on each side of the medulla oblongata that is situated between the medial vestibular nucleus and the inferior cerebellar peduncle and that sends fibers down both sides of the spinal cord to synapse with motor neurons of the ventral roots (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.244.name: Magnocellular part of inferior vestibular nucleus

term_localized.en: Magnocellular part of inferior vestibular nucleus

A14.1.04.245.name: Medial vestibular nucleus
A14.1.04.245.definition: the one of the four vestibular nuclei on each side of the medulla oblongata that sends ascending fibers to the oculomotor and trochlear nuclei in the cerebrum on the opposite side of the brain and sends descending fibers down both sides of the spinal cord to synapse with motor neurons of the ventral roots (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.253.name: Nucleus ambiguus
A14.1.04.253.definition: an elongated nucleus in the medulla oblongata that is a continuation of a group of cells in the ventral horn of the spinal cord and gives rise to the motor fibers of the glossopharyngeal, vagus, and accessory nerves supplying striated muscle of the larynx and pharynx (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.256.name: Arcuate nucleus
A14.1.04.256.definition: any of several cellular masses in the thalamus, hypothalamus, or medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.258.name: Area postrema
A14.1.04.258.definition: a tongue-shaped structure in the caudal region of the fourth ventricle of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.04.308.name: Lateral reticular nucleus
A14.1.04.308.definition: a nucleus of the reticular formation that is situated in the ventrolateral part of the medulla oblongata, receives fibers especially from the dorsal horn of the spinal cord, and sends axons to the cerebellum on the same side of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.004.name: Cerebellopontine angle
A14.1.05.004.definition: a region of the brain at the junction of the pons and cerebellum that is a frequent site of tumor formation (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.204.name: Lateral nucleus
A14.1.05.204.definition: any of a group of nuclei of the thalamus situated in the dorsolateral region extending from its anterior to posterior ends (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.304.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
A14.1.05.304.definition: any of four longitudinal bundles of white matter of which there are two on each side that extend from the midbrain to the upper parts of the spinal cord where they are located close to the midline ventral to the gray commissure and that are composed of fibers especially from the vestibular nuclei (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.315.name: Trapezoid body
A14.1.05.315.definition: a bundle of transverse fibers in the dorsal part of the pons (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.317.name: Lateral lemniscus
A14.1.05.317.definition: a band of nerve fibers that arises in the cochlear nuclei and terminates in the inferior colliculus and the lateral geniculate body of the opposite side of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.403.name: Reticular formation
A14.1.05.403.definition: a mass of nerve cells and fibers situated primarily in the brain stem and functioning upon stimulation especially in arousal of the organism —called also reticular substance (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.406.name: Principal sensory nucleus of trigeminal nerve

term_localized.en: Principal sensory nucleus of trigeminal nerve
term_localized.es: Núcleo sensitivo principal del nervio trigémino

A14.1.05.415.name: Superior olivary nucleus
A14.1.05.415.definition: a small gray nucleus situated on the dorsolateral aspect of the trapezoid body —called also superior olivary nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.426.name: Medial vestibular nucleus
A14.1.05.426.definition: the one of the four vestibular nuclei on each side of the medulla oblongata that sends ascending fibers to the oculomotor and trochlear nuclei in the cerebrum on the opposite side of the brain and sends descending fibers down both sides of the spinal cord to synapse with motor neurons of the ventral roots (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.427.name: Lateral vestibular nucleus
A14.1.05.427.definition: the one of the four vestibular nuclei on each side of the medulla oblongata that is situated on the inner side of the inferior cerebellar peduncle beneath the floor of the fourth ventricle and that sends fibers down the same side of the spinal cord through the vestibulospinal tract —called also Deiters' nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.429.name: Superior vestibular nucleus
A14.1.05.429.definition: the one of the four vestibular nuclei on each side of the medulla oblongata that is situated dorsal to the lateral vestibular nucleus at the junction of the floor and lateral wall of the fourth ventricle and that sends ascending fibers to the oculomotor and trochlear nuclei in the cerebrum on the same side of the brain —called also Bekhterev's nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Núcleo intersticial del fascículo longitudinal s medial

A14.1.05.701.name: Fourth ventricle
A14.1.05.701.definition: a somewhat rhomboidal ventricle of the posterior part of the brain that connects at the front with the third ventricle through the aqueduct of Sylvius and at the back with the central canal of the spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.702.name: Rhomboid fossa
A14.1.05.702.definition: the floor of the fourth ventricle of the brain formed by the dorsal surfaces of the pons and medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.703.name: Median sulcus
A14.1.05.703.definition: a shallow groove along the midline of the posterior part of the spinal cord that separates the two posterior funiculi and is the external boundary of the posterior median septum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.705.name: Facial colliculus
A14.1.05.705.definition: a medial eminence on the floor of the fourth ventricle of the brain produced by the nucleus of the abducens nerve and the flexure of the facial nerve around it (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.714.name: Fastigium
A14.1.05.714.definition: the period at which the symptoms of a disease (as a febrile disease) are most pronounced  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.715.name: Choroid plexus
A14.1.05.715.definition: a highly vascular portion of the pia mater that projects into the ventricles of the brain and secretes cerebrospinal fluid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.05.723.name: Obex
A14.1.05.723.definition: a thin triangular lamina of gray matter in the roof of the fourth ventricle of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.004.name: Cerebral peduncle
A14.1.06.004.definition: either of two large bundles of nerve fibers passing from the pons forward and outward to form the main connection between the cerebral hemispheres and the spinal cord (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.010.name: Frenulum
A14.1.06.010.definition: a connecting fold of membrane serving to support or restrain a part (as the tongue) (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.014.name: Inferior colliculus
A14.1.06.014.definition: either member of the posterior and lower pair of corpora quadrigemina that are situated next to the pons and together constitute one of the lower centers for hearing (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.015.name: Superior colliculus
A14.1.06.015.definition: either member of the anterior and higher pair of corpora quadrigemina that together constitute a primitive center for vision —called also optic lobe, optic tectum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.111.name: Substantia nigra
A14.1.06.111.definition: a layer of deeply pigmented gray matter situated in the midbrain and containing the cell bodies of a tract of dopamine-producing nerve cells whose secretion tends to be deficient in Parkinson's disease (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.204.name: Lateral lemniscus
A14.1.06.204.definition: a band of nerve fibers that arises in the cochlear nuclei and terminates in the inferior colliculus and the lateral geniculate body of the opposite side of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.207.name: Medial lemniscus
A14.1.06.207.definition: a band of nerve fibers that transmits proprioceptive impulses from the spinal cord to the thalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.209.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
A14.1.06.209.definition: any of four longitudinal bundles of white matter of which there are two on each side that extend from the midbrain to the upper parts of the spinal cord where they are located close to the midline ventral to the gray commissure and that are composed of fibers especially from the vestibular nuclei (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Decusación de los pedúnculos cerebelosos superiores

A14.1.06.313.name: Interpeduncular nucleus
A14.1.06.313.definition: a mass of nerve cells lying between the cerebral peduncles in the midsagittal plane just dorsal to the pons —called also interpeduncular ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.316.name: Lateral nucleus
A14.1.06.316.definition: any of a group of nuclei of the thalamus situated in the dorsolateral region extending from its anterior to posterior ends (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.317.name: Medial nucleus
A14.1.06.317.definition: any of several small masses or layers of gray matter that are situated adjacent to the inferior olive and of which there are typically two on each side:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.323.name: Red nucleus
A14.1.06.323.definition: a nucleus of gray matter in the tegmentum of the midbrain on each side of the middle line that receives fibers from the cerebellum of the opposite side by way of the superior cerebellar peduncle and gives rise to fibers of the rubrospinal tract of the opposite side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.06.327.name: Reticular formation
A14.1.06.327.definition: a mass of nerve cells and fibers situated primarily in the brain stem and functioning upon stimulation especially in arousal of the organism —called also reticular substance (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Decusación de las fibras del nervio trodear

A14.1.07.001.name: Cerebellum
A14.1.07.001.definition: a large dorsally projecting part of the brain concerned especially with the coordination of muscles and the maintenance of bodily equilibrium, situated between the brain stem and the back of the cerebrum and formed in humans of two lateral lobes and a median lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.011.name: Paleocerebellum
A14.1.07.011.definition: a phylogenetically old part of the cerebellum concerned with maintenance of normal postural relationships and made up chiefly of the anterior lobe of the vermis and of the pyramid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.012.name: Neocerebellum
A14.1.07.012.definition: the phylogenetically youngest part of the cerebellum associated with the cerebral cortex in the integration of voluntary limb movements and comprising most of the cerebellar hemispheres and the superior vermis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.108.name: Wing of central lobule (H II and H III)

term_localized.en: Wing of central lobule (H II and H III)
term_localized.la: Ala lobuli centralis (H II et H III)

A14.1.07.116.name: Anterior quadrangular lobule (H IV and H V)

term_localized.en: Anterior quadrangular lobule (H IV and H V)
term_localized.la: Lobulus quadrangularis anterior (H IV et H V)
term_localized.es: Lobulillo cuadrangular anterior (H IV y H V)

A14.1.07.119.name: Primary fissure
A14.1.07.119.definition: a fissure of the cerebellum that is situated between the culmen and declive and that marks the boundary between the anterior lobe and the posterior lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.209.name: Horizontal fissure
A14.1.07.209.definition: a fissure of the right lung that begins at the oblique fissure and runs horizontally dividing the lung into superior and middle lobes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.301.name: Flocculonodular lobe
A14.1.07.301.definition: the posterior lobe of the cerebellum that consists of the nodulus and paired lateral flocculi and is concerned with equilibrium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.403.name: Granular layer
A14.1.07.403.definition: the deeper layer of the cortex of the cerebellum containing numerous small closely packed cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.405.name: Molecular layer
A14.1.07.405.definition: the outer layer of the cortex of the cerebellum and cerebrum consisting of a mass of unmyelinated fibers rich in synapses  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.407.name: Dentate nucleus
A14.1.07.407.definition: a large laminar nucleus of gray matter forming an incomplete capsule within the white matter of each cerebellar hemisphere (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.411.name: Fastigial nucleus
A14.1.07.411.definition: a nucleus lying near the midline in the roof of the fourth ventricle of the brain —called also roof nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.412.name: Cerebellar peduncles
A14.1.07.412.definition: any of three large bands of nerve fibers that join each hemisphere of the cerebellum with the parts of the brain below and in front:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.07.415.name: Juxtarestiform body
A14.1.07.415.definition: a part of the inferior cerebellar peduncle containing nerve fibers that reciprocally connect the cerebellum and the vestibular nuclei of the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.001.name: Diencephalon
A14.1.08.001.definition: the posterior subdivision of the forebrain —called also betweenbrain, interbrain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.002.name: Epithalamus
A14.1.08.002.definition: a dorsal segment of the diencephalon containing the habenula and the pineal gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.104.name: Pulvinar
A14.1.08.104.definition: a rounded prominence on the back of the thalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.302.name: Lateral geniculate body
A14.1.08.302.definition: a part of the metathalamus that consists of an oval elevation produced by the underlying lateral geniculate nucleus and is situated on the posterolateral surface of the thalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.303.name: Medial geniculate body
A14.1.08.303.definition: a part of the metathalamus consisting of a small oval tubercle situated between the pulvinar, colliculi, and cerebral peduncle that receives nerve impulses from the inferior colliculus and relays them to the auditory cortex (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.402.name: Mammillary body
A14.1.08.402.definition: either of two small rounded bodies that project from the posterior hypothalamus, receive input from the hippocampus via the fornix and relay impulses to the anterior nuclei of the thalamus, and are thought to play a role in memory —called also corpus albicans (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.403.name: Optic chiasm
