A14.1.08.403.definition: the X-shaped partial decussation on the undersurface of the hypothalamus through which the optic nerves are continuous with the brain —called also optic chiasm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.404.name: Optic tract
A14.1.08.404.definition: the portion of each optic nerve between the optic chiasma and the diencephalon proper (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.407.name: Preoptic area
A14.1.08.407.definition: a region of the brain that is situated immediately below the anterior commissure, above the optic chiasma, and anterior to the hypothalamus although it is not clearly demarcated from the hypothalamus and that regulates certain autonomic activities often with the hypothalamus —called also preoptic region (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.408.name: Tuber cinereum
A14.1.08.408.definition: an eminence of gray matter which lies on the lower surface of the brain between the optic tracts and in front of the mammillary bodies and of which the upper surface forms part of the floor of the third ventricle and the lower surface bears the infundibulum to which the pituitary gland is attached (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.409.name: Median eminence
A14.1.08.409.definition: a raised area in the floor of the third ventricle of the brain produced by the infundibulum of the hypothalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.410.name: Third ventricle
A14.1.08.410.definition: the median unpaired ventricle of the brain bounded by parts of the telencephalon and diencephalon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.411.name: Interventricular foramen
A14.1.08.411.definition: the opening from each lateral ventricle into the third ventricle of the brain —called also foramen of Monro (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.414.name: Habenular commissure
A14.1.08.414.definition: a band of nerve fibers situated in front of the pineal gland that connects the habenular nucleus on one side with that on the other (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.416.name: Posterior commissure
A14.1.08.416.definition: a bundle of white matter crossing from one side of the brain to the other just rostral to the superior colliculi and above the opening of the aqueduct of Sylvius into the third ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.417.name: Infundibular recess
A14.1.08.417.definition: a funnel-shaped downward prolongation of the floor of the third ventricle of the brain behind the optic chiasma into the infundibulum of the pineal gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.419.name: Lamina terminalis
A14.1.08.419.definition: a thin layer of gray matter in the telencephalon that extends backward from the corpus callosum above the optic chiasma and forms the median portion of the rostral wall of the third ventricle of the cerebrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.420.name: Column
A14.1.08.420.definition: a longitudinal subdivision of the spinal cord that resembles a column or pillar: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.421.name: Anterior commissure
A14.1.08.421.definition: a band of nerve fibers crossing from one side of the brain to the other just anterior to the third ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.511.name: Subcommissural organ
A14.1.08.511.definition: an aggregation of columnar cells situated between the posterior commissure and the third ventricle of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.623.name: Lateral nucleus
A14.1.08.623.definition: any of a group of nuclei of the thalamus situated in the dorsolateral region extending from its anterior to posterior ends (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.624.name: Medial nucleus
A14.1.08.624.definition: any of several small masses or layers of gray matter that are situated adjacent to the inferior olive and of which there are typically two on each side:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.625.name: Lateral nucleus
A14.1.08.625.definition: any of a group of nuclei of the thalamus situated in the dorsolateral region extending from its anterior to posterior ends (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.670.name: Lateral lemniscus
A14.1.08.670.definition: a band of nerve fibers that arises in the cochlear nuclei and terminates in the inferior colliculus and the lateral geniculate body of the opposite side of the brain (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.671.name: Mammillothalamic fasciculus
A14.1.08.671.definition: a bundle of nerve fibers that runs from the mammillary body to the anterior nucleus of the thalamus —called also mammillothalamic fasciculus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.672.name: Medial lemniscus
A14.1.08.672.definition: a band of nerve fibers that transmits proprioceptive impulses from the spinal cord to the thalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.673.name: Optic radiation
A14.1.08.673.definition: any of several neural radiations concerned with the visual function; especially : one made up of fibers from the pulvinar and the lateral geniculate body to the cuneus and other parts of the occipital lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.702.name: Subthalamic nucleus
A14.1.08.702.definition: an oval mass of gray matter that is located in the caudal part of the subthalamus along the medial part of the internal capsule, receives fibers from the lateral part of the globus pallidus, sends fibers through the internal capsule to the medial part of the globus pallidus, and when affected with lesions is associated with hemiballismus of the contralateral side of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.703.name: Nuclei of perizonal fields (H, H1, H2)

term_localized.en: Nuclei of perizonal fields (H, H1, H2)
term_localized.es: Núcleos del campo perizonal (H, H1, H2)

A14.1.08.707.name: Zona incerta
A14.1.08.707.definition: a flat thin layer of gray matter located in the dorsal part of the subthalamus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Núcleo dorsal del cuerpo geniculado lateral

A14.1.08.810.name: Dorsal nucleus
A14.1.08.810.definition: any of several small masses or layers of gray matter that are situated adjacent to the inferior olive and of which there are typically two on each side:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.909.name: Paraventricular nucleus
A14.1.08.909.definition: a discrete band of neurons in the anterior part of the hypothalamus that produce vasopressin and especially oxytocin and that innervate the neurohypophysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.911.name: Suprachiasmatic nucleus
A14.1.08.911.definition: either of a pair of neuron clusters in the hypothalamus situated directly above the optic chiasma that receive photic input from the retina via the optic nerve and that regulate the body's circadian rhythms —abbreviation SCN (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.912.name: Supra-optic nucleus
A14.1.08.912.definition: a small nucleus of closely packed neurons that overlies the optic chiasma and is intimately connected with the neurohypophysis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.921.name: Dorsal nucleus
A14.1.08.921.definition: any of several small masses or layers of gray matter that are situated adjacent to the inferior olive and of which there are typically two on each side:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.923.name: Arcuate nucleus
A14.1.08.923.definition: any of several cellular masses in the thalamus, hypothalamus, or medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Organo vascular de la lámina terminal

A14.1.08.949.name: Fornix
A14.1.08.949.definition: an anatomical arch or fold: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.954.name: Mammillothalamic fasciculus
A14.1.08.954.definition: a bundle of nerve fibers that runs from the mammillary body to the anterior nucleus of the thalamus —called also mammillothalamic fasciculus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.08.955.name: Medial forebrain bundle
A14.1.08.955.definition: a prominent tract of nerve fibers that connects the subcallosal area of the cerebral cortex with the lateral areas of the hypothalamus and that has fibers passing to the tuber cinereum, the brain stem, and the mammillary bodies (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.001.name: Telencephalon
A14.1.09.001.definition: the anterior subdivision of the embryonic forebrain or the corresponding part of the adult forebrain that includes the cerebral hemispheres and associated structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.002.name: Cerebral hemisphere
A14.1.09.002.definition: either of the two hollow convoluted lateral halves of the cerebrum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.003.name: Cerebral cortex
A14.1.09.003.definition: the convoluted surface layer of gray matter of the cerebrum that functions chiefly in coordination of sensory and motor information —called also pallium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.103.name: Central sulcus
A14.1.09.103.definition: the sulcus separating the frontal lobe of the cerebral cortex from the parietal lobe —called also fissure of Rolando, Rolandic fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.108.name: Parieto-occipital sulcus
A14.1.09.108.definition: a fissure near the posterior end of each cerebral hemisphere separating the parietal and occipital lobes —called also parieto-occipital fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.110.name: Frontal lobe
A14.1.09.110.definition: the anterior division of each cerebral hemisphere having its lower part in the anterior fossa of the skull and bordered behind by the central sulcus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.119.name: Precentral gyrus
A14.1.09.119.definition: the gyrus containing the motor area immediately anterior to the central sulcus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.123.name: Parietal lobe
A14.1.09.123.definition: the middle division of each cerebral hemisphere that is situated behind the central sulcus, above the sylvian fissure, and in front of the parieto-occipital sulcus and that contains an area concerned with bodily sensations (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.124.name: Angular gyrus
A14.1.09.124.definition: the cerebral gyrus of the posterior part of the external surface of the parietal lobe that arches over the posterior end of the sulcus between the superior and middle gyri of the temporal lobe —called also angular convolution (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.128.name: Postcentral gyrus
A14.1.09.128.definition: a gyrus of the parietal lobe located just posterior to the central sulcus, lying parallel to the precentral gyrus of the temporal lobe, and comprising the somatosensory cortex (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.131.name: Supramarginal gyrus
A14.1.09.131.definition: a gyrus of the inferior part of the parietal lobe that is continuous in front with the postcentral gyrus and posteriorly and inferiorly with the superior temporal gyrus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.132.name: Occipital lobe
A14.1.09.132.definition: the posterior lobe of each cerebral hemisphere that is separated medially from the parietal lobe by the parieto-occipital sulcus, is indistinctly separated more laterally from the temporal and parietal lobes, bears the visual areas, and has the form of a 3-sided pyramid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.134.name: Lunate sulcus
A14.1.09.134.definition: a sulcus of the cerebrum on the lateral part of the occipital lobe that marks the front boundary of the visual area (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.136.name: Temporal lobe
A14.1.09.136.definition: a large lobe of each cerebral hemisphere that is situated in front of the occipital lobe and contains a sensory area associated with the organ of hearing (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.149.name: Insula
A14.1.09.149.definition: the lobe in the center of the cerebral hemisphere that is situated deeply between the lips of the sylvian fissure —called also central lobe, island of Reil (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.201.name: Medial and inferior surfaces of cerebral hemisphere

term_localized.en: Medial and inferior surfaces of cerebral hemisphere
term_localized.la: Facies medialis et inferior hemispherii cerebri
term_localized.es: Caras medial e inferior del hemisferio cerebral

A14.1.09.206.name: Collateral sulcus
A14.1.09.206.definition: a sulcus of the tentorial surface of the cerebrum lying below and external to the calcarine sulcus and causing an elevation on the floor of the lateral ventricle between the hippocampi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.211.name: Subcallosal area
A14.1.09.211.definition: a small area of cortex in each cerebral hemisphere below the genu of the corpus callosum —called also parolfactory area (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.223.name: Precuneus
A14.1.09.223.definition: a somewhat rectangular convolution bounding the mesial aspect of the parietal lobe of the cerebrum and lying immediately in front of the cuneus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.224.name: Cuneus
A14.1.09.224.definition: a convolution of the mesial surface of the occipital lobe of the brain above the calcarine sulcus that forms a part of the visual area (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.225.name: Calcarine sulcus
A14.1.09.225.definition: a sulcus in the mesial surface of the occipital lobe of the cerebrum —called also calcarine fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.230.name: Limbic lobe
A14.1.09.230.definition: the marginal medial portion of the cortex of a cerebral hemisphere (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.231.name: Cingulate gyrus
A14.1.09.231.definition: a medial gyrus of each cerebral hemisphere that partly surrounds the corpus callosum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.234.name: Parahippocampal gyrus
A14.1.09.234.definition: a convolution on the inferior surface of the cerebral cortex of the temporal lobe that borders the hippocampus and contains elements of both the archipallium and neopallium —called also hippocampal convolution, hippocampal gyrus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.235.name: Uncus
A14.1.09.235.definition: a hooked anatomical part or process; specifically : the anterior curved end of the parahippocampal gyrus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.236.name: Hippocampal sulcus
A14.1.09.236.definition: a fissure of the mesial surface of each cerebral hemisphere extending from behind the posterior end of the corpus callosum forward and downward to the recurved part of the parahippocampal gyrus —called also hippocampal fissure (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.237.name: Dentate gyrus
A14.1.09.237.definition: a narrow strip of cortex associated with the hippocampal sulcus that continues forward to the uncus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.241.name: Corpus callosum
A14.1.09.241.definition: the great band of commissural fibers uniting the cerebral hemispheres (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.242.name: Rostrum
A14.1.09.242.definition: a bodily part or process suggesting a bird's bill: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.243.name: Genu
A14.1.09.243.definition: an abrupt flexure; especially : the bend in the anterior part of the corpus callosum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.244.name: Trunk
A14.1.09.244.definition: the human body apart from the head and appendages : torso  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.245.name: Splenium
A14.1.09.245.definition: the thick rounded fold that forms the posterior border of the corpus callosum and is continuous by its undersurface with the fornix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.246.name: Indusium griseum
A14.1.09.246.definition: a thin layer of gray matter over the dorsal surface of the corpus callosum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.252.name: Tapetum
A14.1.09.252.definition: any of various membranous layers or areas especially of the choroid and retina of the eye; specifically : tapetum lucidum  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.255.name: Fornix
A14.1.09.255.definition: an anatomical arch or fold: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.258.name: Body
A14.1.09.258.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.259.name: Crus
A14.1.09.259.definition: the lower or hind limb especially between the knee and the ankle or tarsus : shank  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.260.name: Commissure
A14.1.09.260.definition: a point or line of union or junction between two anatomical parts (as the lips at their angles or adjacent heart valves)  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.262.name: Septum pellucidum
A14.1.09.262.definition: the thin double partition extending vertically from the lower surface of the corpus callosum to the fornix and neighboring parts, separating the lateral ventricles of the brain, and enclosing the fifth ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.263.name: Cave
A14.1.09.263.definition: a space beneath the dura mater containing the trigeminal ganglion —called also Meckel's cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.264.name: Lamina
A14.1.09.264.definition: a thin plate or layer especially of an anatomical part: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.272.name: Lateral ventricle
A14.1.09.272.definition: an internal cavity in each cerebral hemisphere that consists of a central body and three cornua including an anterior one curving forward and outward, a posterior one curving backward, and an inferior one curving downward (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.275.name: Stria terminalis
A14.1.09.275.definition: a bundle of nerve fibers that passes from the amygdala along the demarcation between the thalamus and caudate nucleus mostly to the anterior part of the hypothalamus with a few fibers crossing the anterior commissure to the amygdala on the opposite side (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.279.name: Choroid plexus
A14.1.09.279.definition: a highly vascular portion of the pia mater that projects into the ventricles of the brain and secretes cerebrospinal fluid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.281.name: Atrium
A14.1.09.281.definition: an anatomical cavity or passage; especially : a chamber of the heart that receives blood from the veins and forces it into a ventricle or ventricles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.301.name: Cerebral cortex
A14.1.09.301.definition: the convoluted surface layer of gray matter of the cerebrum that functions chiefly in coordination of sensory and motor information —called also pallium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.303.name: Paleocortex
A14.1.09.303.definition: the part of the cerebral cortex that is evolutionarily older than the neocortex and that is composed especially of the olfactory cortex (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.304.name: Neocortex
A14.1.09.304.definition: the large 6-layered dorsal region of the cerebral cortex that is unique to mammals; broadly : the mammalian cerebral cortex (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Estría de la capa granular externa
Estría de la capa granular interna
Estría de la capa piramidal lntema

A14.1.09.321.name: Hippocampus
A14.1.09.321.definition: a curved elongated ridge that is an important part of the limbic system, extends over the floor of the descending horn of each lateral ventricle of the brain, consists of gray matter covered on the ventricular surface with white matter, and is involved in forming, storing, and processing memory (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.323.name: Pes
A14.1.09.323.definition: the distal segment of the hind limb of a vertebrate including the tarsus and foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.325.name: Presubiculum
A14.1.09.325.definition: a part of the parahippocampal gyrus lying between the subiculum and the main olfactory region (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.326.name: Subiculum
A14.1.09.326.definition: a part of the parahippocampal gyrus that is a ventral continuation of the hippocampus and is situated ventrally and medially to the dentate gyrus; also : a section of this that borders the hippocampal sulcus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.332.name: Fimbria
A14.1.09.332.definition: a bordering fringe especially at the entrance of the fallopian tubes  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.333.name: Alveus
A14.1.09.333.definition: a thin layer of medullary nerve fibers on the ventricular surface of the hippocampus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.339.name: Dentate gyrus
A14.1.09.339.definition: a narrow strip of cortex associated with the hippocampal sulcus that continues forward to the uncus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.341.name: Molecular layer
A14.1.09.341.definition: the outer layer of the cortex of the cerebellum and cerebrum consisting of a mass of unmyelinated fibers rich in synapses  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.342.name: Granular layer
A14.1.09.342.definition: the deeper layer of the cortex of the cerebellum containing numerous small closely packed cells (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Núcleo de la estría olfatoria lateral
Núcleo del lecho de la estría terminal

A14.1.09.421.name: Claustrum
A14.1.09.421.definition: the one of the four basal ganglia in each cerebral hemisphere that consists of a thin lamina of gray matter between the lentiform nucleus and the insula (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.429.name: Olfactory bulb
A14.1.09.429.definition: a bulbous anterior projection of the olfactory lobe that is the place of termination of the olfactory nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.431.name: Olfactory tract
A14.1.09.431.definition: a tract of nerve fibers in the olfactory lobe on the inferior surface of the frontal lobe of the brain that passes from the olfactory bulb to the olfactory trigone (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.432.name: Olfactory trigone
A14.1.09.432.definition: a triangular area of gray matter on each side of the brain forming the junction of an olfactory tract with a cerebral hemisphere near the optic chiasma (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.433.name: Olfactory tubercle
A14.1.09.433.definition: a small area of gray matter behind the olfactory trigone that is noted for being innervated by dopaminergic neurons from the ventral tegmental area (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.440.name: Nucleus accumbens
A14.1.09.440.definition: a nucleus forming the floor of the caudal part of the anterior prolongation of the lateral ventricle of the brain and receiving dopaminergic innervation from the ventral tegmental area as part of the mesolimbic pathway (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.502.name: Caudate nucleus
A14.1.09.502.definition: the one of the four basal ganglia in each cerebral hemisphere that comprises a mass of gray matter in the corpus striatum, forms part of the floor of the lateral ventricle, and is separated from the lentiform nucleus by the internal capsule —called also caudate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.503.name: Head
A14.1.09.503.definition: the division of the human body that contains the brain, the eyes, the ears, the nose, and the mouth; also : the corresponding anterior division of the body of various animals including all vertebrates, most arthropods, and many mollusks and worms  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.504.name: Body
A14.1.09.504.definition: the organized physical substance of an animal or plant either living or dead: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.505.name: Tail
A14.1.09.505.definition: the rear end or a process or prolongation of the rear end of the body of an animal  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.506.name: Lentiform nucleus
A14.1.09.506.definition: the one of the four basal ganglia in each cerebral hemisphere that comprises the larger and external nucleus of the corpus striatum including the outer reddish putamen and two inner pale yellow globular masses constituting the globus pallidus —called also lenticular nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.507.name: Putamen
A14.1.09.507.definition: an outer reddish layer of gray matter in the lentiform nucleus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.515.name: Corpus striatum
A14.1.09.515.definition: either of a pair of masses of nerve tissue which lie beneath and external to the anterior cornua of the lateral ventricles of the brain and form part of their floor and each of which contains a caudate nucleus and a lentiform nucleus separated by sheets of white matter to give the mass a striated appearance in section (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.542.name: Optic radiation
A14.1.09.542.definition: any of several neural radiations concerned with the visual function; especially : one made up of fibers from the pulvinar and the lateral geniculate body to the cuneus and other parts of the occipital lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.547.name: Optic radiation
A14.1.09.547.definition: any of several neural radiations concerned with the visual function; especially : one made up of fibers from the pulvinar and the lateral geniculate body to the cuneus and other parts of the occipital lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.550.name: Corona radiata
A14.1.09.550.definition: the zone of small follicular cells immediately surrounding the ovum in the graafian follicle and accompanying the ovum on its discharge from the follicle  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.555.name: Cingulum
A14.1.09.555.definition: a ridge about the base of the crown of a tooth  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.556.name: Inferior longitudinal fasciculus
A14.1.09.556.definition: a band of association fibers in each cerebral hemisphere that interconnects the occipital and temporal lobes and that passes near the lateral walls of the posterior and inferior horns of the lateral ventricle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.557.name: Superior longitudinal fasciculus
A14.1.09.557.definition: a large bundle of association fibers in the white matter of each cerebral hemisphere that extends above the insula from the frontal lobe to the occipital lobe where it curves downward and forward into the temporal lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.560.name: Uncinate fasciculus
A14.1.09.560.definition: a hook-shaped bundle of long association fibers connecting the frontal lobe with the anterior portion of the temporal lobe (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.1.09.571.name: Hippocampal commissure
A14.1.09.571.definition: a triangular band of nerve fibers joining the two crura of the fornix of the rhinencephalon anteriorly before they fuse to form the body of the fornix —called also lyra, psalterium (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)
