A14.2.00.001.name: Peripheral nervous system
A14.2.00.001.definition: the part of the nervous system that is outside the central nervous system and comprises the cranial nerves excepting the optic nerve, the spinal nerves, and the autonomic nervous system (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.002.name: Ganglion
A14.2.00.002.definition: a small cystic tumor (as on the back of the wrist) containing viscid fluid and connected either with a joint membrane or tendon sheath  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.006.name: Spinal ganglion

term_localized.es: Ganglio sensitivo de los nervios espinales

A14.2.00.006.definition: a ganglion on the dorsal root of each spinal nerve that is one of a series of ganglia containing cell bodies of sensory neurons —called also dorsal root ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Ganglio sensitivo de los nervios craneales

A14.2.00.013.name: Nerve
A14.2.00.013.definition: any of the filamentous bands of nervous tissue that connect parts of the nervous system with the other organs, conduct nerve impulses, and are made up of axons and dendrites together with protective and supportive structures and that for the larger nerves have the fibers gathered into funiculi surrounded by a perineurium and the funiculi enclosed in a common epineurium  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.014.name: Endoneurium
A14.2.00.014.definition: the delicate connective tissue network holding together the individual fibers of a nerve trunk (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.015.name: Perineurium
A14.2.00.015.definition: the sheath of connective tissue that surrounds a bundle of nerve fibers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.016.name: Epineurium
A14.2.00.016.definition: the external connective-tissue sheath of a nerve trunk (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.023.name: Mixed nerve
A14.2.00.023.definition: a nerve containing both sensory and motor fibers (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.027.name: Spinal nerve
A14.2.00.027.definition: any of the paired nerves which leave the spinal cord of a craniate vertebrate, supply muscles of the trunk and limbs, and connect with the nerves of the sympathetic nervous system, which arise by a short motor ventral root and a short sensory dorsal root, and of which there are 31 pairs in humans classified according to the part of the spinal cord from which they arise into 8 pairs of cervical nerves, 12 pairs of thoracic nerves, 5 pairs of lumbar nerves, 5 pairs of sacral nerves, and one pair of coccygeal nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.028.name: Rootlets
A14.2.00.028.definition: a small root; also : one of the ultimate divisions of a nerve root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.033.name: Ramus communicans
A14.2.00.033.definition: any of the bundles of nerve fibers connecting a sympathetic ganglion with a spinal nerve and being divided into two kinds:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.036.name: Cauda equina
A14.2.00.036.definition: the roots of the spinal nerves that extend beyond the termination of the spinal cord at the first lumbar vertebra in the form of a bundle of filaments within the spinal canal resembling a horse's tail (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.00.038.name: Cranial nerve
A14.2.00.038.definition: any of the 12 paired nerves that arise from the lower surface of the brain with one of each pair on each side and pass through openings in the skull to the periphery of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.001.name: Cranial nerves
A14.2.01.001.definition: any of the 12 paired nerves that arise from the lower surface of the brain with one of each pair on each side and pass through openings in the skull to the periphery of the body (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.003.name: Terminal ganglion
A14.2.01.003.definition: a usually parasympathetic ganglion situated on or close to an innervated organ and being the site where preganglionic nerve fibers terminate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.005.name: Olfactory nerves
A14.2.01.005.definition: either of the pair of nerves that are the first cranial nerves, that serve to conduct sensory stimuli from the olfactory organ to the brain, and that arise from the olfactory cells as discrete bundles of unmyelinated fibers passing in small groups (in humans, about 20) through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone and terminating in the olfactory bulb —called also first cranial nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.013.name: Sensory root
A14.2.01.013.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.014.name: Trigeminal ganglion
A14.2.01.014.definition: the large flattened sensory root ganglion of the trigeminal nerve that lies within the skull and behind the orbit —called also gasserian ganglion, semilunar ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.015.name: Motor root
A14.2.01.015.definition: a nerve root containing only motor fibers; specifically : ventral root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.016.name: Ophthalmic nerve
A14.2.01.016.definition: the one of the three major branches or divisions of the trigeminal nerve that supply sensory fibers to the lacrimal gland, eyelids, ciliary muscle, nose, forehead, and adjoining parts —called also ophthalmic, ophthalmic division (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.018.name: Lacrimal nerve
A14.2.01.018.definition: a small branch of the ophthalmic nerve that enters the lacrimal gland with the lacrimal artery and supplies the lacrimal gland and the adjacent conjunctiva and the skin of the upper eyelid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el nervio cigomático

A14.2.01.020.name: Frontal nerve
A14.2.01.020.definition: a branch of the ophthalmic nerve supplying the forehead, scalp, and adjoining parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.021.name: Supra-orbital nerve
A14.2.01.021.definition: a branch of the frontal nerve supplying the forehead, scalp, cranial periosteum, and adjacent parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.024.name: Supratrochlear nerve
A14.2.01.024.definition: a branch of the frontal nerve supplying the skin of the forehead and the upper eyelid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.025.name: Nasociliary nerve
A14.2.01.025.definition: a branch of the ophthalmic nerve distributed in part to the ciliary ganglion and in part to the mucous membrane and skin of the nose —called also nasal nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.026.name: Sensory root

term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el ganglio ciliar

A14.2.01.026.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.037.name: Maxillary nerve
A14.2.01.037.definition: the one of the three major branches or divisions of the trigeminal nerve that supplies sensory fibers to the skin areas of the middle part of the face, the upper jaw and its teeth, and the mucous membranes of the palate, nasal cavities, and nasopharynx —called also maxillary division, superior maxillary nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.039.name: Sensory root
A14.2.01.039.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.043.name: Nasopalatine nerve
A14.2.01.043.definition: a parasympathetic and sensory nerve that arises in the pterygopalatine ganglion, passes through the sphenopalatine foramen, across the roof of the nasal cavity to the nasal septum, and obliquely downward to and through the incisive canal, and innervates especially the glands and mucosa of the nasal septum and the anterior part of the hard palate (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.056.name: Zygomatic nerve
A14.2.01.056.definition: a branch of the maxillary nerve that divides into a facial branch supplying the skin of the prominent part of the cheek and a temporal branch supplying the skin of the anterior temporal region (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.059.name: Infra-orbital nerve
A14.2.01.059.definition: a branch of the maxillary nerve that divides into branches distributed to the skin of the upper part of the cheek, the upper lip, and the lower eyelid (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.064.name: Mandibular nerve
A14.2.01.064.definition: the one of the three major branches or divisions of the trigeminal nerve that supplies sensory fibers to the lower jaw, the floor of the mouth, the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, and the lower teeth and supplies motor fibers to the muscles of mastication —called also inferior maxillary nerve, mandibular (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.067.name: Sensory root

term_localized.es: Rr. ganglionares para el ganglio ótico

A14.2.01.067.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: N. del músculo tensor del velo del paladar
N. del músculo tensor del tímpano

A14.2.01.074.name: Auriculotemporal nerve
A14.2.01.074.definition: the branch of the mandibular nerve that supplies sensory fibers to the skin of the external ear and temporal region and autonomic fibers from the otic ganglion to the parotid gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Rr. de la membrana del tímpano
Rr. comunicantes con el nervio facial

A14.2.01.081.name: Lingual nerve
A14.2.01.081.definition: a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve supplying the anterior two thirds of the tongue and responding to stimuli of pressure, touch, and temperature (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Rr. para el istmo de las fauces
Rr. comunicantes con el nervio hipogloso

A14.2.01.084.name: Chorda tympani
A14.2.01.084.definition: a branch of the facial nerve that traverses the middle ear cavity and the infratemporal fossa and supplies autonomic fibers to the sublingual and submandibular glands and sensory fibers to the anterior part of the tongue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.087.name: Sensory root

term_localized.es: Rr. ganglionares para el ganglio submandibular

A14.2.01.087.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Rr. ganglionares para el ganglio sublingual

A14.2.01.089.name: Inferior alveolar nerve
A14.2.01.089.definition: a branch of the mandibular nerve that passes through the mandibular canal to the mental foramen giving off various branches along the way to the teeth of the lower jaw and finally to the skin of the chin and the skin and mucous membrane of the lower lip —called also inferior alveolar, inferior dental nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.094.name: Mental nerve
A14.2.01.094.definition: a branch of the inferior alveolar nerve that emerges from the bone of the mandible near the mental protuberance and divides into branches which are distributed to the skin of the chin and to the skin and mucous membranes of the lower lip (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.100.name: Geniculum
A14.2.01.100.definition: a small knee-shaped anatomical structure or abrupt bend (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el nervio glosofaríngeo

A14.2.01.116.name: Geniculate ganglion
A14.2.01.116.definition: a small reddish ganglion consisting of sensory and sympathetic nerve cells located at the sharp backward bend of the facial nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el plexo timpánico
R. comunicante con el nervio vago

A14.2.01.122.name: Vestibular nerve
A14.2.01.122.definition: a branch of the auditory nerve that consists of bipolar neurons with cell bodies collected in the vestibular ganglion, with peripheral processes passing to the semicircular canals, utricle, and saccule, and with central processes passing to the vestibular nuclei of the medulla oblongata (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.123.name: Vestibular ganglion
A14.2.01.123.definition: a sensory ganglion in the trunk of the vestibular nerve in the internal auditory canal that contains cell bodies supplying nerve fibers comprising the vestibular nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.133.name: Cochlear nerve
A14.2.01.133.definition: a branch of the auditory nerve that arises in the spiral ganglion of the cochlea and conducts sensory stimuli from the organ of hearing to the brain —called also cochlear, cochlear branch, cochlear division (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.136.name: Superior ganglion
A14.2.01.136.definition: the upper and smaller of the two sensory ganglia of the glossopharyngeal nerve that may be absent but when present is situated in a groove in which the nerve passes through the jugular foramen —called also jugular ganglion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.137.name: Inferior ganglion
A14.2.01.137.definition: the lower and larger of the two sensory ganglia of the glossopharyngeal nerve —called also petrosal ganglion, petrous ganglion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.138.name: Tympanic nerve
A14.2.01.138.definition: a branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve arising from the petrosal ganglion and entering the middle ear where it takes part in forming the tympanic plexus —called also Jacobson's nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.140.name: Tympanic plexus
A14.2.01.140.definition: a nerve plexus of the middle ear that is formed by the tympanic nerve and two or three filaments from the carotid plexus, sends fibers to the mucous membranes of the middle ear, the eustachian tube, and the mastoid cells, and gives off the lesser petrosal nerve to the otic ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.143.name: Communicating branch with auricular branch of vagus nerve

term_localized.en: Communicating branch with auricular branch of vagus nerve
term_localized.la: R. communicans cum ramo auriculare nervi vagi
term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el ramo auricular del nervio vago
R. comunicante con el ramo meníngeo
R. comunicante con el nervio auriculotemporal
R. comunicante con la cuerda del tímpano

A14.2.01.154.name: Superior ganglion
A14.2.01.154.definition: the upper and smaller of the two sensory ganglia of the glossopharyngeal nerve that may be absent but when present is situated in a groove in which the nerve passes through the jugular foramen —called also jugular ganglion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.157.name: Inferior ganglion
A14.2.01.157.definition: the lower and larger of the two sensory ganglia of the glossopharyngeal nerve —called also petrosal ganglion, petrous ganglion  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.159.name: Pharyngeal plexus
A14.2.01.159.definition: a plexus formed by branches of the glossopharyngeal, vagus, and sympathetic nerves supplying the muscles and mucous membrane of the pharynx and adjoining parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.160.name: Superior laryngeal nerve
A14.2.01.160.definition: laryngeal nerve —called also superior laryngeal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.163.name: Communicating branch with recurrent laryngeal nerve

term_localized.en: Communicating branch with recurrent laryngeal nerve
term_localized.la: R. communicans cum nervo laryngeo recurrente
term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el nervio laríngeo recurrente

A14.2.01.166.name: Recurrent laryngeal nerve
A14.2.01.166.definition: laryngeal nerve —called also recurrent laryngeal (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.01.172.name: Pulmonary plexus
A14.2.01.172.definition: either of two nerve plexuses associated with each lung that lie on the dorsal and ventral aspects of the bronchi of each lung and distribute fibers mainly from the vagus nerve to the lungs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: N. anterior de la curvatura menor
N. posterior de la curvatura menor

A14.2.02.001.name: Spinal nerves
A14.2.02.001.definition: any of the paired nerves which leave the spinal cord of a craniate vertebrate, supply muscles of the trunk and limbs, and connect with the nerves of the sympathetic nervous system, which arise by a short motor ventral root and a short sensory dorsal root, and of which there are 31 pairs in humans classified according to the part of the spinal cord from which they arise into 8 pairs of cervical nerves, 12 pairs of thoracic nerves, 5 pairs of lumbar nerves, 5 pairs of sacral nerves, and one pair of coccygeal nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.02.007.name: Suboccipital nerve
A14.2.02.007.definition: the first cervical nerve that supplies muscles around the suboccipital triangle including the rectus capitis posterior major, obliquus capitis superior, and obliquus capitis inferior and that sends branches to the rectus capitis posterior minor and semispinalis capitis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.02.012.name: Cervical plexus
A14.2.02.012.definition: a plexus formed by the anterior divisions of the four upper cervical nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.02.013.name: Ansa cervicalis
A14.2.02.013.definition: a nerve loop from the upper cervical nerves that accompanies the hypoglossal nerve and innervates the infrahyoid muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.02.028.name: Phrenic nerve
A14.2.02.028.definition: a general motor and sensory nerve on each side of the body that arises chiefly from the fourth cervical nerve, passes down through the thorax to the diaphragm, and supplies or gives off branches supplying especially the pericardium, pleura, and diaphragm —called also phrenic (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.001.name: Brachial plexus
A14.2.03.001.definition: a complex network of nerves that is formed chiefly by the lower four cervical nerves and the first thoracic nerve, lies partly within the axilla, and supplies nerves to the chest, shoulder, and arm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.002.name: Roots
A14.2.03.002.definition: the usually underground part of a seed plant body that functions as an organ of absorption, aeration, and food storage or as a means of anchorage and support and that differs from a stem especially in lacking nodes, buds, and leaves  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.003.name: Trunks
A14.2.03.003.definition: the human body apart from the head and appendages : torso  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.009.name: Cords
A14.2.03.009.definition: a long slender flexible material usually consisting of several strands (as of thread or yarn) woven or twisted together  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.014.name: Suprascapular nerve
A14.2.03.014.definition: a branch of the brachial plexus that supplies the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.016.name: Thoracodorsal nerve
A14.2.03.016.definition: a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus that supplies the latissimus dorsi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.021.name: Lateral cord
A14.2.03.021.definition: a cord of nerve tissue that is formed by union of the superior and middle trunks of the brachial plexus and that forms one of the two roots of the median nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.022.name: Medial cord
A14.2.03.022.definition: a cord of nerve tissue that is continuous with the anterior division of the inferior trunk of the brachial plexus and that is one of the two roots forming the median nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.023.name: Posterior cord
A14.2.03.023.definition: a cord of nerve tissue that is formed from the posterior divisions of the three trunks of the brachial plexus and that divides into the axillary and radial nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.024.name: Musculocutaneous nerve
A14.2.03.024.definition: a large branch of the brachial plexus supplying various parts of the upper arm (as flexor muscles) and forearm (as the skin)  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.031.name: Median nerve
A14.2.03.031.definition: a nerve that arises by two roots from the brachial plexus and passes down the middle of the front of the arm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: R. comunicante con el nervio cubital

A14.2.03.040.name: Ulnar nerve
A14.2.03.040.definition: a large superficial nerve of the arm that is a continuation of the medial cord of the brachial plexus, passes around the elbow superficially in a groove between the olecranon and the medial epicondyle of the humerus, and continues down the inner side of the forearm to supply the skin and muscles of the little-finger side of the forearm and hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.049.name: Radial nerve
A14.2.03.049.definition: a large nerve that arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus and passes spirally down the humerus to the front of the lateral epicondyle where it divides into a superficial branch distributed to the skin of the back of the hand and arm and a deep branch to the underlying extensor muscles —called also musculospiral nerve, nervus radialis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.051.name: Inferior lateral cutaneous nerve of arm

term_localized.en: Inferior lateral cutaneous nerve of arm
term_localized.es: N. cutáneo lateral inferior del brazo
R. comunicante con el nervio cubital

A14.2.03.059.name: Axillary nerve
A14.2.03.059.definition: a large nerve arising from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus and supplying the deltoid and teres minor muscles and the skin of the shoulder (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.03.061.name: Superior lateral cutaneous nerve of arm

term_localized.en: Superior lateral cutaneous nerve of arm
term_localized.es: N. cutáneo lateral superior del brazo

A14.2.04.005.name: Posterior cutaneous nerve
A14.2.04.005.definition: a branch of the radial nerve that arises on the medial side of the arm in the axilla and supplies the skin on the dorsal surface almost to the olecranon (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.04.006.name: Intercostal nerves
A14.2.04.006.definition: any of 11 nerves on each side of which each is an anterior division of a thoracic nerve lying between a pair of adjacent ribs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.04.012.name: Intercostobrachial nerves
A14.2.04.012.definition: a branch of the second intercostal nerve that crosses the axilla and supplies the skin of the inner and back part of the upper half of the arm (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.06.001.name: Sacral nerves and coccygeal nerve (S1-S5, Co)

term_localized.en: Sacral nerves and coccygeal nerve (S1-S5, Co)
term_localized.la: Nervi sacrales et nervus coccygeus (S1-S5, Co)

A14.2.07.001.name: Lumbosacral plexus
A14.2.07.001.definition: a network of nerves comprising the lumbar plexus and the sacral plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.002.name: Lumbar plexus
A14.2.07.002.definition: a plexus embedded in the psoas major and formed by the anterior or ventral divisions of the four upper lumbar nerves of which the first is usually supplemented by a communication from the twelfth thoracic nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.003.name: Iliohypogastric nerve
A14.2.07.003.definition: a branch of the first lumbar nerve that divides into branches distributed to the skin of the lateral part of the buttocks, the skin of the pubic region, and the muscles of the anterolateral abdominal wall (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.006.name: Ilio-inguinal nerve
A14.2.07.006.definition: a branch of the first lumbar nerve that is distributed to the muscles of the anterolateral wall of the abdomen, to the skin of the proximal and medial part of the thigh, and to the base of the penis and the scrotum in the male or the mons veneris and labia majora in the female (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.008.name: Genitofemoral nerve
A14.2.07.008.definition: a nerve that arises from the first and second lumbar nerves and is distributed by way of branches to the skin of the scrotum or the labia majora and to the upper anterior aspect of the thigh (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.012.name: Obturator nerve
A14.2.07.012.definition: a branch of the lumbar plexus that arises from the second, third, and fourth lumbar nerves and that supplies the hip and knee joints, the adductor muscles of the thigh, and the skin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.020.name: Femoral nerve
A14.2.07.020.definition: the largest branch of the lumbar plexus that in humans comes from the second, third, and fourth lumbar nerves and supplies extensor muscles of the thigh and skin areas on the front of the thigh and medial surface of the leg and foot and that sends articular branches to the hip and knee joints —called also anterior crural nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.023.name: Saphenous nerve
A14.2.07.023.definition: a nerve that is the largest and longest branch of the femoral nerve and supplies the skin over the medial side of the leg (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Rr. cutáneos mediales de la pierna

A14.2.07.026.name: Lumbosacral trunk
A14.2.07.026.definition: a nerve trunk that is formed by the fifth lumbar nerve and a smaller branch of the fourth lumbar nerve and that connects the lumbar plexus to the sacral plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.027.name: Sacral plexus
A14.2.07.027.definition: a nerve plexus that lies against the posterior and lateral walls of the pelvis, is formed by the union of the lumbosacral trunk and the first, second, and third sacral nerves, and continues into the thigh as the sciatic nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.037.name: Pudendal nerve
A14.2.07.037.definition: a nerve that arises from the second, third, and fourth sacral nerves and that supplies the external genitalia, the skin of the perineum, and the anal sphincters (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.043.name: Coccygeal nerve
A14.2.07.043.definition: either of the 31st or lowest pair of spinal nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.046.name: Sciatic nerve
A14.2.07.046.definition: either of the pair of largest nerves in the body that arise one on each side from the sacral plexus and that pass out of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen and down the back of the thigh to its lower third where division into the tibial and common peroneal nerves occurs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.058.name: Tibial nerve
A14.2.07.058.definition: the large nerve in the back of the leg that is a continuation of the sciatic nerve and terminates at the medial malleolus in the lateral and medial plantar nerves —called also medial popliteal nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.2.07.062.name: Sural nerve
A14.2.07.062.definition: any of several nerves in the region of the calf of the leg; especially : one formed by the union of a branch of the tibial nerve with a branch of the common peroneal nerve that supplies branches to the skin of the back of the leg and sends a continuation to the little toe by way of the lateral side of the foot (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.01.005.name: Rami communicantes
A14.3.01.005.definition: any of the bundles of nerve fibers connecting a sympathetic ganglion with a spinal nerve and being divided into two kinds:  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.01.017.name: Vertebral ganglion
A14.3.01.017.definition: any of a group of sympathetic ganglia which form two chains extending from the base of the skull to the coccyx along the sides of the spinal column (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.01.021.name: Ansa subclavia
A14.3.01.021.definition: a nerve loop that connects the middle and inferior cervical ganglia and passes around the subclavian artery (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.02.003.name: Ciliary ganglion
A14.3.02.003.definition: a small autonomic ganglion on the nasociliary branch of the ophthalmic nerve receiving preganglionic fibers from the oculomotor nerve and sending postganglionic fibers to the ciliary muscle and to the sphincter pupillae —called also lenticular ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.02.006.name: Pterygopalatine ganglion
A14.3.02.006.definition: an autonomic ganglion of the maxillary nerve that is situated in the pterygopalatine fossa and that receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the facial nerve and sends postganglionic fibers to the nasal mucosa, palate, pharynx, and orbit —called also Meckel's ganglion, sphenopalatine ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.02.009.name: Submandibular ganglion
A14.3.02.009.definition: an autonomic ganglion that is situated on the hyoglossus muscle above the deep part of the submandibular gland, receives preganglionic fibers from the facial nerve by way of the chorda tympani, and sends postganglionic fibers to the submandibular and sublingual glands —called also submaxillary ganglion (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.02.014.name: Otic ganglion
A14.3.02.014.definition: a small parasympathetic ganglion that is associated with the mandibular nerve, is located just below the foramen ovale of the sphenoid bone, receives preganglionic fibers from the glossopharyngeal nerve by way of the lesser petrosal nerve, and sends postganglionic fibers to the parotid gland by way of the auriculotemporal nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.02.020.name: Sensory root
A14.3.02.020.definition: a nerve root containing only sensory fibers; specifically : dorsal root (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.006.name: Cavernous plexus
A14.3.03.006.definition: a nerve plexus of the sympathetic nervous system that lies below and internal to the carotid artery at each side of the sella turcica (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.010.name: Vertebral plexus
A14.3.03.010.definition: a plexus of veins associated with the spinal column (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.013.name: Cardiac plexus
A14.3.03.013.definition: a nerve plexus of the autonomic nervous system supplying the heart and neighboring structures and situated near the heart and the arch and ascending part of the aorta (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.016.name: Pulmonary plexus
A14.3.03.016.definition: either of two nerve plexuses associated with each lung that lie on the dorsal and ventral aspects of the bronchi of each lung and distribute fibers mainly from the vagus nerve to the lungs (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.032.name: Renal plexus
A14.3.03.032.definition: a plexus of the autonomic nervous system that arises especially from the celiac plexus, surrounds the renal artery, and accompanies it into the kidney which it innervates (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.041.name: Myenteric plexus
A14.3.03.041.definition: a network of nerve fibers and ganglia between the longitudinal and circular muscle layers of the intestine —called also Auerbach's plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.047.name: Hypogastric nerve
A14.3.03.047.definition: a nerve or several parallel nerve bundles situated dorsal and medial to the common and the internal iliac arteries, crossing the branches of the internal iliac artery, and entering the inferior part of the hypogastric plexus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.055.name: Vesical plexus
A14.3.03.055.definition: a plexus of nerves that comprises preganglionic fibers derived chiefly from the hypogastric plexus and postganglionic neurons whose fibers are distributed to the bladder and adjacent parts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A14.3.03.056.name: Cavernous nerves of clitoris ♀-Cavernous nerves of penis ♂

term_localized.en: Cavernous nerves of clitoris ♀-Cavernous nerves of penis ♂

A15.0.00.000.name: Sense organs
A15.0.00.000.definition: a bodily structure that receives a stimulus (as heat or sound waves) and is affected in such a manner as to initiate a wave of excitation in associated sensory nerve fibers which convey specific impulses to the central nervous system where they are interpreted as corresponding sensations : receptor (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.1.00.001.name: Olfactory organ
A15.1.00.001.definition: an organ of chemical sense that receives stimuli interpreted as odors from volatile and soluble substances in low dilution, that lies in the walls of the upper part of the nasal cavity, and that forms a mucous membrane continuous with the rest of the lining of the nasal cavity and made up of tall columnar sustentacular cells containing golden brown pigment interspersed with olfactory cells the outer processes of which project between the sustentacular cells as small vesicles surmounted by delicate sensory filaments and the inner ends of which are continuous with fibers of the olfactory nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Porción olfactoria de la mucosa nasal

A15.2.01.001.name: Eyeball
A15.2.01.001.definition: the more or less globular capsule of the vertebrate eye formed by the sclera and cornea together with their contained structures (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.01.004.name: Equator
A15.2.01.004.definition: a circle or circular band dividing the surface of a body into two usually equal and symmetrical parts especially at the place of greatest width  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.01.005.name: Meridians
A15.2.01.005.definition: an imaginary circle or closed curve on the surface of a sphere or globe-shaped body (as the eyeball) that lies in a plane passing through the poles  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.02.002.name: Sclera
A15.2.02.002.definition: the dense fibrous opaque white outer coat enclosing the eyeball except the part covered by the cornea —called also sclerotic, sclerotic coat (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.02.009.name: Substantia propria
A15.2.02.009.definition: the layer of lamellated transparent fibrous connective tissue that makes up the bulk of the cornea of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.02.012.name: Cornea
A15.2.02.012.definition: the transparent part of the coat of the eyeball that covers the iris and pupil and admits light to the interior (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.02.020.name: Substantia propria
A15.2.02.020.definition: the layer of lamellated transparent fibrous connective tissue that makes up the bulk of the cornea of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.002.name: Choroid
A15.2.03.002.definition: a vascular membrane containing large branched pigment cells that lies between the retina and the sclera of the eye —called also choroid coat (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.007.name: Basal lamina
A15.2.03.007.definition: the part of the gray matter of the embryonic neural tube from which the motor nerve roots arise  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.009.name: Ciliary body
A15.2.03.009.definition: a vascular structure encircling the inner surface of the eye behind the iris that secretes the aqueous humor, contains the ciliary muscle and ciliary processes, and is comprised anteriorly of the pars plicata and posteriorly of the pars plana (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.011.name: Ciliary processes
A15.2.03.011.definition: any of the vascular folds on the inner surface of the ciliary body that produce the aqueous humor and between which pass the suspensory zonular fibers joining the ciliary muscle to the lens (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.014.name: Ciliary muscle
A15.2.03.014.definition: a circular band of smooth muscle fibers situated in the ciliary body and serving as the chief agent in accommodation when it contracts by drawing the ciliary processes centripetally and relaxing the suspensory ligament of the lens so that the lens is permitted to become more convex (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.019.name: Basal lamina
A15.2.03.019.definition: the part of the gray matter of the embryonic neural tube from which the motor nerve roots arise  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.020.name: Iris
A15.2.03.020.definition: the opaque muscular contractile diaphragm that is suspended in the aqueous humor in front of the lens of the eye, is perforated by the pupil and is continuous peripherally with the ciliary body, has a deeply pigmented posterior surface which excludes the entrance of light except through the pupil and a colored anterior surface which determines the color of the eyes  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.028.name: Pupil
A15.2.03.028.definition: the contractile usually round aperture in the iris of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.03.029.name: Sphincter pupillae
A15.2.03.029.definition: a broad flat band of smooth muscle in the iris that surrounds the pupil of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.002.name: Retina
A15.2.04.002.definition: the sensory membrane that lines most of the large posterior chamber of the vertebrate eye, is composed of several layers including one containing the rods and cones, and functions as the immediate instrument of vision by receiving the image formed by the lens and converting it into chemical and nervous signals which reach the brain by way of the optic nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.006.name: Ora serrata
A15.2.04.006.definition: the dentate border of the retina (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.010.name: Layer of inner and outer segments

term_localized.en: Layer of inner and outer segments
term_localized.es: Capa de los segmentos externos e internos

A15.2.04.021.name: Macula
A15.2.04.021.definition: a spot or blotch; especially : macule  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.023.name: Foveola
A15.2.04.023.definition: a small pit; specifically : one of the pits in the embryonic gastric mucosa from which the gastric glands develop (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.024.name: Optic nerve
A15.2.04.024.definition: either of the pair of sensory nerves that comprise the second pair of cranial nerves, arise from the ventral part of the diencephalon, form an optic chiasma before passing to the eye and spreading over the anterior surface of the retina, and conduct visual stimuli to the brain —called also second cranial nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.04.034.name: Subarachnoid space
A15.2.04.034.definition: the space between the arachnoid and the pia mater through which the cerebrospinal fluid circulates and across which extend delicate trabeculae of connective tissue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Arteriola temporal superior de la retina
Arteriola nasal superior de la retina
Arteriola nasal inferior de la retina
Vénula temporal superior de la retina
Vénula temporal inferior de la retina
Vénula nasal inferior de la retina

A15.2.05.001.name: Lens
A15.2.05.001.definition: a curved piece of glass or plastic used singly or combined in eyeglasses or an optical instrument (as a microscope) for forming an image by focusing rays of light  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.05.012.name: Axis
A15.2.05.012.definition: a straight line about which a body or a geometric figure rotates or may be thought of as rotating  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.05.013.name: Equator
A15.2.05.013.definition: a circle or circular band dividing the surface of a body into two usually equal and symmetrical parts especially at the place of greatest width  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.05.014.name: Radii
A15.2.05.014.definition: the bone on the thumb side of the human forearm or on the corresponding part of the forelimb of vertebrates above fishes that in humans is movably articulated with the ulna at both ends so as to permit partial rotation about that bone, that bears on its inner aspect somewhat distal to the head a prominence for the insertion of the biceps tendon, and that has the lower end broadened for articulation with the proximal bones of the carpus so that rotation of the radius involves also that of the hand (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.06.002.name: Aqueous humor
A15.2.06.002.definition: a transparent fluid occupying the space between the crystalline lens and the cornea of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.06.003.name: Anterior chamber
A15.2.06.003.definition: a space in the eye bounded in front by the cornea and in back by the iris and middle part of the lens (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.06.005.name: Posterior chamber
A15.2.06.005.definition: a narrow space in the eye that is behind the peripheral part of the iris and in front of the suspensory ligament of the lens and the ciliary processes and is filled with aqueous humor (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.06.008.name: Vitreous body
A15.2.06.008.definition: the clear colorless transparent jelly that fills the eyeball posterior to the lens, is enclosed by a delicate hyaloid membrane, and in the adult is nearly homogeneous but in the fetus is pervaded by fibers with minute nuclei at their points of junction (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.014.name: Check ligament of lateral rectus muscle

term_localized.en: Check ligament of lateral rectus muscle

A15.2.07.017.name: Trochlea
A15.2.07.017.definition: an anatomical structure resembling a pulley: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.020.name: Levator palpebrae superioris
A15.2.07.020.definition: a thin flat extrinsic muscle of the eye arising from the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone, passing forward and downward over the superior rectus, and inserting into the tarsal plate of the skin of the upper eyelid which it raises (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.023.name: Eyebrow
A15.2.07.023.definition: the ridge over the eye or hair growing on it —called also brow (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.024.name: Eyelids
A15.2.07.024.definition: either of the movable lids of skin and muscle that can be closed over the eyeball —called also palpebra (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.030.name: Palpebral fissure
A15.2.07.030.definition: the space between the margins of the eyelids —called also rima palpebrarum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.034.name: Medial angle of eye
A15.2.07.034.definition: the angle formed by the eyelids near the nose (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.037.name: Eyelashes
A15.2.07.037.definition: the fringe of hair edging the eyelid —usually used in plural  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.044.name: Sebaceous glands
A15.2.07.044.definition: any of the small sacculated glands lodged in the substance of the derma, usually opening into the hair follicles, and secreting an oily or greasy material composed in great part of fat which softens and lubricates the hair and skin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.047.name: Conjunctiva
A15.2.07.047.definition: the mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelids and is continued over the forepart of the eyeball (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.048.name: Plica semilunaris
A15.2.07.048.definition: the vertical fold of conjunctiva that occupies the canthus of the eye nearer the nose and is homologous to the nictitating membrane of lower animals (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.049.name: Lacrimal caruncle
A15.2.07.049.definition: a small reddish follicular elevation at the medial angle of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.056.name: Lacrimal apparatus
A15.2.07.056.definition: the bodily parts which function in the production of tears including the lacrimal glands, lacrimal ducts, lacrimal sacs, nasolacrimal ducts, and lacrimal puncta (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.057.name: Lacrimal gland
A15.2.07.057.definition: an acinous gland that is about the size and shape of an almond, secretes tears, and is situated laterally and superiorly to the bulb of the eye in a shallow depression on the inner surface of the frontal bone —called also tear gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.065.name: Lacrimal punctum
A15.2.07.065.definition: the opening of either the upper or the lower lacrimal duct at the inner canthus of the eye (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.068.name: Lacrimal sac
A15.2.07.068.definition: the dilated oval upper end of the nasolacrimal duct that is situated in a groove formed by the lacrimal bone and the frontal process of the maxilla, is closed at its upper end, and receives the lacrimal ducts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.2.07.070.name: Nasolacrimal duct
A15.2.07.070.definition: a duct that transmits tears from the lacrimal sac to the inferior meatus of the nose —called also nasal duct (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.00.001.name: Ear
A15.3.00.001.definition: the characteristic vertebrate organ of hearing and equilibrium consisting in the typical mammal of a sound-collecting outer ear separated by the tympanic membrane from a sound-transmitting middle ear that in turn is separated from a sensory inner ear by membranous fenestrae  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.001.name: External ear
A15.3.01.001.definition: the parts of the ear that are external to the eardrum; also : pinna (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.005.name: Helix
A15.3.01.005.definition: the incurved rim of the external ear  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.009.name: Antihelix
A15.3.01.009.definition: the curved elevation of cartilage within or in front of the helix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.010.name: Triangular fossa
A15.3.01.010.definition: a shallow depression in the anterior part of the top of the ear's auricle between the two crura into which the antihelix divides (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.012.name: Scapha
A15.3.01.012.definition: an elongated depression of the ear that separates the helix and antihelix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.016.name: Antitragus
A15.3.01.016.definition: a prominence on the lower posterior portion of the concha of the external ear opposite the tragus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.017.name: Tragus
A15.3.01.017.definition: a small projection in front of the external opening of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Surco de la raíz del hélix

A15.3.01.042.name: Antitragicus
A15.3.01.042.definition: a small muscle arising from the outer part of the antitragus and inserted into the antihelix (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.045.name: External acoustic meatus
A15.3.01.045.definition: the auditory canal leading from the opening of the external ear to the eardrum —called also external acoustic meatus, external auditory meatus (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.01.050.name: Notch in cartilage of acoustic meatus

term_localized.en: Notch in cartilage of acoustic meatus
term_localized.es: Incisura del cartílago del conducto auditivo

A15.3.01.052.name: Tympanic membrane
A15.3.01.052.definition: a thin membrane separating the middle ear from the inner part of the external auditory canal that vibrates in response to sound energy and transmits the resulting mechanical vibrations to the structures of the middle ear —called also eardrum, tympanum (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.001.name: Middle ear
A15.3.02.001.definition: the intermediate portion of the ear of higher vertebrates consisting typically of a small air-filled membrane-lined chamber in the temporal bone continuous with the nasopharynx through the eustachian tube, separated from the external ear by the tympanic membrane and from the inner ear by fenestrae, and containing a chain of three ossicles that extends from the tympanic membrane to the oval window and transmits vibrations to the inner ear —called also tympanic cavity (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.009.name: Oval window
A15.3.02.009.definition: an oval opening between the middle ear and the vestibule having the base of the stapes or columella attached to its membrane —called also fenestra ovalis, fenestra vestibuli (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.015.name: Round window
A15.3.02.015.definition: a round opening between the middle ear and the cochlea that is closed over by a membrane —called also fenestra cochleae, fenestra rotunda (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.019.name: Secondary tympanic membrane
A15.3.02.019.definition: a membrane closing the round window and separating the scala tympani from the middle ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.027.name: Tympanic aperture of canaliculus for chorda tympani

term_localized.en: Tympanic aperture of canaliculus for chorda tympani
term_localized.es: Abertura timpánica del conductillo de la cuerda del timpano

A15.3.02.029.name: Mastoid cells
A15.3.02.029.definition: one of the small cavities in the mastoid process that develop after birth and are filled with air —called also mastoid air cell (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.033.name: Stapes
A15.3.02.033.definition: the innermost of the chain of three ossicles in the middle ear of a mammal having the form of a stirrup, a base occupying the oval window, and a head connected with the incus —called also stirrup (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.038.name: Incus
A15.3.02.038.definition: the middle bone of the chain of three ossicles in the middle ear of a mammal resembling a premolar tooth with the body having a facet which articulates with the malleus and with the longer of the two widely separated crura having a process which articulates with the stapes —called also ambos, anvil (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.041.name: Lenticular process
A15.3.02.041.definition: the tip of the long process of the incus which articulates with the stapes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.043.name: Malleus
A15.3.02.043.definition: the outermost of the chain of three ossicles in the middle ear of a mammal consisting of a head, neck, short process, long process, and handle with the short process and handle being fastened to the tympanic membrane and the head articulating with the head of the incus —called also hammer (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Articulaciones de los huesecillos del oído
Ligamentos de los huesecillos del oído

A15.3.02.061.name: Tensor tympani
A15.3.02.061.definition: a small muscle of the middle ear that is located in the bony canal just above the bony part of the eustachian tube, that arises from the canal containing it, from the cartilaginous portion of the eustachian tube, and from the adjacent greater wing of the sphenoid bone, that is inserted by a long tendon into the manubrium of the malleus near its base, and that serves to adjust the tension of the tympanic membrane —called also tensor tympani muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.062.name: Stapedius
A15.3.02.062.definition: a small muscle of the middle ear that arises from the wall of the tympanum, is inserted into the neck of the stapes by a tendon that sometimes contains a slender spine of bone, and serves to check and dampen vibration of the stapes —called also stapedius muscle (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Pliegue de la cuerda del tímpano

A15.3.02.076.name: Isthmus
A15.3.02.076.definition: a contracted anatomical part or passage connecting two larger structures or cavities: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.02.083.name: Mucosa
A15.3.02.083.definition: a membrane rich in mucous glands that lines body passages and cavities (as of the digestive, respiratory, and genitourinary tracts) which connect directly or indirectly with the exterior : mucous membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Orificio faríngeo de la trompa auditiva

A15.3.03.003.name: Bony labyrinth
A15.3.03.003.definition: the cavity in the petrous portion of the temporal bone that contains the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear and is divided into the vestibule, cochlea, and semicircular canals —called also osseous labyrinth (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.004.name: Vestibule
A15.3.03.004.definition: any of various bodily cavities especially when serving as or resembling an entrance to some other cavity or space: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.015.name: Semicircular canals
A15.3.03.015.definition: any of the loop-shaped tubular parts of the labyrinth of the ear that together constitute a sensory organ associated with the maintenance of bodily equilibrium, that consist of an inner membranous canal of the membranous labyrinth and a corresponding outer bony canal of the bony labyrinth, and that in all vertebrates above cyclostomes form a group of three in each ear usually in planes nearly at right angles to each other (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.025.name: Cochlea
A15.3.03.025.definition: a division of the bony labyrinth of the inner ear coiled into the form of a snail shell and consisting of a spiral canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone in which lies a smaller membranous spiral passage that communicates with the saccule at the base of the spiral, ends blindly near its apex, and contains the organ of Corti (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.038.name: Modiolus
A15.3.03.038.definition: a central bony column in the cochlea of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.043.name: Scala vestibuli
A15.3.03.043.definition: the lymph-filled spirally arranged canal in the bony canal of the cochlea that is separated from the cochlear duct below by the vestibular membrane, is connected with the oval window, and receives vibrations from the stapes (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.044.name: Helicotrema
A15.3.03.044.definition: the minute opening by which the scala tympani and scala vestibuli communicate at the top of the cochlea of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.045.name: Scala tympani
A15.3.03.045.definition: the lymph-filled spirally arranged canal in the bony canal of the cochlea that is separated from the cochlear duct by the basilar membrane, communicates at its upper end with the scala vestibuli, and abuts at its lower end upon the membrane that separates the round window from the middle ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.056.name: Perilymph
A15.3.03.056.definition: the fluid between the membranous and bony labyrinths of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.059.name: Membranous labyrinth
A15.3.03.059.definition: the system of membrane-lined interconnected sacs and passages that is suspended within the bony labyrinth of the inner ear, is filled with endolymph and surrounded by perilymph, and includes the cochlear duct, utricle, saccule, and semicircular ducts (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.061.name: Endolymph
A15.3.03.061.definition: the watery fluid in the membranous labyrinth of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.063.name: Utricle
A15.3.03.063.definition: a small anatomical pouch: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.065.name: Saccule
A15.3.03.065.definition: a little sac; specifically : the smaller chamber of the membranous labyrinth of the ear that contains the macula sacculi (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.076.name: Utriculosaccular duct
A15.3.03.076.definition: a narrow tube connecting the utricle to the saccule in the membranous labyrinth of the ear (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.081.name: Ductus reuniens
A15.3.03.081.definition: a passage in the ear that connects the cochlea and the saccule (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.082.name: Maculae
A15.3.03.082.definition: a spot or blotch; especially : macule  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.086.name: Otolith
A15.3.03.086.definition: a calcareous concretion in the inner ear of a vertebrate or in the otocyst of an invertebrate that is especially conspicuous in many bony fishes where it forms a hard body and in most of the higher vertebrates where it is represented by a mass of small calcareous otoconia —called also statolith (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.093.name: Cochlear duct
A15.3.03.093.definition: the spirally arranged canal in the bony canal of the cochlea that contains the organ of Corti, is triangular in cross section, and is bounded by the vestibular membrane above, by the periosteum-lined wall of the cochlea laterally, and by the basilar membrane below —called also ductus cochlearis, scala media (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.096.name: Stria vascularis
A15.3.03.096.definition: the upper part of the spiral ligament of the cochlear duct that contains numerous small blood vessels (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.099.name: Spiral ligament
A15.3.03.099.definition: the thick periosteum that forms the outer wall of the cochlear duct and that gives attachment to the outer edge of the basilar membrane (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.102.name: Basal lamina
A15.3.03.102.definition: the part of the gray matter of the embryonic neural tube from which the motor nerve roots arise  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.108.name: Tectorial membrane
A15.3.03.108.definition: a membrane having the consistency of jelly that covers the surface of the organ of Corti (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

term_localized.es: Fondo de saco de la cúpula

A15.3.03.125.name: Spiral ganglion
A15.3.03.125.definition: a mass of bipolar cell bodies occurring in the modiolus of the organ of Corti and giving off axons which comprise the cochlear nerve (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.3.03.131.name: Cochlear branch
A15.3.03.131.definition: a branch of the auditory nerve that arises in the spiral ganglion of the cochlea and conducts sensory stimuli from the organ of hearing to the brain —called also cochlear, cochlear branch, cochlear division (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A15.4.00.002.name: Taste bud
A15.4.00.002.definition: an end organ that mediates the sensation of taste, lies chiefly in the epithelium of the tongue and especially in the walls of the circumvallate papillae, and consists of a conical or flask-shaped mass made up partly of supporting cells and partly of neuroepithelial sensory cells terminating peripherally in short hairlike processes which project into the pore in the overlying epithelium and by which communication with the mouth cavity is effected (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.002.name: Skin
A16.0.00.002.definition: the 2-layered covering of the body consisting of an outer ectodermal epidermis that is more or less cornified and penetrated by the openings of sweat and sebaceous glands and an inner mesodermal dermis that is composed largely of connective tissue and is richly supplied with blood vessels and nerves (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.009.name: Epidermis
A16.0.00.009.definition: the outer epithelial layer of the external integument of the animal body that is derived from the embryonic epiblast; specifically : the outer nonsensitive and nonvascular layer of the skin of a vertebrate that overlies the dermis  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.010.name: Dermis
A16.0.00.010.definition: the vascular, thick layer of the skin lying below the epidermis and above the superficial fascia that contains fibroblasts, macrophages, mast cells, B cells, and sensory nerve endings and has an extracellular matrix composed of proteoglycans and glycoproteins embedded with collagen and elastin fibers —called also corium, cutis, cutis vera, derma (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.011.name: Papillary layer
A16.0.00.011.definition: the superficial layer of the dermis raised into papillae that fit into corresponding depressions on the inner surface of the epidermis (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.012.name: Papillae
A16.0.00.012.definition: a small projecting body part similar to a nipple in form: as  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.013.name: Reticular layer
A16.0.00.013.definition: the deeper layer of the dermis formed of interlacing fasciculi of white fibrous tissue (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.014.name: Hairs
A16.0.00.014.definition: a slender threadlike outgrowth of the epidermis of an animal; especially : one of the usually pigmented filaments that form the characteristic coat of a mammal  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.017.name: Eyebrows
A16.0.00.017.definition: the ridge over the eye or hair growing on it —called also brow (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.018.name: Beard
A16.0.00.018.definition: the hair that grows on a man's face often excluding the mustache (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.023.name: Hair follicle
A16.0.00.023.definition: the tubular epithelial sheath that surrounds the lower part of the hair shaft and encloses at the bottom a vascular papilla supplying the growing basal part of the hair with nourishment (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.029.name: Sweat gland
A16.0.00.029.definition: a simple tubular gland of the skin that secretes perspiration, in humans is widely distributed in nearly all parts of the skin, and consists typically of an epithelial tube extending spirally from a minute pore on the surface of the skin into the dermis or subcutaneous tissues where it ends in a convoluted tuft —called also sudoriferous gland, sudoriparous gland (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.00.030.name: Sebaceous gland
A16.0.00.030.definition: any of the small sacculated glands lodged in the substance of the derma, usually opening into the hair follicles, and secreting an oily or greasy material composed in great part of fat which softens and lubricates the hair and skin (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.01.001.name: Nail
A16.0.01.001.definition: a horny sheath of thickened and condensed epithelial stratum lucidum that grows out from a vascular matrix of dermis and protects the upper surface of the end of each finger and toe of humans and most other primates and that is strictly homologous with the hoof or claw of other mammals from which it differs chiefly in shape and size —called also nail plate  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.01.009.name: Perionyx
A16.0.01.009.definition: the persistent layer of stratum corneum at the base of a fingernail or toenail (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.01.010.name: Eponychium
A16.0.01.010.definition: the thickened layer of epidermal tissue over the developing fetal fingernail or toenail that disappears before birth except over the base of the nail  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.01.011.name: Hyponychium
A16.0.01.011.definition: the thickened layer of epidermis beneath the free end of a nail  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.001.name: Breast
A16.0.02.001.definition: either of the pair of mammary glands extending from the front of the chest in pubescent and adult females of humans and some other mammals; also : either of the analogous but rudimentary organs of the male chest especially when enlarged  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.004.name: Nipple
A16.0.02.004.definition: the protuberance of a mammary gland upon which in the female the lactiferous ducts open and from which milk is drawn  (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.006.name: Mammary gland
A16.0.02.006.definition: any of the large compound sebaceous glands that in female mammals are modified to secrete milk, are situated ventrally in pairs, and usually terminate in a nipple (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.010.name: Lactiferous duct
A16.0.02.010.definition: any of the milk-carrying ducts of the mammary gland that open on the nipple (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.011.name: Lactiferous sinus
A16.0.02.011.definition: an expansion in a lactiferous duct at the base of the nipple in which milk accumulates (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)

A16.0.02.012.name: Areola
A16.0.02.012.definition: the colored ring around the nipple (Merriam-Webster Dictionary)
